[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Welcome back!  PART 2  When I signed in for the 1.e4 Lifetime Repertoire, I was assuming that Part 1 shouldn’t take more than 2 months of work. I had no such illusions before Part 2. :-@@EndBracket@@ Preparing the lines took many months, which explains the big gap between the two parts. I hope that the quality of Part 2 will reward you for having to wait for so long. Part 2 is significantly bigger as it covers more topical openings than Part 1.  Those of you who have already gone through Part 1 know that I don’t really do shortcuts and I try to choose the most challenging lines as they are simply more rewarding in the long run. Part 2 covers three great openings: the Sicilian Defense, the French Defense, and the Caro-Kann Defense. I also dealt with the smaller ones: Scandinavian, Alekhine, Owen, Nimzowitsch, and St. George Defense.   ABOUT ME  I have been playing chess for thirty years, I have a grandmaster title, I was a Polish Champion, I discovered a new line in the Ruy Lopez, and I had the honor of helping the five-time World Champion, Viswanathan Anand, for more than seven years.   MY APPROACH TO OPENINGS  There are many approaches when it comes to openings. Some players fight for advantage, while others look for positions that suit their style. Some look for sharp lines while others may prefer quiet ones. In the course, I was trying to implement my own approach. I would like to explain its key points:  
Flexibility  Sometimes the position calls for aggressive means, and sometimes it is best to play quietly. I believe that having too strong preferences means having weaknesses and that we should try to be flexible and accept that chess is a rich game with a huge variety of positions. Such an approach is great for our development as it forces us to leave our comfort zone. It also helps in achieving my next point.   Challenge  No matter which way we decide to go, there always has to be one. I believe that applying pressure on our opponents straight from the openings is the best way to achieve a satisfying position. It doesn’t have to mean playing sharp, although it often does. If we are able to put pressure on our opponents from the very beginning, they will be more likely to crack at some point.   Practical approach  Does it make sense to memorize a long and extremely complicated line if we don’t really expect it and there is a good and simple alternative? Does it make sense to enter the line that we know our opponent wants us to enter?   During my career as a player and coach, I have made many opening choices − both good and bad. I have gained a lot of experience, and in this course, I will share this experience with you.   My opening choices are not exclusively based on the objective evaluations of the positions but also on their practical value.   Thinking long-term  There are all kinds of small, interesting lines that give us decent chances of catching our opponents off guard. However, these lines don’t necessarily help us improve our skills, and long-term, this is the most important thing. I like positions that are strategically complex, I like the effort of learning and understanding them, and I hope that you will enjoy this part as well − this is the most rewarding part of our work on openings.  I would like to thank you for purchasing my course, and I hope that you will like it. I am looking forward to hearing your feedback. Enjoy!  Grzegorz Gajewski }
