[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide − Sicilian"]
[Black "Dragon 9.O-O-O d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ The Dragon Variation is one of the most colorful lines in chess, even by Sicilian standards. It involves so many important tactical motifs that one simply has to study it if taking chess seriously. Exchange sacrifices on c3, vigorous Pawn attacks, unexpected strikes in the center − it's all there.  If I am not mistaken, it was Mikhail Botvinnik who once said that every chess player has to play at least thirty games in the Dragon. Today, these classical motifs are somewhat detached from the theory. With precise play, White simply doesn't allow Black to execute them, taking most of the fun away. That is exactly what we are about to do. }
6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O
{ Why not  9.Bc4?  The answer is simple: this is what Black is hoping for. The amount of theory is overwhelming and the final verdict is not as good as one would expect. This makes it rather difficult for White from a practical point of view. Our choice is simple and very unpleasant for Black. No wonder it has been the most popular continuation on the top level for quite some time already. }
9... d5
{ The critical continuation which makes sense − by skipping Bf1-c4, White saved time but also allowed ...d6-d5. }
10. exd5
{ For a long time  10.Qe1  was considered the main continuation. However, currently Black seems to be doing okay in that line, so the attention has moved to our choice. }
10... Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bd4
{ White's approach is very simple: we want to neutralize Black's activity and then our superior Pawn structure will tell. Also, Black is going to experience some real problems with finding a place for the light-squared Bishop. }
12... e5 { The most popular move, but, in my opinion, not the best one. } 13.
Bc5
{ What we have is an improved version of the @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2n2np1/3p4/3NP3/2N1BP2/PPPQ2PP/2KR1B1R w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Qe1  line.  With the Queen on d2, White doesn't need to worry about ...Bg7-h6+ or ...Qd8-g5+, which limits Black's options for the next moves. }
13... Re8 14. Ne4 Qc7
{ This specific move order allows us to reach a very pleasant endgame.  14...Be6  transposes to the 13...Be6 line. }
15. h4 f5 { The critical response. We should now take the endgame. } 16. Nd6
Rd8 17. Nxc8 Raxc8
{ Black is ready to meet  18.Bc4  with  18...h5!  , so we should act quickly. }
18. h5 { White's attack is dangerous enough to force Black's reply. } 18... Nb6
{ Now massive simplifications are quite likely. } 19. Bxb6 axb6
{ Nobody has tried it so far, but I think it is not impossible to recapture with the Pawn. }
20. Bc4+ Kf8 21. Qb4+ c5 { Not nice, but Black didn't really have a choice. }
22. Qa4 { 22.Qb3  can be also tried. } 22... Rxd1+ 23. Rxd1 Rd8
{ In view of Rd1-d7, it feels like this has to be played. However, it turns out to be a losing mistake!   Instead, Black should use the weakness of our back rank, to consolidate the pieces:  23...Bf6!  Now  24.Rd7?  goes nowhere as Black has  24...Bg5+  25.Kb1  Rd8!  However, the natural @@StartFEN@@2r2k2/2q4p/1p3bp1/2p1pp1P/Q1B5/5P2/PPP3P1/2KR4 w - - 1 24@@EndFEN@@  24.a3  is a good reply, making luft for the King. The full variation is given in the dedicated chapter. }
24. Rxd8+ Qxd8 25. c3
{ The most accurate, although  25.a3  is also possible. Black can't stop the invasion of White's  Queen as the c6, d7, a7, and a8-squares can't be covered simultaneously.  The opposite-colored Bishop endgame arising after @@StartFEN@@3q1k2/6bp/1p4p1/2p1pp1P/Q1B5/2P2P2/PP4P1/2K5 b - - 0 25@@EndFEN@@  25...Bh6+  26.Kc2  Qd2+  27.Kb3  Qd1+  28.Ka3  Qxa4+  29.Kxa4  is completely winning for White as our King is too active. }
