[White "Quickstarter Guide − Sicilian"]
[Black "Keres Attack 6.g4 h6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen Variation is a great system, but mostly for educational reasons. One should simply study the structure and play some games with it. However, at least in this move order, it is not really playable. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is by far the most dangerous weapon against the Scheveningen and the main reason for Black to stay away from the whole system. Since Black has not put any pressure on the center yet, White can afford to push the Pawn aggressively.  If you compare it with the 6.h3 Najdorf, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  a6  6.h3  e6  7.g4  ,  White saved a tempo by skipping h2-h3 completely. What's more important in the opening than a tempo? }
6... h6 { The best response − Black slows down our attack. } 7. Rg1 Nc6
{ There is a lot of theory after  8.h4  d5!  White is slightly better in the end, but most of the pressure is gone. }
8. Be3
{ The setup I want to suggest is not only strong but also avoids the ...d6-d5 lines. }
8... Be7
{ 8...d5?  9.Bb5  is dangerous for Black as can be seen in the corresponding chapter. }
9. Qe2 { From e2 the Queen protects the Pawn on g4. } 9... Nxd4 10. Bxd4 e5 11.
Be3 Be6 { A typical move and I also don't see any alternatives. } 12. O-O-O Nd7
13. Qb5
{ A novelty and one more reason to praise our ninth move. The Queen is attacking the b7-Pawn, but what we really want is to bring the Bishop to c4. }
13... Qc8
{ The black Queen is preventing Bf1-c4 and is also staying away from the c7-square since a white Knight could land on d5. }
14. Kb1 a6 15. Qd3
{ White is better. We want to go Nc3-d5 and f2-f4. Black still can not castle because of g4-g5. }
