[Black "Rossolimo 3.Bb5 d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Perhaps I should start with some explanations on why would we choose Bb5 against ...Nc6. Surely, you will find many repertoires that involve a Bb5 setup, for instance, in the Sicilian with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.Bb5+  or, as is the case here, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  3.Bb5  . You will also find a lot of repertoires where the attention shifts to  3.d4  instead.  I wanted to be as flexible as possible and my goal was to suggest the most challenging solution. The sad truth is that the Sveshnikov Variation is not posing Black serious problems at the moment, which shouldn't come as a surprise, as there aren't many topical games in this opening anymore. On the few occasions when White does go for the Sveshnikov, we will witness some boring draw, unless Black simply forgets the line. Besides the fact that White ran out of ideas, modern engines revealed that Black is okay in more than one way.  The Rossolimo though still has some poison in it, and this is also the trend at top-level chess. There are many games played by very strong GMs and it would be a shame to not include it in your repertoire based on the mere fact that you might go for 3.d4 in different lines.  We do have quite some work ahead though as we have to go through many lines, but I believe it is worth the effort and I am sure you will enjoy playing the Rossolimo with White. }
3... d6
{ Black intends to develop the Bishop to d7 and then push us back with ...a7-a6. I used to like this system a lot, but that was more than ten years ago... }
4. O-O Bd7
{ The alternatives are covered in the relevant chapter, so I don't think this move requires any specific explanation. It just has to be done. }
5. Re1
{ Not only protecting the e4-Pawn but also releasing the f1-square for the Bishop. }
5... Nf6 6. c3 a6 7. Bf1 Bg4 8. d4
{ This is straightforward and effective. White simply grabs the center. } 8...
cxd4 9. cxd4 d5
{ This line is equal to  9...e5  , both in terms of quality and popularity. }
10. e5 { The critical try. White grabs space in the center. } 10... Ng8
{ Quite a typical retreat − the Knight will come back via e7. } 11. Re3
{ A novelty. White anticipates ...Bg4xf3, but also the Rook might be quite useful on the 3rd rank. }
11... e6 12. h3 Bh5 13. Nbd2
{ Offering Black a Pawn.  13...Nxd4?!  Now we are going to see the Rook's potential.  14.g4  Nxf3+  15.Nxf3  Bg6  16.Rb3!  The b7-Pawn is in danger.  For instance,  16...b5??  would nicely lose after  17.Rxb5!  axb5  18.Bxb5+  Ke7  19.Nd4  . See the corresponding variation for the full overview. }
13... Nge7 14. Be2
{ It takes a little bit of gymnastics from White, but we are finally beginning to achieve full coordination. }
14... Bg6
{ 14...Nf5?  runs into  15.Rb3!  and Black has to give up the Bishop pair, which is the only way to defend against both g4 and Rxb7. }
15. Rc3 Nf5 { It looks tempting, but White has a stoic answer. } 16. a3
{ We would like to bring the Knight to b3, but the immediate  16.Nb3  would be met with  16...Bb4!  After the text move, Black can't take on d4. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p3ppp/p1n1p1b1/3pPn2/3P4/P1R2N1P/1P1NBPP1/R1BQ2K1 b kq - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Ncxd4?  17.Nxd4  Nxd4  18.Qa4+  might be already winning for White! For instance,  18...Nb5  doesn't help much since we won't rush with  19.Bxb5+  , but play  19.Rb3  instead, increasing the pressure on the pinned Knight. Following  19...f6  20.Nf3  ,  Black can no longer avoid the inevitable as Nd4 and Bxb5+ are big threats. }
16... Be7 17. Nb3 O-O 18. Bf4
{ We want to double the Rooks on the c-file and bring the Knight to c5. White is slightly better. }
