[Black "Rossolimo 3.Bb5 e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Perhaps I should start with some explanations on why would we choose Bb5 against ...Nc6. Surely, you will find many repertoires that involve a Bb5 setup, for instance, in the Sicilian with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.Bb5+  or, as is the case here, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  3.Bb5  . You will also find a lot of repertoires where the attention shifts to  3.d4  instead.  I wanted to be as flexible as possible and my goal was to suggest the most challenging solution. The sad truth is that the Sveshnikov Variation is not posing Black serious problems at the moment, which shouldn't come as a surprise, as there aren't many topical games in this opening anymore. On the few occasions when White does go for the Sveshnikov, we will witness some boring draw, unless Black simply forgets the line. Besides the fact that White ran out of ideas, modern engines revealed that Black is okay in more than one way.  The Rossolimo though still has some poison in it, and this is also the trend at top-level chess. There are many games played by very strong GMs and it would be a shame to not include it in your repertoire based on the mere fact that you might go for 3.d4 in different lines.  We do have quite some work ahead though as we have to go through many lines, but I believe it is worth the effort and I am sure you will enjoy playing the Rossolimo with White. }
3... e5
{ For many years this line has been considered dubious and not many players paid attention to it, which naturally made it a great area for those who enjoyed exploring unknown paths. In the 2000s we had Zvjaginsev @@StartBracket@@as usual@@EndBracket@@, in the 2010s − Jobava. Finally, it got to the mainstream thanks to Magnus and, not surprisingly, Dubov. }
4. O-O Bd6 { The only serious continuation, in my opinion. } 5. d3
{ Simple and effective. The problem is that after  5.c3  a6  6.Ba4  b5  , I just couldn't prove White's advantage. It actually looks like a cool line for Black. }
5... Nf6 6. Bg5 { It is best to do it right away. } 6... a6 7. Bc4 Be7 8. a4
O-O 9. Nc3 d6 10. Bxf6
{ White gives up the Bishop pair in exchange for a very nice outpost for the Knight on d5, a square which was significantly weakened due to Black's ...c7-c5 and ...e7-e5 Pawn moves. }
10... Bxf6 11. Nd5
{ Somehow we transposed to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  e5  line,  with a4 and ...a6 included. This favors White − normally in that line, Black isn't keen to place the Pawn on a6 as it weakens the b6-square. }
11... Rb8 { 11...Be6  12.c3  g6  13.Qd2  Rb8  14.Ra3  transposes. } 12. c3 g6
{ Another typical way, Black wants to hide the Bishop on g7. } 13. Qd2
{ This is not just a developing move. After  13...Bg7  , White has  14.Qg5!  Black's Queen was covering many important squares so the trade is favorable for us. Also, our trumps will be just as noticeable in the endgame as they were with the Queens on. The complete line is given in the dedicated chapter. }
13... Be6 14. Ra3
{ We are giving up on the Qd2-g5 idea. Just to understand why, let's see the following line:  14.h3  Bg7  15.Qg5  b5!  16.Qxd8  Rfxd8  17.axb5  axb5  18.Bb3  Bxd5  19.Bxd5  Ne7  20.Bb3  c4!  21.dxc4  bxc4  22.Bxc4  Rxb2  . White is probably still pressing, but the position is too simplified to have hopes. I trust you are noticing the obvious − Black always has to make some accurate moves. }
14... Bg7 15. Rfa1
{ White is slightly better. I am not that naive to be hoping for ...b7-b5 now. The point of doubling the Rooks on the a-file is to play a4-a5. }
