[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide − Sicilian"]
[Black "Taimanov Variation 5.Nc3 Qc7 6.Be3 Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black delays moving the Pawn to d6 in order to have some more active options for the dark-squared Bishop. The Taimanov Variation has been for many years one of my favorite weapons for Black. However, the computer revolution did not serve it well, and although the line is objectively correct, new challenges keep popping up, questioning its practical value. }
6. Be3 Nf6 { Today this move order is considered inaccurate. } 7. f4 Bb4
{ This is how Black should challenge us even though it is not enough. } 8. Nb5
Qa5 9. e5 Ne4
{ Black wants to prevent Be3-d2, but is giving us other options. } 10. Bd3
{ 10.Qd3  is also nice. } 10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bxc3+ 12. Kf2 Bxa1
{ This is not a wise decision but, on the other hand,  12...O-O  13.Rb1  is just much better for White. }
13. Nd6+ Ke7 14. Qxa1
{ White's domination is undeniable since it is hard to talk about compensation. Which one of you would choose the black Rooks over our minor pieces? }
14... b6 15. Rd1 Ba6 16. Be4
{ We want to immobilize the black Queen with a2-a4. If Black plays  16...Qa4  , then we can activate our own Queen with  17.Qc3  . The engines believe that White is already winning, so I guess we have no reason to complain.  Ideas are pushing f4-f5, or taking on c6 and playing on the dark squares. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide − Sicilian"]
[Black "Taimanov Variation 5.Nc3 Qc7 6.Be3 a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black delays moving the Pawn to d6 in order to have some more active options for the dark-squared Bishop. The Taimanov Variation has been for many years one of my favorite weapons for Black. However, the computer revolution did not serve it well, and although the line is objectively correct, new challenges keep popping up, questioning its practical value. }
6. Be3 a6 7. g4
{ Currently, this aggressive move is one of the main challenges for Black. In some ways, it is similar to the  7.Qd2  line,  but there f2-f3 is played automatically, whereas here, at least in some lines, we can skip it and save time. }
7... b5 { By far the most popular continuation. } 8. Nxc6 Qxc6
{ Black is now threatening ...b5-b4. } 9. Qd2
{ Let Black take the Pawn, development is more important to us. } 9... b4 10.
Ne2 Qxe4 { 10...Bb7  11.O-O-O  Nf6  12.f3  would transpose. } 11. Rg1
{ The Queen is pretty exposed on e4, but that goes without saying. } 11... Qc4
{ The main move in the position. } 12. Ng3 Qc7
{ This is how Black played so far. } 13. O-O-O Nf6
{ I think this is the cleanest example of White benefiting from placing the Knight on g3 rather than f4. }
14. Bf4 { Black is facing an unpleasant choice. } 14... Qb6 15. Be5
{ This is not possible with the Queen on c5. On the other hand,  15.g5  wouldn't be that effective with the Queen on b6:  15...Nd5  16.Be5  Bb7  16.Nh5  O-O-O!  and the difference is that with the Queen  on b6, we don't have the Rg1-g4-c4 idea. }
15... d5 16. Kb1 Bb7 17. g5 Nd7 18. Bd4 Qc6 19. f4
{ Once again, we have more than enough compensation. Black probably should just castle long and then we can bring our Knight to b3. }
