[Black "Sicilian Four Knights 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ This line has become very popular, and most of the Sveshnikov players use it at least occasionally in order to avoid the Rossolimo. }
6. a3
{ Putting the Pawn on a3 so early has been one of the biggest developments in the Sicilian Defense in recent years. It can be tried against many different versions of Taimanov/Kan/Paulsen. }
6... Be7
{ The most critical response. Black keeps the Pawn on a7 and the Queen on d8, so in the case of long-castle plans, there will be more options available. }
7. Nxc6
{ I consider it a very good practical try, played by Anand and Caruana, among others. }
7... bxc6 8. e5 Nd5 9. Qg4
{ This is the difference compared to the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/2n1pn2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nxc6  line:  the Bishop is already on e7, so we can attack the g7-Pawn. }
9... g6 { The main move. } 10. Qg3 f5
{ A typical idea, but it doesn't mean it is always a good move. } 11. exf6 Nxf6
12. Be2 Qb6 { 12...O-O  13.h4!  and Black is in trouble. } 13. h4
{ Now Black is facing a difficult task: castling is not possible, but it's not clear what else to do. For instance,  13...Ba6  14.Bxa6  Qxa6  15.Bh6  Qb6  16.O-O-O!  and White is better. There is no need to be afraid of  16...Rb8  since we have  17.Na4  and after  17...Qb5  18.Rd3  ,  the knight on a4 is taboo.  In case of @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/p2pb2p/1qp1pnp1/8/7P/P1N3Q1/1PP1BPP1/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Rf8  14.Bh6!  Qxb2  15.O-O  and White has nice compensation for the Pawn. }
13... Qb8 14. Bf4 Qxb2 15. O-O
{ White has more than enough compensation for the Pawn.  15...Qxc2?  is refuted by  16.Bd3!  while after @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/p2pb2p/2p1pnp1/8/5B1P/P1N3Q1/1qP1BPP1/R4RK1 b kq - 1 15@@EndFEN@@  15...O-O  , we can go  16.Ra2!  Qb6  17.h5  . }
