[Black "Nimzowitsch Variation 2.Nf3 Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Nimzowitsch Variation is still quite popular, even at the top level. However, it has nothing to do with its objective strength. Chess players simply like to have fun sometimes. With the last move, Black is provoking us to push our central Pawn to e5. }
3. e5 { We don't mind at all. } 3... Nd5 4. Nc3 Nxc3 5. dxc3 Nc6
{ 5...e6  6.Bf4  Nc6  transposes. } 6. Bf4
{ This is the most natural square for the Bishop, defending our central Pawn and also anticipating ...d7-d6. }
6... Qb6
{ This is too risky. Black just can't go for the Pawns with so many pieces still in their starting positions. }
7. Bd3 Qxb2 8. O-O Qxc3 9. Re1
{ White's advantage in development is crushing. } 9... e6 10. a4
{ Now the black Queen is in danger. } 10... Qb4
{ 10...Qa5  11.Nd2  or @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/2p1P3/P4B2/2qB1N2/2P2PPP/R2QR1K1 b kq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...c4  Bd2  would hardly be any better. }
11. Be4 Be7 12. Nd2
{ We can include the Rook into the game with Re1-e3 or the Queen with Qd1-g4@@StartBracket@@h5@@EndBracket@@, or simply advance the h-Pawn. There is plenty of time as Black has no clear way of finishing development. Even though we sacrificed two Pawns to get this kind of compensation, it still feels like a huge discount. }
