[White "Quickstarter Guide − French"]
[Black "Winawer 6.bxc3 Ne7 7.Qg4 Nf5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... Bb4
{ The Winawer Variation is quite unique, even for the French. In most of the lines, the Bishop captures the Knight, and the arising Pawn structure is so specific that most of the players struggle to cope with it, especially since Black's dark squares are so weak that we tend to overestimate White's position. }
4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 { 6...Qc7  7.Qg4  Ne7  would transpose. } 7.
Qg4 Nf5
{ The reason why Black's last move isn't great is that the black Knight will be exposed on f5. The excuse is that Black will be able to activate the Queen quickly but as you will see, that plan simply doesn't work. }
8. Bd3 h5 9. Qf4 Qh4 { This is Black's main point. } 10. Qd2
{ 10.Ne2  would only offer White a slight advantage and I believe that Black deserves to be punished for the opening choice. }
10... Qg4 { The threat is ...Qg4xg2, or at least Black thinks that is. } 11.
Nf3 { We are okay with sacrificing that one as well. } 11... Qxg2 12. Ke2
{ Although we are not going to win that Queen, we will get more than enough for the Pawn. }
12... b6
{ Black is trying to neutralize White's initiative by swapping the light-squared Bishops. But I guess  12...Qxh1  can't be ignored.  13.Qg5!  We now want to go Bc1-b2, but also taking on f5 and then on g7 is a threat.  13...Ne7!?  14.dxc5!  Now, Black has no more tricks. A more detailed view is given in the corresponding chapter. }
13. Rg1 Qh3 14. dxc5 { It's a perfect moment to open up the position. } 14...
Ba6
{ 14...bxc5  15.Qf4!  would be too much. The Queen is really active in the center. It is also preventing the exchange of  Bishops @@StartBracket@@Qf4-a4+@@EndBracket@@. }
15. Qf4 Bxd3+ 16. cxd3
{ White has a powerful initiative, but we have to be precise here. So let's make a few more moves. }
16... Nc6
{ 16...bxc5  17.Rb1  followed by Rb7 would only make it easier for us. } 17.
cxb6 axb6 18. a4
{ An important move. White is preparing Bc1-a3. Notice that  18.Rg5  ,  preparing Nf3-g1, would be  met with  18...f6! }
18... O-O 19. Rg5 { Now, Black doesn't have a good answer. } 19... f6 20. exf6
Rxf6 21. Ng1 e5 { The only move. } 22. Nxh3 exf4 23. Nxf4
{ White is a Pawn up and has a better position, as all of Black's Pawns are weak. Probably, our position is already winning. }
