[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide − French"]
[Black "Rubinstein Variation 4.Nxe4 Nf6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... dxe4
{ Black has released the tension in the center. In general, this should be good news for White. }
4. Nxe4 Nf6 { A dubious continuation. } 5. Nxf6+
{ Taking back with the Pawn breaks Black's Pawn structure. Taking back with Queen is against one of the most principled rules: we should not develop our Queen early as it can easily become a target. }
5... Qxf6 { The Queen is exposed on f6. } 6. Nf3 h6
{ After Bf1-d3, Black will anyway have to do it so we might as well start with it. }
7. Bd3 Bd6
{ 7...Nc6  8.c3  Bd6  9.Qe2  Bd7  10.O-O  transposes to the 7...Bd6 move order. }
8. Qe2 { Giving Black one more chance to lose the Queen. } 8... O-O
{ Perfect. } 9. Qe4 Qf5
{ Objectively,  9...Re8  or  9...g6  would be preferable, but in any case, White is already winning. }
10. Qh4 Qf6 11. Bg5 { Black can resign. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide − French"]
[Black "Rubinstein Variation 4.Nxe4 Nd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... dxe4
{ Black has released the tension in the center. In general, this should be good news for White. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ Black's plan is to develop the pieces and, when the time comes, challenge White's center with ...c7-c5. It's a frequent guest in tournament practice mainly because of the complex positions arising from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bb4  or  3...Nf6  4.e5  , which are not to everyone's taste.  Also, if White does not handle the opening accurately, Black might equalize quite easily by just making healthy moves. Naturally, we are going to handle the opening as accurately as we can. }
5. Nf3 Ngf6 { 5...Be7  transposes to the 4...Be7 move order. } 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7.
Be3
{ This specific move order is directed against the ...c7-c5 plan which would be kind of a problem after  7.Bd3  .  Black can now develop his dark-squared Bishop to one of two possible squares or directly challenge our setup with ...Nf6-d5. }
7... Nd5
{ The most ambitious response. If we allow taking on e3 with  8.Bd3  Nxe3  9.fxe3  , then Black will  be able to achieve ...e6-e5 with the Bishop on c8. Please compare it  with the Pichot-Meier game @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/8/3P4/4BN2/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bd6  8.Bd3  b6  9.Qe2  O-O  10.O-O-O  Bb7  11.Rhe1  Nd5  @@EndBracket@@  . }
8. Bd2 Be7
{ Black is delaying ...c7-c5 waiting for White to develop the light-squared Bishop first. If Black challenges our Pawn center with  8...c5  , the only move to fight for advantage but also a logical one is  9.Bb5+  . Following  9...Bd7  10.Bxd7+  Qxd7  11.c4  Nb6  12.Rc1!  ,  the c4-Pawn has been defended, while Black can't take  12...cxd4  due to  13.c5  Nd5  14.Ne5  . The variation is thoroughly analyzed in the dedicated chapter. }
9. Bd3 c5
{ Both sides moved their Bishops @@StartBracket@@Bf1-d3 and ...Bf8-e7@@EndBracket@@ so it's hard to say that Black has actually gained anything with this delay. }
10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. O-O
{ Probably this is one of the most difficult moments. We have already seen how well the long castle lines worked so why not now? Let's try  11.Qe2  instead:  11...O-O  12.O-O-O  and now  12...Qc7  will transpose to one of the 7...Be7 lines which we like.  However Black can instead go  12...b5!  and it turns out that things are not that simple. Perhaps it is easier to reverse the question: why didn't we just castle short after@@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/8/3P4/4BN2/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Be7?  After  8.Bd3  O-O  9.O-O  , Black is not  forced to go ...c7-c5. The Bishop can be fianchettoed  − after  9...b6  , it seems that Black is doing just fine. }
11... O-O 12. Qe2 Qc7 13. Qe4
{ Provoking some serious weaknesses in Black's camp. } 13... f5
{ 13...Nf6  would give White a too strong attack after  14.Qh4  . } 14. Qe2 Bd7
15. Rfe1
{ White has a nice long-term advantage. We can place the Knight on e5 improving the pressure on Black's position. Also, a2-a3 makes a lot of sense − we would be happy to play b2-b4 and if Black stops it with ...a7-a5, then at least we provoked another weakness. }
