[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide − Caro-Kann & Others"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 3.e5 Bf5 4.h4 h6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The name Caro-Kann Defense comes from two players, Horatio Caro and Marcus Kann, who analyzed this opening in 1886. Its strategic idea is both sound and simple: Black wants to put the Pawn on d5, just like in the French, but without depriving the light-squared Bishop of its future on the h3-c8 diagonal.  I consider it a third @@StartBracket@@next to the Sicilian Defense and 1.e4 e5@@EndBracket@@ great @@StartBracket@@and bulletproof@@EndBracket@@ defense against 1.e4 − something that can be successfully used for a very long time. It is also strategically rich, as White can aim for both open and closed positions. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ The Advance Variation has always been considered critical against the Caro-Kann. After all, grabbing space in the center can't be a bad strategy. }
3... Bf5
{ This is the Caro-Kann players' argument in their debates with the French players. The Bishop is strong on f5, although it is frequently becoming a target and is sometimes missed on the Queenside. }
4. h4
{ One of the hottest Caro-Kann trends in recent years. It has been a part of the repertoires of many top 1.e4 players in the world such as Caruana, Giri, or Dominguez Perez. The main point of this aggressive continuation is to prepare the even more aggressive g2-g4.  Now Black has a choice: either allow g2-g4 or prevent it with ...h7-h5. Since ...h7-h5 is by far the main @@StartBracket@@and best!@@EndBracket@@ continuation, we could also say that by playing h2-h4, White is provoking ...h7-h5 which, as a result, weakens the g5-square. }
4... h6
{ Black does not want to weaken the g5-square. In my opinion, this is just too passive. }
5. g4 Bd7
{ I find it hard to justify this retreat, the Bishop is simply passive on d7. }
6. Be3 e6
{ An important moment as the natural  7.Nd2  will be met with  7...c5!  where Black seems okay. }
7. Nc3
{ Not the most natural square for the Knight but think of the @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pPb2/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nc3  e6  5.g4  line − with the black  light-squared Bishop on d7 instead of h7, we have a clearly better version of it. }
7... c5 8. dxc5 { This is why we developed the Knight to c3. } 8... Qc7
{ 8...a6  would be a lesser evil but the simple  9.Nf3  Qc7  10.Qd4  gives White a great advantage. }
9. Nb5 { Black can't take  9...Qxe5??  in view of  10.Nf3  . } 9... Bxb5 10.
Bxb5+ Nc6 11. c3 { We had to prevent ...Qc7-a5+. } 11... Qxe5 12. Qa4 Qc7 13.
Nf3
{ We will castle long and then advance the g-Pawn. Black's King will find no rest anywhere on the board. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide − Caro-Kann & Others"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 3.e5 Bf5 4.h4 h6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The name Caro-Kann Defense comes from two players, Horatio Caro and Marcus Kann, who analyzed this opening in 1886. Its strategic idea is both sound and simple: Black wants to put the Pawn on d5, just like in the French, but without depriving the light-squared Bishop of its future on the h3-c8 diagonal.  I consider it a third @@StartBracket@@next to the Sicilian Defense and 1.e4 e5@@EndBracket@@ great @@StartBracket@@and bulletproof@@EndBracket@@ defense against 1.e4 − something that can be successfully used for a very long time. It is also strategically rich, as White can aim for both open and closed positions. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ The Advance Variation has always been considered critical against the Caro-Kann. After all, grabbing space in the center can't be a bad strategy. }
3... Bf5
{ This is the Caro-Kann players' argument in their debates with the French players. The Bishop is strong on f5, although it is frequently becoming a target and is sometimes missed on the Queenside. }
4. h4
{ One of the hottest Caro-Kann trends in recent years. It has been a part of the repertoires of many top 1.e4 players in the world such as Caruana, Giri, or Dominguez Perez. The main point of this aggressive continuation is to prepare the even more aggressive g2-g4.  Now Black has a choice: either allow g2-g4 or prevent it with ...h7-h5. Since ...h7-h5 is by far the main @@StartBracket@@and best!@@EndBracket@@ continuation, we could also say that by playing h2-h4, White is provoking ...h7-h5 which, as a result, weakens the g5-square. }
4... h6
{ Black does not want to weaken the g5-square. In my opinion, this is just too passive. }
5. g4 Be4 6. f3 Bh7 7. Bd3
{ I know that  7.e6!?  was just screaming to be played, but after checking it for a while I decided that it was just not worth it, especially since our choice is both simple and strong. }
7... Bxd3 8. Qxd3 e6 9. h5
{ Fixing the black Pawns − g7 and h6 might be potentially weak in the endgame. }
9... c5 { Any other move would at best lead to a transposition. } 10. c3 Nd7
{ Black wants to bring the other Knight to c6. I believe that this is a misunderstanding, as the Knight won't be able to put pressure on our e5-Pawn anyway and the other Knight on d7 is just passive. }
11. f4 Ne7 12. Ne2
{ Basically, the same idea as Black's ...Nb8-d7: the other Knight will come to f3. }
12... Nc6 13. a3
{ 13.Nd2  cxd4  14.cxd4  Nb4  15.Qb3  would be no drama, but why allow it at all? White is clearly better. We will bring the Knight  to f3, move the King to f2 and then simply push the Pawn to f5, freeing the f4-square for the other Knight. }
