[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide − Caro-Kann & Others"]
[Black "Scandinavian Defense 2.exd5 Qxd5 3.Nc3 Qd6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian Defense is on the same level as the Alekhine Defense − it is not a good opening, objectively, but it does require some knowledge from us. For this reason, it is quite popular in rapid and blitz chess as the opening accuracy of even strong players is not that impressive in shorter time controls. }
2. exd5 Qxd5
{ Unlike other openings, Black begins development with the Queen. We know it's not a good strategy in general but we still have to prove it wrong. }
3. Nc3
{ For many years  3...Qa5  was played rather automatically, but today it's just one of the options. }
3... Qd6
{ Quite a popular continuation, mostly because Black's problem after  3...Qa5  became apparent.  3...Qd6  can be combined with many setups: the light-squared Bishop may be fianchettoed or developed to g4 @@StartBracket@@sometimes f5@@EndBracket@@. The dark-squared Bishop may be fianchettoed as well.  The Queen is less exposed on d6, although it can still be attacked. For instance, if White fianchettoes the light-squared Bishop, then the black Queen can be chased away with Bc1-f4. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6
{ I think this is the most important line. White could just fianchetto the light-squared Bishop, which would surely give a slight advantage, but this is the Scandinavian and we should expect more. }
6. Ne5
{ The critical move. We want to bring the Bishop to f4, although you are going to see other ideas too. }
6... Nbd7 { Now  7.Bf4  is not that effective as Black has  7...Nd5! } 7. f4
{ The position resembles the Caro-Kann Defense with one big difference: Black hasn't managed to develop the light-squared Bishop. }
7... Nb6 8. g4
{ White's aggressive play is justified. We didn't want Black to play ...h7-h5 followed by ...Bc8-f5. }
8... g6
{ 8...e6  9.g5  would be too much. After the text move, Black is not afraid of @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp2pp1p/1npq1np1/4N3/3P1PP1/2N5/PPP4P/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.g5  as  9...Nh5  is possible. }
9. Bg2 Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. a4 Be6 12. f5 { Black just can't catch a breath. }
12... Bd5 { 12...Bc4  13.Rf2  and a4-a5 is a threat. } 13. Nxd5 Nfxd5 14. a5
Nd7 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. Ra3
{ Thanks to the space advantage and Bishop pair, White has a clear advantage. We also have a simple plan: we want to bring the Rook to h3 and the Queen to h4. }
*

