1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian Defense is on the same level as the Alekhine Defense − it is not a good opening, objectively, but it does require some knowledge from us. For this reason, it is quite popular in rapid and blitz chess as the opening accuracy of even strong players is not that impressive in shorter time controls. }
2. exd5 Nf6
{ Black is intending to recapture with the Knight rather than the Queen. Many lines are just bad for Black and not because of specific lines but simply bad − passive pieces, no clear plan, etc. Therefore, I didn't try to cover every possible option, it is just not necessary. }
3. d4 Nxd5 4. Nf3 g6 { The most popular setup. } 5. c4 Nb6
{ With the Bishop on c8 defending the b7-Pawn, our usual c4-c5 plans are not that effective, although still acceptable. }
6. Nc3 Bg7 7. h3
{ I think this is too strong to look at other options. We prevented ...Bc8-g4 and now we will develop our Bishops. }
7... O-O 8. Be2 Nc6 9. Be3 e5
{ Pretty much the only way that Black can challenge our position. } 10. d5 Ne7
11. g4
{ Not allowing the black Knight to reach f5 but also revealing our intentions of castling long. }
11... f5 12. Qd2 e4
{ If  12...Nd7  @@StartBracket@@threatening ...f5-f4@@EndBracket@@,  then just  13.Bh6  , with a great advantage. }
13. Nh4 Nd7 { Black is regrouping. } 14. O-O-O Ne5 15. Bh6
{ Clearly, we don't mind swapping the dark-squared Bishops. } 15... Bxh6 16.
Qxh6 Nf7 17. Qe3
{ White has an outstanding position. We can try to open it up with f2-f3 or just push the Pawn to f4. Black has no real counterplay. }
