[White "Quickstarter Guide − Caro-Kann & Others"]
[Black "Alekhine Defense 5.f4 Bf5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6
{ As the title gives it away, the Alekhine Defense was introduced in 1921 by the former World Champion, Alexander Alekhine. This opening hasn't been very popular at the top level, but the boom of online chess brought it back to the limelight, together with other dubious lines.  The basic idea of developing the Knight to f6 straight away is to provoke White to advance the Pawn to the fifth ranks as early as move two and then challenge White's Pawn center. In a way, Black employs a similar strategy as in the Grünfeld Defense, but here, it is actually incorrect. }
2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6
{ There are many moves here, such as  4.Nf3  , but we will go  4.c4  . } 4. c4
Nb6 5. f4
{ While there are other good lines, this is clearly the most ambitious continuation. White simply grabs as much space as possible. }
5... Bf5 { Some young players have been using this move on the Internet. } 6.
Nc3 e6 7. Nf3 Be7 8. Be3 O-O
{ Black's point is that after  9.Be2?!  ,  instead of taking on e5,  9...d5!  is available, with a good game. }
9. Bd3
{ Normally @@StartBracket@@with ...d6xe5 and ...Nc6 included@@EndBracket@@, we can't really put the bishop on d3 because ...Bf5-g4 would be strong, but here we don't need to worry about it because Black has no pressure against d4. }
9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 d5 11. b3
{ Since the Knight on c3 is defended, we don't care about ...Be7-b4. } 11...
dxc4 { Otherwise, we could go c4-c5. } 12. bxc4 Na6 13. Rd1
{ White has a dominant position in the center. Let's just castle and prepare d4-d5 or f4-f5. }
