1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf was my hardest challenge in the whole course @@StartBracket@@including Part 1@@EndBracket@@. My assumption was that although Black is fine in general, we can certainly create some real practical problems in one of the main lines. So I started checking the main lines and it turned out that Black was indeed fine @@StartBracket@@so far so good@@EndBracket@@, but creating even practical problems was much harder than I expected − so much for the assumption.  The longer I checked the lines, the clearer it became to me: there are no main lines in the Najdorf anymore, there are just lines. Once I abandoned my old-school approach, I could broaden my explorations and all kinds of smaller lines started to grab my interest. Then I realized that this is what the top players have been doing for a while now, trying relatively unknown variations in order to surprise the opponent, but also because some of these lines are much stronger than we used to think. }
6. Rg1
{ Was that what Ian Nepomniachtchi prepared for the World Championship match in Dubai? We will never find out, but it's not unlikely. In the first few months of 2022, he became the biggest promoter of this aggressive line. The idea behind White's 6th move is as sound as the far more popular  6.h3  − we want  to push the Pawn to g4. }
6... Nc6
{ The main point of this move is that Black simply wants to win the g4-Pawn. }
7. g4 { Let Black grab the Pawn! } 7... h6
{ Not a popular move but it was played a few times in the last two years. Black is preventing g4-g5 while remaining flexible about the future plans. }
8. h4
{ This interesting idea has only been tried a couple of times. White insists on sacrificing the Pawn. }
8... Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Nxg4 10. Nd5 { 10.Be2  e5!  would be fine for Black. } 10...
Bd7 11. Be2 h5
{ This improvement should be anticipated. Black keeps the Knight although now we have the g5-square. }
12. Bg5 { 12.f3  was also possible but developing the Bishop looks nicer. }
12... f6 { Sensible but not 100% accurate. } 13. Be3 Rc8 14. O-O-O
{ In the next variation you will see why starting with 12...f6 was inaccurate but right now I can already say that castling long is an upgrade for White. }
14... e6 15. Nb6 Nxe3
{ A losing mistake although why it is one, is not obvious at all, even for the engines! }
16. Nxc8 Nxd1 17. Nxd6+ Bxd6 18. Qxd6 Nxf2 19. Rxg7
{ So far everything was pretty straightforward. Now Black has an illusory choice.  19...Nxe4??  @@StartBracket@@as well as some other moves@@EndBracket@@ will quickly lose after  20.Rg8+!  Rxg8  21.Bxh5+  with a mate to follow. }
19... Ng4 20. e5
{ Naturally, we don't mind the b1-h7 diagonal to open.  20...fxe5  21.Bd3  wins on the spot. }
20... Bc8 21. Qb4
{ We still need to be accurate. Black can't take  21...Nxe5  because of  22.Bxh5+!  Rxh5  23.Rg8+  Kd7  24.Qd4+  . Please compare this with @@StartFEN@@2bqk2r/1p4R1/p2Qpp2/4P2p/6nP/8/PPP1B3/2K5 w k - 1 21@@EndFEN@@  21.Qa3?!  − the same line wouldn't work as there would be no check in the end. }
21... f5 22. Qc5
{ It might not seem this way but White is completely winning.  22...Bd7  23.Bf3  Qxh4  24.Qd6!  and the Queen has to come back.  24...Qd8  25.Bxb7  , Black is practically in zugzwang. }
