6. Rg1
{ Was that what Ian Nepomniachtchi prepared for the World Championship match in Dubai? We will never find out, but it's not unlikely. In the first few months of 2022, he became the biggest promoter of this aggressive line. The idea behind White's 6th move is as sound as the far more popular  6.h3  − we want  to push the Pawn to g4. }
6... h6 { It's not about stopping g4-g5 but rather preparing ...g7-g5. } 7. g4
g5
{ We used to believe that placing the Pawn on g5 is always good in the Najdorf, but it is no longer the case. }
8. Be3 e6 { A bad move but also the main move, at least in the database. } 9.
h4 Rg8 { Holding this Pawn on g5 is a matter of life for Black. } 10. Qd2 Nfd7
11. O-O-O
{ It is already clear that this is too much − everything in Black's position is subordinated to the g5-Pawn. }
11... Nc6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Be2
{ We can hide the King on b1 and push the Pawn to f4. White has an overwhelming edge − almost all of Black's pieces are still in their starting positions! }
