13... Nh5 14. Rg5 e5
{ A losing mistake but only because of specific tactics, otherwise Black would be fine. }
15. Nf5 gxf5 16. exf5
{ White is threatening Qe2 and Bxc5 so Black doesn't have much of a choice. }
16... Bf6 17. Rxh5 Rxh5 18. Qe2 { A double attack! } 18... Rxf5
{ 18...Rg5  19.f4! } 19. Bxc5 Be7 20. Be4
{ This will give us an additional tempo. } 20... Rg5 21. Be3 Rg8 22. Kb1
{ With such powerful pieces, White must have a winning advantage. We want to open up the position with f2-f4 and if Black touches the light-squared Bishop, then we will collect the Queenside Pawns. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Najdorf 5.Nc3 a6 6.Rg1 − 6th Moves"]
[Black "Najdorf 6.Rg1 h5 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf was my hardest challenge in the whole course @@StartBracket@@including Part 1@@EndBracket@@. My assumption was that although Black is fine in general, we can certainly create some real practical problems in one of the main lines. So I started checking the main lines and it turned out that Black was indeed fine @@StartBracket@@so far so good@@EndBracket@@, but creating even practical problems was much harder than I expected − so much for the assumption.  The longer I checked the lines, the clearer it became to me: there are no main lines in the Najdorf anymore, there are just lines. Once I abandoned my old-school approach, I could broaden my explorations and all kinds of smaller lines started to grab my interest. Then I realized that this is what the top players have been doing for a while now, trying relatively unknown variations in order to surprise the opponent, but also because some of these lines are much stronger than we used to think. }
6. Rg1
{ Was that what Ian Nepomniachtchi prepared for the World Championship match in Dubai? We will never find out, but it's not unlikely. In the first few months of 2022, he became the biggest promoter of this aggressive line. The idea behind White's 6th move is as sound as the far more popular  6.h3  − we want  to push the Pawn to g4. }
6... h5
{ This is a really bold reaction! However, it's not that bold when your engine says it's okay to do it. :-@@EndBracket@@ }
7. Be3
{ I am not sure why almost nobody plays this natural move. Perhaps ...h7-h5 is so provoking that everybody feels that White has to react in some special way? }
7... Nbd7
{ Interesting move − Black is remaining flexible, although it is clear that ...b7-b5 would be the goal. }
8. h3 { We stick to the plan. } 8... h4 9. g4 hxg3 10. Rxg3
{ And the Rook is out! } 10... g6 { This is the best. } 11. Qd2 Nc5
{ The best. It might seem like a natural move but so do the alternatives − Black really has to be precise. }
12. f3 { 12.Bg2?!  Nh5!  would now be great for Black. } 12... Bg7
{ 12...Bd7  13.O-O-O  Bg7  would transpose. } 13. O-O-O Bd7 14. a3
{ We could throw in  14.Nf5  Bf8  15.Nd4  just to show who is the boss. The position is unclear with both sides having some interesting ideas.  We will keep thinking about Nd4-f5 while Black will try to arrange some counterplay on the Queenside. A healthy plan would be to move the Bishop to g2 and then push f3-f4.   One more thing: remember to move the King to b1, for instance, @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1p1bppb1/p2p1np1/2n5/3NP3/P1N1BPRP/1PPQ4/2KR1B2 b kq - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Rc8  15.Bg2?  Na4!  and Black is better. A tactical explanation is that after  16.Nxa4  Bxa4  17.Qb4  , Black has  17...b5!  18.b3  Qc7!  and if  19.bxa4  then  19...Nd5!  20.exd5  Bxd4  and Black wins.  Therefore @@StartFEN@@2rqk2r/1p1bppb1/p2p1np1/2n5/3NP3/P1N1BPRP/1PPQ4/2KR1B2 w k - 1 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Kb1!  should be played and the same line will no longer work for Black. In different positions, you might find different tactical explanations and since it is hard to figure them out over the board it is better to rely on one's feeling − and my feeling is that  whenever Black's Rook moves to c8, Kc1-b1 is very likely to be the move. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Najdorf 5.Nc3 a6 6.Rg1 − 6th Moves"]
[Black "Najdorf 6.Rg1 h5 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf was my hardest challenge in the whole course @@StartBracket@@including Part 1@@EndBracket@@. My assumption was that although Black is fine in general, we can certainly create some real practical problems in one of the main lines. So I started checking the main lines and it turned out that Black was indeed fine @@StartBracket@@so far so good@@EndBracket@@, but creating even practical problems was much harder than I expected − so much for the assumption.  The longer I checked the lines, the clearer it became to me: there are no main lines in the Najdorf anymore, there are just lines. Once I abandoned my old-school approach, I could broaden my explorations and all kinds of smaller lines started to grab my interest. Then I realized that this is what the top players have been doing for a while now, trying relatively unknown variations in order to surprise the opponent, but also because some of these lines are much stronger than we used to think. }
6. Rg1
{ Was that what Ian Nepomniachtchi prepared for the World Championship match in Dubai? We will never find out, but it's not unlikely. In the first few months of 2022, he became the biggest promoter of this aggressive line. The idea behind White's 6th move is as sound as the far more popular  6.h3  − we want  to push the Pawn to g4. }
6... h5
{ This is a really bold reaction! However, it's not that bold when your engine says it's okay to do it. :-@@EndBracket@@ }
7. Be3
{ I am not sure why almost nobody plays this natural move. Perhaps ...h7-h5 is so provoking that everybody feels that White has to react in some special way? }
7... e5
{ This natural move is a novelty, which shows how much potential to grow there is. }
8. Nb3
{ 8.Nf3  is also interesting but since we are dealing with a novelty, there is no need for alternative lines. }
8... Ng4
{ It is counterintuitive to do this now as the Knight has left the key d5-square. However, it is not impossible. }
9. Bd2 Nxh2 10. Bc4
{ I also tried  10.Nd5!?  After  10...Nxf1  11.Ba5  , Black saves the day with  11...Ne3!!  12.fxe3  Qh4+  13.g3  Qh2  and the position is unclear. }
10... Ng4 11. Qe2 { We are betting on development. } 11... Nd7 12. Nd5
{ Preventing ...Nd7-b6. } 12... Ngf6 13. Rh1
{ It is actually quite important not to castle here.  13.O-O-O?!  Nxd5!  14.Bxd5  Nb6!  and after  15.Ba5  , Black has  15...Qg5+!  After the text move, White has enough compensation for the Pawn and, what is more important, it won't be easy for Black to find the right follow-up. }
13... g6
{ I will only consider this because White's next move is not obvious either. }
14. Na5
{ Stopping the b7-Pawn @@StartBracket@@Na5-c6@@EndBracket@@ but more importantly, vacating the b3-square for the Bishop. }
14... Nxd5 15. Bxd5 Nb6 16. Bb3
{ I prefer this over  16.Bxb7  Bxb7  17.Nxb7  Qc8  with an unclear position. We will castle long on the next move and then perhaps put some pressure  on the d6-Pawn with Bd2-b4. }
