[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Najdorf 5.Nc3 a6 6.Rg1 − 6th Moves"]
[Black "Najdorf 6.Rg1 h5 #15"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf was my hardest challenge in the whole course @@StartBracket@@including Part 1@@EndBracket@@. My assumption was that although Black is fine in general, we can certainly create some real practical problems in one of the main lines. So I started checking the main lines and it turned out that Black was indeed fine @@StartBracket@@so far so good@@EndBracket@@, but creating even practical problems was much harder than I expected − so much for the assumption.  The longer I checked the lines, the clearer it became to me: there are no main lines in the Najdorf anymore, there are just lines. Once I abandoned my old-school approach, I could broaden my explorations and all kinds of smaller lines started to grab my interest. Then I realized that this is what the top players have been doing for a while now, trying relatively unknown variations in order to surprise the opponent, but also because some of these lines are much stronger than we used to think. }
6. Rg1
{ Was that what Ian Nepomniachtchi prepared for the World Championship match in Dubai? We will never find out, but it's not unlikely. In the first few months of 2022, he became the biggest promoter of this aggressive line. The idea behind White's 6th move is as sound as the far more popular  6.h3  − we want  to push the Pawn to g4. }
6... h5
{ This is a really bold reaction! However, it's not that bold when your engine says it's okay to do it. :-@@EndBracket@@ }
7. Be3
{ I am not sure why almost nobody plays this natural move. Perhaps ...h7-h5 is so provoking that everybody feels that White has to react in some special way? }
7... e5
{ This natural move is a novelty, which shows how much potential to grow there is. }
8. Nb3
{ 8.Nf3  is also interesting but since we are dealing with a novelty, there is no need for alternative lines. }
8... Be6
{ So, we have got some kind of 6.Be3 Najdorf with Rg1 and ...h5 included. It is not easy to figure out which side benefits from this inclusion, but it is clear that the sides with a better understanding of the nuances will get the upper hand.   8...Be7  9.h3  Be6  transposes. }
9. h3
{ 9.Qd2  was also possible but then we would have to consider  9...Ng4  . }
9... Nbd7 10. Qd2
{ We should note that  10.Qf3?!  would be inaccurate here.  10...Rc8!  and Black is threatening the typical exchange sacrifice  on c3 and, compared with the 9...Be7 variation, White can't go  11.Nd5  as the c2-Pawn would fall. }
10... Be7 11. O-O-O b5 12. f4
{ Actually, I think that White should be happy with how the opening went. If you move the Rook back to h1, we will get one of the theoretical positions in the Be3 Najdorf. }
12... Qc7 13. Kb1 { White is ready to push the Pawn to f5 and then go g2-g4. }
13... Nb6
{ Black is now threatening ...b5-b4 and our usual  14.a3  won't work that well because of  14...Na4! }
14. Qf2 { The best chance! } 14... Na4 { A typical idea. } 15. Nd5 Bxd5
{ The only move. } 16. exd5 Ne4
{ Once again, other moves were bad. Black's point is that after  17.Qf3  , there is  17...Nac3+!  18.bxc3  Nxc3+  19.Kc1  e4!  20.Qf2  Bf6  and White can't prevent the perpetual check. As you can see, the line is extremely demanding for Black. }
17. Qe1 Rc8
{ Now we can't go  18.Bd3?  Nac3+  19.bxc3  Nxc3+  20.Ka1  e4  with a winning position as Black hasn't castled yet! }
18. Rc1 O-O 19. g4
{ We do have the opposite side castling so I guess no explanation is required here. }
19... exf4 20. Bd4
{ This is the Najdorf which means that White needs to be careful too.  20.Bxf4??  would lose in spectacular fashion after  20...Bf6!  21.Qxe4  @@StartBracket@@it was already too late for correcting mistakes@@EndBracket@@  21...Nc3+!  22.bxc3  Qxc3  . }
20... Ng3 21. gxh5
{ White's threat is simple: we want to take the Knight on g3. } 21... Bg5
{ Black is anticipating  Rg1xg3  . Amazingly, this is the only move that doesn't lose. Even  21...Bh4  22.Qd2!  is already +7 according to the engines. }
22. Rxg3 fxg3 23. Qxg3 f6
{ The point! However, now the light squares are terrible again. } 24. Bd3
{ We are already very deep, given where we started. Both  24...Bxc1  25.Nxc1  and @@StartFEN@@2r2rk1/2q3p1/p2p1p2/1p1P2bP/n2B4/1N1B2QP/PPP5/1KR5 b - - 1 24@@EndFEN@@  24...Nc5  25.Bf5  Nxb3  26.axb3  Bxc1  27.Kxc1  give White beautiful compensation for two @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ exchanges. The computers only see the draw @@StartBracket@@as always@@EndBracket@@ but the practical value is, in my opinion, simply outstanding. }
