h5
{ As solid as it looks, it is not bulletproof. Black will have to watch out for the Bishop sacrifice on h5, there is also an f4-f5 idea, especially now with the g6-Pawn being vulnerable. Most of the time though, the position might get simplified. In these cases, we should be aiming for the light-squared Bishop ending. Many of Black's Pawns are fixed on the light squares which makes them good targets. }
10. Be3 Bg7 11. Be2 Qa5
{ I think that this is critical. Black is wasting no time for castling and instead, is trying to quickly create counterplay. }
12. Qd2 Nc5 13. O-O-O Ne6 { A key move for Black's plan. } 14. Nb3
{ This is the best chance.  14.Nxc6  bxc6  is just unclear as Black is able to create enough counterplay on the b-file. }
14... Bxc3 15. Qxc3
{ Doubled Pawns aren't nice but we will compensate for them. } 15... Qxc3 16.
bxc3 Bd7 17. f4 { We now want to to play a2-a4. } 17... b5
{ In spite of my previous comment, this is rather clear: Black prevented a2-a4, for now. }
18. Kb2
{ White is a bit better. We have quite a few interesting plans: we can put one Rook on a1, threatening a2-a4, and the other one on f1 @@StartBracket@@supporting f4-f5@@EndBracket@@ or e1 @@StartBracket@@supporting e4-e5@@EndBracket@@. Black's main problem is that it is not entirely clear how to continue. }
