[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf was my hardest challenge in the whole course @@StartBracket@@including Part 1@@EndBracket@@. My assumption was that although Black is fine in general, we can certainly create some real practical problems in one of the main lines. So I started checking the main lines and it turned out that Black was indeed fine @@StartBracket@@so far so good@@EndBracket@@, but creating even practical problems was much harder than I expected − so much for the assumption.  The longer I checked the lines, the clearer it became to me: there are no main lines in the Najdorf anymore, there are just lines. Once I abandoned my old-school approach, I could broaden my explorations and all kinds of smaller lines started to grab my interest. Then I realized that this is what the top players have been doing for a while now, trying relatively unknown variations in order to surprise the opponent, but also because some of these lines are much stronger than we used to think. }
6. Rg1
{ Was that what Ian Nepomniachtchi prepared for the World Championship match in Dubai? We will never find out, but it's not unlikely. In the first few months of 2022, he became the biggest promoter of this aggressive line. The idea behind White's 6th move is as sound as the far more popular  6.h3  − we want  to push the Pawn to g4. }
6... g6 { Black is hoping to get an improved version of the Dragon. } 7. g4
{ In case you were thinking about  7.f3  , trying to play in the same way we do against the normal Dragon,  7...Qb6!  is strong.  This is one of the few cases when we really don't like our Rook on g1. }
7... Nc6 8. g5 Nd7 9. h4 { It is best to advance the h-Pawn right away. } 9...
h6 { Hoping to clear up the situation. } 10. h5
{ I consider it a great practical try. } 10... Nxd4
{ This is clearly the best. } 11. Qxd4
{ 11.hxg6?  is not a smart intermediate move since it can be met with  11...Ne5!  and it is Black who has the upper hand now. }
11... Ne5 { Black wins a priceless tempo thanks to the ...Ne5-f3+ threat. } 12.
Be2 hxg5
{ Black is now ready for  13.hxg6  Bg7!  14.gxf7+  Kxf7  with an unclear position. }
13. Bxg5 Rxh5
{ The key to Black's defense, otherwise White's advantage would be decisive. }
14. Bxh5 gxh5 { Black is threatening ...Ne5-f3+. } 15. O-O-O
{ If now  15...Nf3??  then White is much better after  16.Qh8! } 15... Bg4
{ Adding another threat. } 16. Nd5
{ Objectively speaking, Black is already okay so for us it's mainly about finding the best practical try. After our last move, Black can equalize in three ways but none of them is simple. }
16... Qa5 { Black is now threatening to win both our Rook and the a2-Pawn. }
17. Kb1 Nf3
{ I especially hope for this one.  18.Qe3  Nxg1  19.Rxg1  Rc8  looks great for Black so why not? }
18. Bd2
{ Surprise! Once again, Black's Queen is caught off guard. After  18...Qd8  19.Qh8  Nxg1  20.Rxg1  , White is easily winning. }
18... Nxd4 19. Bxa5 Bxd1 20. Nc7+ Kd7 21. Rxd1 Rb8
{ Black is lucky to have this. } 22. Rxd4 b6 23. Nxa6 Ra8 24. Bc3 Rxa6 25. Rd3
{ Black cannot save the h5-Pawn. Whether the game can be saved is a different question but being a clear Pawn up, we have every right to hope for the best. }
*

