18. Bxe7 Bxd1 { Only now. } 19. Qxd1 Bxe7 20. b4
{ 20.Rg8+  was also possible with the same outcome. } 20... Qb5
{ 20...Qa4  would also end in the same way. } 21. Rg8+ Bf8
{ But not  21...Kd7?  22.a4!  and Black has to go for  22...Qxd5  23.Qxd5  Rxg8  . After  24.Qxb7  Ke8  @@StartBracket@@  24...Ke6?  25.f4  , with a winning position.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@4k1r1/1Q2bp2/p2p4/4n2p/PP2P3/8/2P2P2/1K6 w - - 1 25@@EndFEN@@  25.Qb8+  Bd8  26.Qxd6  White has decent winning chances. }
22. Nf6+ Ke7 23. Nd5+ Kd7
{ 23...Ke8  would force a perpetual check but let's how we should continue if Black decides to play on. }
24. a4 { Not the only move but it would be my choice. } 24... Qc6 25. c3
{ White has enough compensation for the piece and Black still needs to be careful not to lose this one. }
25... Re8 { 25...Be7??  26.Rxc8  and either recapture loses the Queen. } 26.
Qxh5 Be7 27. Rxe8 Kxe8 28. Qh8+ Kd7 29. Qg8
{ White has a simple threat: f2-f4. } 29... Bd8
{ The only saving move. Now the Bishop controls the crucial b6-square, allowing the Queen to move. }
30. Qh7
{ We had to be careful here!  30.f4?  would be losing since Black has  30...Qc4! }
30... Qxa4 31. Qh3+ Ke8 32. Qh8+ { White gives a perpetual check. } *

