7. a4 { Not the only move, but it is the most challenging one. } 7... bxa4
{ Objectively speaking, this is okay but from a practical point of view, White gets some great attacking chances. }
8. g4 { It is so much easier when we don't need to worry about ...b5-b4. } 8...
g6 9. g5 { The best try. } 9... Nfd7 { 9...Nh5?  10.Be2  . } 10. h4 Bg7 11. h5
O-O { Black could not simply allow h5-h6, which would now be met with ...Bh8. }
12. hxg6 hxg6 13. Nf5
{ If Black won't accept the piece sacrifice, then we will simply take on g7 with a big advantage. }
13... gxf5 14. Qh5 Ne5
{ The only move to stay in the game, anything else loses. For example,  14...Nc6  does develop a piece, but it doesn't bring the black King any comfort.  15.Rh1  Re8  16.g6  and Black is busted. After @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/3nppb1/p2p4/5pPQ/p3P3/2N5/1PP2P2/R1B1KBR1 b Q - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14...e6  , we have a similar story:  15.exf5  exf5  16.Bc4  , with lethal consequences. }
15. Rh1 Re8 16. Qh7+ Kf8 17. exf5 Bxf5
{ After  17...Qb6  18.Be2  ,  threatening f6, Black would have to give back the piece anyway and only in a worse version.  Trying to prevent f6 would only make things worse for Black since both  18...Bb7  and  18...Nbd7  can be met by  19.g6  followed by Bh6, with a winning attack for White. }
18. Qxf5 Ng6 { 18...e6  19.Qh7  followed by Rxa4 and White should be better. }
19. Rxa4 Nd7 20. Rh7 Kg8 { Freeing the f8-square for the Knight. } 21. Qh3
Bxc3+
{ 21...Ndf8??  22.Rxg7+!  Kxg7  23.f4!  and White's attack is unstoppable. }
22. bxc3 Ndf8 23. Rh6 Qd7
{ The Knights keep Black's King safe so there is no point in avoiding the exchange of Queens. }
24. Qxd7 Nxd7 25. Be3
{ Black is close to equality but still needs to be careful as White's Bishops are strong. }
