[Round "?"]
[White "2. Najdorf 6.Rg1 b5"]
[Black "Najdorf 6.Rg1 b5 7.a4 bxa4 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf was my hardest challenge in the whole course @@StartBracket@@including Part 1@@EndBracket@@. My assumption was that although Black is fine in general, we can certainly create some real practical problems in one of the main lines. So I started checking the main lines and it turned out that Black was indeed fine @@StartBracket@@so far so good@@EndBracket@@, but creating even practical problems was much harder than I expected − so much for the assumption.  The longer I checked the lines, the clearer it became to me: there are no main lines in the Najdorf anymore, there are just lines. Once I abandoned my old-school approach, I could broaden my explorations and all kinds of smaller lines started to grab my interest. Then I realized that this is what the top players have been doing for a while now, trying relatively unknown variations in order to surprise the opponent, but also because some of these lines are much stronger than we used to think. }
6. Rg1
{ Was that what Ian Nepomniachtchi prepared for the World Championship match in Dubai? We will never find out, but it's not unlikely. In the first few months of 2022, he became the biggest promoter of this aggressive line. The idea behind White's 6th move is as sound as the far more popular  6.h3  − we want  to push the Pawn to g4. }
6... b5
{ The most aggressive reaction. It is like an invitation to dance − it would be a pity to decline. }
7. a4 { Not the only move, but it is the most challenging one. } 7... bxa4
{ Objectively speaking, this is okay but from a practical point of view, White gets some great attacking chances. }
8. g4 { It is so much easier when we don't need to worry about ...b5-b4. } 8...
g6 9. g5 { The best try. } 9... Nfd7 { 9...Nh5?  10.Be2  . } 10. h4 Bb7 11. h5
Nc5
{ Smart play from Black to keep the Bishop on f8 and counterattack on the other side instead. }
12. Rg4 { Quite a way to defend our central Pawn! } 12... Nc6
{ This is possible, although Black's task will be extremely difficult. } 13.
Nxc6 Bxc6 14. Nd5 gxh5
{ 14...Bg7  was not possible due to  15.h6  and I didn't see what else Black could play. }
15. Rf4 Bg7 { 15...Ne6  16.Rf5! } 16. Qxh5 Rf8 17. Ra3
{ Another Rook comes into play. } 17... Nxe4 18. Rxe4 Qa5+
{ An important move as  18...Bxd5  19.Rexa4  would be clearly better for White. }
19. Bd2 Qxd5 20. Rae3 Qxe4
{ Black might be tempted to do this, however, Black's position will remain difficult. }
21. Rxe4 Bxe4 22. Qe2 Bc6 23. Bb4 { Now the d6-Pawn is hanging. } 23... Be5 24.
Qc4
{ White keeps the initiative. If  24...Bd7  then  25.Qe4  Rb8  26.Be2  is strong, preventing any counter-chances. For example,  26.Bxa6  allows the liberating  26...f5!  27.Qh4  Be6  28.c3  f4  and if  29.Qxh7  Rg8  , when Black is suddenly back in the game.  After @@StartFEN@@1r2kr2/3bpp1p/p2p4/4b1P1/pB2Q3/8/1PP2P2/4KB2 w - - 8 26@@EndFEN@@  26.Be2  , Black has serious coordination issues. Trying to disentangle with  26...Be6  can be met by  27.f4  and White's Queen weighs more than the two Rooks. Probably Black should defend with @@StartFEN@@r3kr2/4pp1p/p1bp4/4b1P1/pBQ5/8/1PP2P2/4KB2 b q - 5 24@@EndFEN@@  24...Rc8  25.Qxa6  Kd7  . }
*

