6. Rg1
{ Was that what Ian Nepomniachtchi prepared for the World Championship match in Dubai? We will never find out, but it's not unlikely. In the first few months of 2022, he became the biggest promoter of this aggressive line. The idea behind White's 6th move is as sound as the far more popular  6.h3  − we want  to push the Pawn to g4. }
6... b5
{ The most aggressive reaction. It is like an invitation to dance − it would be a pity to decline. }
7. a4 { Not the only move, but it is the most challenging one. } 7... b4
{ This is by far the most popular continuation and also a critical one. } 8.
Nd5 Nxe4
{ I think this is the sharpest possible line in the whole 6.Rg1 system. } 9.
Bc4
{ This is the best try, and it was already played in the game between Maxime Vachier-Lagrave and Ding Liren in Opera Euro Rapid, chess24 2021. }
9... e6 10. Qe2 { White has so many active pieces! } 10... Nc5
{ Basically the only move. } 11. c3
{ Following in the Frenchman's footsteps, we want to undermine the Knight's position, which is the only piece that Black has developed so far! }
11... bxc3 12. b4 Nb7 { Not the nicest move but it's the best Black can do. }
13. g4
{ It isn't the first time White makes this brilliant move − it might be connected with Nd4-f5, Rg1-g3, or g4-g5. A truly multi-purpose move! }
13... g6
{ Covering the f5-square and preparing the fianchetto, what could possibly go wrong? }
14. h4 { The dark squares! White is threatening Bc1-g5. } 14... Be7
{ 14...h6  15.h5!  and if  15...g5  then  16.Nf5  wins. } 15. Bh6
{ This piece sacrifice should give White a decisive edge. } 15... exd5 16. Bxd5
{ White is threatening Qf3 or simply Rg3. More importantly, Black has no moves. }
16... Qb6 { At least with this Black is attacking something. } 17. Bg7 Rg8 18.
Bf6 Be6 { Actually, this is quite challenging. } 19. Bxe6 Bxf6 20. Bxf7+ Kxf7
{ It might seem like the worst is behind Black... } 21. Qe6+ Kg7 22. Nf5+
{ Suddenly, Black is getting mated. } *

