[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ The Najdorf was my hardest challenge in the whole course @@StartBracket@@including Part 1@@EndBracket@@. My assumption was that although Black is fine in general, we can certainly create some real practical problems in one of the main lines. So I started checking the main lines and it turned out that Black was indeed fine @@StartBracket@@so far so good@@EndBracket@@, but creating even practical problems was much harder than I expected − so much for the assumption.  The longer I checked the lines, the clearer it became to me: there are no main lines in the Najdorf anymore, there are just lines. Once I abandoned my old-school approach, I could broaden my explorations and all kinds of smaller lines started to grab my interest. Then I realized that this is what the top players have been doing for a while now, trying relatively unknown variations in order to surprise the opponent, but also because some of these lines are much stronger than we used to think. }
6. Rg1
{ Was that what Ian Nepomniachtchi prepared for the World Championship match in Dubai? We will never find out, but it's not unlikely. In the first few months of 2022, he became the biggest promoter of this aggressive line. The idea behind White's 6th move is as sound as the far more popular  6.h3  − we want  to push the Pawn to g4. }
6... b5
{ The most aggressive reaction. It is like an invitation to dance − it would be a pity to decline. }
7. a4 { Not the only move, but it is the most challenging one. } 7... b4
{ This is by far the most popular continuation and also a critical one. } 8.
Nd5 Nxd5 9. exd5 Bb7 { Targeting the d5-Pawn. } 10. Nf5 Qc7
{ 10...g6?  11.Qd4  Rg8  12.Ne3  and White is much better. } 11. Qd4
{ A novelty − this is simply too good not to try it! } 11... e5
{ The best reply. } 12. Qc4
{ Our assumption is that in the endgame White is going to have good chances for advantage as the b4-Pawn is weak. }
12... Qxc4 { Any other move would be wrong. } 13. Bxc4 g6
{ Black should aim for immediate counterplay. } 14. Ne3 f5
{ 14...a5  15.c3!  would be slightly better for White. } 15. a5 f4
{ Black is trying to disrupt the harmony between our pieces. You have to admit, this is not a typical endgame @@StartBracket@@or perhaps it's not an endgame at all@@EndBracket@@ − every move is relevant. }
16. Ng4 Nd7 17. f3 Rc8 { 17...Be7  18.Ke2  Rc8  19.b3  transposes. } 18. b3 Be7
{ One more nuance that Black has to be aware of: the Bishop might look bad on e7 but ...Be7-d8 will be Black's critical resource. }
19. Ke2 Kf7
{ Black had to be accurate.  19...h5  20.Nf2  Nf6  21.Rd1  would be clearly better for White  as Ra1-a4 was coming. One thing that we should understand about this endgame is that White generally should have the advantage and it's only thanks to very specific solutions that Black somehow manages to equalize. }
20. Ra4
{ It is important to see the  20.Bd2  line as it allows us to understand a very important point.  20...Rxc4!  Otherwise, White would be just better.  21.bxc4  Rc8  . If Black wins  the c4-Pawn, then d5 would fall as well. It is best to take the draw now.  22.Kd3  Nc5+  23.Ke2=  . }
20... Nc5 { This is why Black needed the Knight on d7. } 21. Rxb4
{ It was already okay to retreat the Rook, forcing Black to do the same as Bc1-d2 would become a threat. }
21... Bd8 22. g3 Bxa5
{ 22...fxg3  23.Be3!  is our point although after  23...gxh2  24.Nxh2  Ba8!  the position remains unclear. }
23. Rxb7+ Nxb7 24. gxf4 exf4 25. Bxf4
{ After  25...Rhe8+  , we should retreat  26.Kd1  . White has enough compensation for the exchange but nothing more. We can still play for a win, for instance, by pushing the h-Pawn, but it is important to remember that the position is balanced so we shouldn't push too hard. }
