{ This is widely considered to be the most challenging continuation. White wants to castle long and developing the Bishop to g5 first is the best way to do it. We should note that after both  6.Be3  Ng4  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.f3  e5  , Black benefits from developing the  Knight to c6 instead of putting the Pawn on a6. }
6... g6
{ One of Dubov's favorite lines, at least in rapid chess. Black is hoping that the Bishop pair will compensate for the broken Pawn structure. }
7. Bxf6 exf6 8. Bb5
{ This line is very simple as Black doesn't have much of a choice. } 8... Bd7
9. Qd2
{ There are of course other moves, this is just what I think is both strong and simple. }
9... Bg7 10. O-O-O O-O 11. Nb3 { It is time to say goodbye to the d6-Pawn. }
11... f5 { The move is logical but there is no follow-up. } 12. Qxd6
{ 12...Bxc3  13.Qxd7  is much better for White. } 12... Be6
{ The side with a material advantage should seek simplifications. ;-@@EndBracket@@ }
13. Qxd8 Rfxd8 14. exf5 Bxf5 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Rxd8+ Rxd8 17. Rd1
{ I am not 100% sure but I think that White's advantage might be enough to convert it into a win. }
