1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ This natural move does not yet commit Black to any specific ideas. Black keeps both ...e7-e6 and ...e7-e5 on the table, just like in the Najdorf. }
6. Bg5
{ This is widely considered to be the most challenging continuation. White wants to castle long and developing the Bishop to g5 first is the best way to do it. We should note that after both  6.Be3  Ng4  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.f3  e5  , Black benefits from developing the  Knight to c6 instead of putting the Pawn on a6. }
6... e6 7. Qd2 Be7
{ This used to be one of the main lines and it's still being chosen quite frequently. }
8. O-O-O O-O { Black is choosing to fight. } 9. h4
{ A rare but strong continuation. White wants to achieve the f2-f3 setup, but it is important to start like this.  9.f3  Nxd4!  10.Qxd4  a6  would be okay for Black. }
9... h6 { Not the best reaction. } 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. e5 dxe5 12. Bxh6
{ This is the point of our previous move. Black can't take the Bishop.  12...gxh6  13.Qxh6  and with the Queen under attack, Black will have no time to organize the defense. The 3rd rank will decide. }
12... Nd5
{ 12...Qxd2+  13.Bxd2  and White has a big advantage in the endgame thanks to Black's damaged Pawn structure. }
13. Rh3 f5 14. Bg5
{ Black's Pawn center might look nice but it's not solid. We shall bring the Bishop to c4 and then to b3 followed by Nc3-a4 and possibly c2-c4. On the Kingside, we can always consider g2-g4. }
