{ This is widely considered to be the most challenging continuation. White wants to castle long and developing the Bishop to g5 first is the best way to do it. We should note that after both  6.Be3  Ng4  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.f3  e5  , Black benefits from developing the  Knight to c6 instead of putting the Pawn on a6. }
6... e6 7. Qd2 Be7
{ This used to be one of the main lines and it's still being chosen quite frequently. }
8. O-O-O O-O { Black is choosing to fight. } 9. h4
{ A rare but strong continuation. White wants to achieve the f2-f3 setup, but it is important to start like this.  9.f3  Nxd4!  10.Qxd4  a6  would be okay for Black. }
9... Nxd4 10. Qxd4 h6
{ As you probably suspect we are not going to retreat the Bishop... } 11. f3
{ I find this a bit more practical than  11.f4  where after  11...Qa5  , though White is better, it is not easy to continue.  With the text move, we are leaving Black no easy choice: either take the Bishop right away or allow us to retreat it and then face the consequences of the 11th move as g4-g5 will be much stronger. }
11... e5 { Black is grabbing space while that's still possible. } 12. Qf2 hxg5
13. hxg5 Nh7 { This is not much different than  13...Ne8  . } 14. f4 Bxg5 15.
fxg5 Qxg5+ 16. Kb1 Be6 17. Be2
{ 17.Rd3  would be less effective here.  The difference is that after playing ...g7-g6 and ...Kg8-g7, the black Queen could retreat to e7, freeing the g5-square for the Knight. }
17... g6 18. Rxd6
{ White has won the Pawn back but the initiative is still there. The Rook can retreat to d3, which will force Black to stay alert. At any time we can consider Nc3-d5, giving Black a tough choice. }
