[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ This natural move does not yet commit Black to any specific ideas. Black keeps both ...e7-e6 and ...e7-e5 on the table, just like in the Najdorf. }
6. Bg5
{ This is widely considered to be the most challenging continuation. White wants to castle long and developing the Bishop to g5 first is the best way to do it. We should note that after both  6.Be3  Ng4  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.f3  e5  , Black benefits from developing the  Knight to c6 instead of putting the Pawn on a6. }
6... e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O Be7
{ How is Black's last move different than  8...Bd7?  The point of developing the light-squared Bishop to d7 and keeping the dark-squared friend in its starting position for a bit longer is that, in the case of Black being forced to recapture on f6 with the g7-Pawn, which usually is the case, the Bishop will be better placed on f8 as it can be activated using the h6-square.   Why would Black even consider starting with  8...Be7  instead? Because the same point applies to the light-squared Bishop.  By keeping it on c8 for a bit longer, Black maintains the possibility of developing or playing ...b7-b5 and ...Bc8-b7 @@StartBracket@@or, though it is less often the case, ...Nc6xd4, ...e6-e5 and ...Bc8-e6@@EndBracket@@, basically saving a tempo as Black normally has to play ...Bc8-d7-c6 and ...b7-b5.  This idea can be rarely executed in the f2-f4 lines @@StartBracket@@with the typical Rauzer Pawns on f7, f6, e6, d6@@EndBracket@@, and the Bishop is needed on d7 from where it supports the crucial e6-Pawn. However, it works nicely against the f3 lines:  9.f3?!  Nxd4!  10.Qxd4  b5!  and, you can take my word for it, Black has no problems. In other words, Black is willing to accept an inferior  version of the f4 lines in order to avoid the f3 variations. }
9. Bxf6 { It is a logical conclusion: we must show some flexibility. } 9...
gxf6 10. f4 Bd7
{ 10...Nxd4  11.Qxd4  Bd7  12.f5  transposes, while @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1p2bp1p/p1nppp2/8/3NPP2/2N5/PPPQ2PP/2KR1B1R b kq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Qc7  11.f5  Nxd4  12.Qxd4  Bd7  13.Kb1  Qc5  transposes as well. }
11. f5
{ There is no reason for us to delay it. The e6-Pawn is our primary target: it is the foundation of Black's position, and getting rid of it will often be worth sacrificing our own Pawn or even an exchange. }
11... Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Qa5 13. Kb1
{ I don't think there is a single line in the chapter where White completely skips this move. }
13... O-O-O
{ I believe that this is slightly inaccurate. It allows White to develop the Bishop to c4 and I think we should take that chance. }
14. Bc4 Qc5 15. Qd3 Kb8 16. a3
{ As mysterious as White's last move seems, there is a logical explanation: we want to increase the pressure on the e6-Pawn with Nc3-e2-f4, but once the Knight comes to e2, there is one more idea: bringing the Queen to b3.   However, if White starts with  16.Ne2  then after  16...Rhg8  17.Nf4  fails to  17...d5!  18.exd5  Rg4!  and in view of  19.g3  e5!  White is in trouble. Instead, we could try @@StartFEN@@1k1r2r1/1p1bbp1p/p2ppp2/2q2P2/2B1P3/3Q4/PPP1N1PP/1K1R3R w - - 9 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Qb3  but then  17...a5!  is the problem.  18.fxe6  a4!  and the Queen has to leave the diagonal. @@StartFEN@@1k1r2r1/1p1bbp1p/p2ppp2/2q2P2/2B1P3/3Q4/PPP1N1PP/1K1R3R w - - 9 17@@EndFEN@@  17.fxe6  would be a reasonable choice, after  17...fxe6  18.Nf4  d5!  19.exd5  Rg4  we can then go  20.d6  Rxf4  21.dxe7  Qxe7  22.g3  with a small advantage but it's also clear that Black is quite solid. Therefore, I prefer this quiet improving move. }
16... h5 { This move is logical enough to consider it. } 17. Ne2 exf5
{ 17...Rhg8  would no longer do the trick.  18.Qb3!  and White is threatening both fxe6 and Bxa6 while not being afraid of  18...a5  as the Queen has the a2-square at her disposal − a2-a3 paid off! }
18. Bxf7 fxe4 19. Qxe4 Qe5 { Otherwise, White would be clearly better. } 20.
Bd5 Qxe4 21. Bxe4 f5 22. Bf3
{ Despite the limited material, White keeps a small advantage, as all of Black's Pawns are weak. We have a nice f4-square for the Knight, we can also bring the King's Rook to e1, or try Rd1-d4-b4, targeting the b7-Pawn. }
