6... e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O Bd7
{ Black is delaying the development of the Kingside, focusing on the Queenside instead. Historically,  9.f4  has been the main continuation here. However, in recent years, it became clear that Black is doing well in more than one way. Therefore, the attention has shifted  towards f2-f3 setups. }
9. f3
{ I haven't noticed any difference between this and  9.f4  . Both moves lead to the same positions, so the move order can be arbitrary. Keeping  the e4-Pawn strong is the cornerstone of this line, it will guarantee us control in the center. }
9... b5
{ This move is the second most popular one in the position but in my opinion, it is inaccurate. The general rule is that Black should not touch the b7-Pawn without taking on d4 first. }
10. Nxc6
{ And this is the reason: we leave the d4-square for the other Knight. } 10...
Bxc6 11. Kb1 { The immediate  11.Ne2  was also possible. } 11... Be7 12. h4
