6... e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O Bd7
{ Black is delaying the development of the Kingside, focusing on the Queenside instead. Historically,  9.f4  has been the main continuation here. However, in recent years, it became clear that Black is doing well in more than one way. Therefore, the attention has shifted  towards f2-f3 setups. }
9. f3
{ I haven't noticed any difference between this and  9.f4  . Both moves lead to the same positions, so the move order can be arbitrary. Keeping  the e4-Pawn strong is the cornerstone of this line, it will guarantee us control in the center. }
9... Nxd4
{ The latest try. Black is dragging our Queen to d4, so now Nc3-e2-d4 will be harder to achieve. }
10. Qxd4 Be7 11. Kb1 { Avoiding any future tricks with ...Nf6xe4. } 11... Qc7
{ Black is anticipating our plan  12.g4  @@StartBracket@@which is another try here@@EndBracket@@. This will now be met with  12...h5!  13.gxh5  Nxh5!  since after  14.Bxe7  , Black can just recapture with the King. }
12. h4 { This is why I prefer pushing the h-Pawn instead. } 12... b5 13. Qd2
{ Making space for the Knight. } 13... h6
{ Not a very popular move, but it has been played by some great players, and it is also the engine's recommendation.   Castling short  13...O-O  would run into the typical  14.e5  dxe5  15.Bxf6  Bxf6  16.Qxd7  with a winning position for White. }
14. Be3 h5 { Stopping our g2-Pawn. } 15. Bd3
{ This is more accurate than  15.Ne2  a5  16.Nd4  Rb8! } 15... b4 16. Ne2 a5
17. Rc1
{ It is less about preparing c4 @@StartBracket@@or c3!@@EndBracket@@ and more about waiting for Black to castle. After the immediate  17.c4  e5!  18.Ng3  g6  ,  it seems okay as Black will manage to regroup the pieces in time with ...Bd7-e6 and ...Nf6-d7.  The other move that I like here is @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/2qbbpp1/3ppn2/p6p/1p2P2P/3BBP2/PPPQN1P1/1K1R3R w kq - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Bg5  . }
17... O-O 18. c4
{ I believe that White is slightly better and certainly the position will be easier to handle. We can bring the Knight to d4, the Bishop to g5, and then, apart from targetting the d6-Pawn, we can also consider the bold g2-g4 if the conditions are good. One move we should definitely watch out for is ...d6-d5. }
