[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ This natural move does not yet commit Black to any specific ideas. Black keeps both ...e7-e6 and ...e7-e5 on the table, just like in the Najdorf. }
6. Bg5
{ This is widely considered to be the most challenging continuation. White wants to castle long and developing the Bishop to g5 first is the best way to do it. We should note that after both  6.Be3  Ng4  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.f3  e5  , Black benefits from developing the  Knight to c6 instead of putting the Pawn on a6. }
6... e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O Bd7
{ Black is delaying the development of the Kingside, focusing on the Queenside instead. Historically,  9.f4  has been the main continuation here. However, in recent years, it became clear that Black is doing well in more than one way. Therefore, the attention has shifted  towards f2-f3 setups. }
9. f3
{ I haven't noticed any difference between this and  9.f4  . Both moves lead to the same positions, so the move order can be arbitrary. Keeping  the e4-Pawn strong is the cornerstone of this line, it will guarantee us control in the center. }
9... Be7
{ This is by far the most popular move in the position, however, I am not a big fan of it. }
10. Nxc6 { Once again, we will vacate the d4-square for the c3-Knight. } 10...
Bxc6 11. Kb1 h6 { Black is trying to live without ...b7-b5. } 12. Be3 Qc7
{ This waiting strategy is quite typical for the f3-Rauzers. Black is afraid of castling too early but, at the same time, Black doesn't have the means to strike in the center. Hence, the strategy is to make as many useful moves @@StartBracket@@...Qc7, ...Rc8 or ...b5@@EndBracket@@ as possible, before making a big decision. }
13. h4
{ It is a sort of nuance. The immediate  13.Ne2  O-O!  14.Nd4  Rfd8  was not so clear, although White seemed pleasant anyway. After our choice, castling is not really an option. @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/1pq1bpp1/p1bppn1p/8/4P2P/2N1BP2/PPPQ2P1/1K1R1B1R b kq - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...O-O?  14.g4  would give White a very strong attack. @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/1pq1bpp1/p1bppn1p/8/4P2P/2N1BP2/PPPQ2P1/1K1R1B1R b kq - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...d5  would once again be met with  14.e5  since the Pawn is poisoned.  14...Qxe5??  15.Bf4  Qh5  16.g4  would win a Knight at least. }
13... b5 14. Ne2 { With the black Pawn on b5, this plan works best. } 14... Nd7
15. Nd4 Bb7
{ After  15...Rc8  , White would just continue with  16.g4  . The text move allows Black to meet @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/1bqnbpp1/p2pp2p/1p6/3NP2P/4BP2/PPPQ2P1/1K1R1B1R w kq - 4 16@@EndFEN@@  16.g4  with  16...d5! }
16. c4
{ A novelty and actually quite a strong. This idea is not often seen in the Rauzer but I remember that during my work on this course, I had seen it at least three or four times, so it is not that unique. White intends to take control over the c-file. }
16... bxc4 17. Bxc4
{ That's a nice @@StartBracket@@and useful@@EndBracket@@ trick!  17...Qxc4?  would lose the Queen after  18.Rc1  . }
17... d5
{ The only way for Black to put up a fight.  17...O-O  18.Rc1  Nc5  19.g4  would be clearly better for White. }
18. Bxd5
{ It is just too nice not to play it! The calm  18.Bb3  was much softer but also a good try to fight for an advantage. }
18... exd5 19. Nf5
{ The point of the sacrifice. The Pawns on d5 and g7 are hanging and Black can't castle. }
19... Bf6
{ This move is perfectly natural but it has one problem: it doesn't work tactically. }
20. Rc1 Qb8 21. Qb4 { White is threatening Nd6+. } 21... a5
{ 21...Bc6  22.Qa3!  wouldn't help Black at all. } 22. Qxb7
{ With this simple tactic, White wins back the piece keeping a healthy Pawn up. After  22...O-O  , we can just swap the Queens and defend  the b2-Pawn by moving the Rook to c2. }
