1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ The Dragon Variation is one of the most colorful lines in chess, even by Sicilian standards. It involves so many important tactical motifs that one simply has to study it if taking chess seriously. Exchange sacrifices on c3, vigorous Pawn attacks, unexpected strikes in the center − it's all there.  If I am not mistaken, it was Mikhail Botvinnik who once said that every chess player has to play at least thirty games in the Dragon. Today, these classical motifs are somewhat detached from the theory. With precise play, White simply doesn't allow Black to execute them, taking most of the fun away. That is exactly what we are about to do. }
6. Be3 Nc6 { This move order does not necessarily have to be accidental. } 7.
f3 h5
{ Preventing g2-g4 is one idea but connect ...h7-h5 with the Bishop on f8 and you might sense Black's intentions: ...Bh6! This clever idea has been recently used by Richard Rapport. }
8. Bc4
{ Useful nuance − Black is waiting for us to move the Queen to d2 in order to take on d4 and then bring the Bishop to h6. Let them wait for a bit longer. }
8... Bd7 9. Qd2 Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Bh6 { There it is. } 11. Qf2 O-O 12. O-O
{ A bit unusual for our Dragon but it's OK. White's pieces are clearly better placed than Black's. After  12...Rc8  , we can just retreat the  Bishop to b3 and then bring the Queen's Rook to d1. We can always consider taking the Knight on f6 as the Bishop pair will not be enough compensation for the damaged Pawn structure. }
