[Round "?"]
[White "5. Dragon 5.Nc3 g6"]
[Black "Dragon 6.Be3 Bg7 7.f3 O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ The Dragon Variation is one of the most colorful lines in chess, even by Sicilian standards. It involves so many important tactical motifs that one simply has to study it if taking chess seriously. Exchange sacrifices on c3, vigorous Pawn attacks, unexpected strikes in the center − it's all there.  If I am not mistaken, it was Mikhail Botvinnik who once said that every chess player has to play at least thirty games in the Dragon. Today, these classical motifs are somewhat detached from the theory. With precise play, White simply doesn't allow Black to execute them, taking most of the fun away. That is exactly what we are about to do. }
6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2 d5
{ Even though the move is a huge mistake, I think it is quite important. Black does challenge our position after all. }
9. e5 Nfd7 10. f4
{ Black is just too slow to successfully undermine our Pawn center. } 10... Nc6
11. O-O-O Nb6 12. Be2
{ White has finished development and also prevented ...Bc8-g4. } 12... f6
{ 12...e6  would be too slow.  13.h4  f6  14.h5!  and Black's position is collapsing. }
13. exf6 Bxf6 14. h4 { Now Black should at least try to put up a fight. } 14...
e5 15. Nxc6 { 15.fxe5  would allow  15...Nxe5  ,  threatening ...Nb6-c4. }
15... bxc6 16. fxe5 Bxe5 17. h5
{ White's attack is too strong. We want to take on g6 and then bring a Rook to h6. If Black avoids getting mated, it will not be without material consequences. }
