[White "5. Dragon 5.Nc3 g6"]
[Black "Dragon 7.f3 Nc6 − 9.O-O-O Bd7 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ The Dragon Variation is one of the most colorful lines in chess, even by Sicilian standards. It involves so many important tactical motifs that one simply has to study it if taking chess seriously. Exchange sacrifices on c3, vigorous Pawn attacks, unexpected strikes in the center − it's all there.  If I am not mistaken, it was Mikhail Botvinnik who once said that every chess player has to play at least thirty games in the Dragon. Today, these classical motifs are somewhat detached from the theory. With precise play, White simply doesn't allow Black to execute them, taking most of the fun away. That is exactly what we are about to do. }
6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O
{ Why not  9.Bc4?  The answer is simple: this is what Black is hoping for. The amount of theory is overwhelming and the final verdict is not as good as one would expect. This makes it rather difficult for White from a practical point of view. Our choice is simple and very unpleasant for Black. No wonder it has been the most popular continuation on the top level for quite some time already. }
9... Bd7
{ It is understandable that Black might not like the ...d6-d5 lines, but with the Bishop on f1, this plan is just too slow. }
10. g4 { White has the luxury of starting with this, preventing ...h7-h5. }
10... Rc8 11. Kb1
{ It is always good to remove the King from the c-file once the Black's Rook has taken it. }
11... Ne5 { Black is playing as if it was the main line. } 12. Be2
{ The most accurate, although  12.h4  would be also great. The point of White's last move is that  we want to play h2-h4 and after ...h7-h5, take on h5 followed by f3-f4, which works better with the Bishop on e2. }
12... Nc4 { I don't think there was any reasonable alternative. } 13. Bxc4 Rxc4
{ This is the 9.Bc4 Dragon main line a tempo up for White, just count the Bishop moves! As usual in sharp positions, one tempo is all it takes... }
14. h4 h5 { This is how Black usually tries to stop White's attack. } 15. gxh5
Nxh5 16. Rhg1
{ Played with a simple and deadly threat: Rg1-g5xh5. The other idea is to use the Knights: Nd4-e2, Nc3-d5, and then one of the Knights will come to f4, eliminating Black's crucial defender. White's position is already close to winning. }
