6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O
{ Why not  9.Bc4?  The answer is simple: this is what Black is hoping for. The amount of theory is overwhelming and the final verdict is not as good as one would expect. This makes it rather difficult for White from a practical point of view. Our choice is simple and very unpleasant for Black. No wonder it has been the most popular continuation on the top level for quite some time already. }
9... d5
{ The critical continuation which makes sense − by skipping Bf1-c4, White saved time but also allowed ...d6-d5. }
10. exd5
{ For a long time  10.Qe1  was considered the main continuation. However, currently Black seems to be doing okay in that line, so the attention has moved to our choice. }
10... Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bd4
{ White's approach is very simple: we want to neutralize Black's activity and then our superior Pawn structure will tell. Also, Black is going to experience some real problems with finding a place for the light-squared Bishop. }
12... e5 { The most popular move, but, in my opinion, not the best one. } 13.
Bc5
{ What we have is an improved version of the @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2n2np1/3p4/3NP3/2N1BP2/PPPQ2PP/2KR1B1R w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Qe1  line.  With the Queen on d2, White doesn't need to worry about ...Bg7-h6+ or ...Qd8-g5+, which limits Black's options for the next moves. }
13... Re8 14. Ne4 Qc7
{ This specific move order allows us to reach a very pleasant endgame.  14...Be6  transposes to the 13...Be6 line. }
15. h4 h5 { A natural reply but it doesn't work tactically. } 16. g4
{ Black has no good response.  16...hxg4  17.h5  gives White a crushing attack while @@StartFEN@@r1b1r1k1/p1q2pb1/2p3p1/2Bnp2p/4N1PP/5P2/PPPQ4/2KR1B1R b - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...f5  shall be met with  17.Nd6  . }
