Rd6 Kg7 26. b4 { The calmer  26.c3  is also possible. } 26... Bf4
{ The best reply − Black is threatening ...e5-e4. } 27. Re6 Rb7 28. a3 a5 29.
Kb2
{ This is stronger than  29.c3  a4!  and it is not  easy to win the a4-Pawn. }
29... axb4 30. a4
{ A rather typical Pawn sacrifice but it doesn't make it any weaker! } 30...
Ra7 31. Kb3
{ After  31...c5  , we can go  32.Bb5  . Black is tied to defending and White has many ways of improving as the King can be easily activated  via c4. Also, we should not ignore the possibility of swapping the Rooks. With the Pawns on b4 and c5, Black's Bishop might not be able to stop our a4-Pawn! All this was played in the game between Dariusz Swiercz and Daniel Naroditsky in the US Championship, St. Louis 2021. White won convincingly that game. }
