{ White's approach is very simple: we want to neutralize Black's activity and then our superior Pawn structure will tell. Also, Black is going to experience some real problems with finding a place for the light-squared Bishop. }
12... e5 { The most popular move, but, in my opinion, not the best one. } 13.
Bc5
{ What we have is an improved version of the @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2n2np1/3p4/3NP3/2N1BP2/PPPQ2PP/2KR1B1R w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Qe1  line.  With the Queen on d2, White doesn't need to worry about ...Bg7-h6+ or ...Qd8-g5+, which limits Black's options for the next moves. }
13... Be6
{ Setting up a small trap:  14.Bxf8?  Qxf8  has already proven to be clearly better for Black as due to the ...Bg7-h6 threat, White has no time to develop the Bishop. This is critical for the evaluation as without the Bishop on c4, Black's attack is deadly. }
14. Ne4
{ 14.Bc4?  would blunder  14...Nxc3  15.Qxc3  Qg5+  and once again Black is better. }
14... Rb8 { Aggressive but incorrect. } 15. Bc4
{ Black didn't achieve anything with ...Ra8-b8 while White will manage to achieve everything we needed. }
15... f5
{ The only practical chance as  15...Re8  16.g4!  would leave Black without any counterplay in a terrible situation. }
16. Ng5 Bh6
{ Such moves can be only strong when bringing specific benefits, otherwise, the Bishop is simply misplaced on h6. }
17. h4 { No benefits in this case. } 17... Rf7 18. Rhe1
{ It might not seem this dramatic but White already has a winning advantage. After  18...Qc7  , we can continue with  19.g3  followed by f3-f4. }
