15... h5
{ This is objectively stronger than  15...h6  , but by no means satisfactory for Black. }
16. Bc4 Nf4
{ The endgame will be better for White, but Black is going to have decent drawing chances as the Pawn on h4 is potentially weak. }
17. Bxe6 Nxe6 { We don't need to trade Queens now. } 18. Qc3 Qc7
{ A natural retreat. Black now wants to take on c5 so White has to act. } 19.
g4
{ This is stronger than  19.Bd6  Qb7  and  20.Bxe5  can be met with  20...Nf4  . }
19... Nxc5 20. Qxc5 Qb6
{ Naturally, Black can't just allow us to attack the King. } 21. g5
{ Putting the Pawns on the same color as the opponent's Bishop is generally a risky strategy in the endgames. Here, however, we effectively shut down the Kingside while the Knight will control all the important squares, preventing Black from activating the Bishop. }
21... Qxc5 22. Nxc5 Rad8
{ There was no time for  22...f6  as after  23.gxf6  Bxf6  24.Ne4  , the Rook would enter the 7th rank. }
23. Ne4 Kf8 24. Rde1
{ This is a very important nuance. One Rook is going to operate on the 3rd rank while another one shall be placed on e1 keeping the center under control. White has a long-term advantage as we will be able to target Black's weaknesses. We should in general be avoiding Rook trades as our Rooks have many files on which they can operate. Black's Rooks are not that effective. }
