{ The Dragon Variation is one of the most colorful lines in chess, even by Sicilian standards. It involves so many important tactical motifs that one simply has to study it if taking chess seriously. Exchange sacrifices on c3, vigorous Pawn attacks, unexpected strikes in the center − it's all there.  If I am not mistaken, it was Mikhail Botvinnik who once said that every chess player has to play at least thirty games in the Dragon. Today, these classical motifs are somewhat detached from the theory. With precise play, White simply doesn't allow Black to execute them, taking most of the fun away. That is exactly what we are about to do. }
6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O
{ Why not  9.Bc4?  The answer is simple: this is what Black is hoping for. The amount of theory is overwhelming and the final verdict is not as good as one would expect. This makes it rather difficult for White from a practical point of view. Our choice is simple and very unpleasant for Black. No wonder it has been the most popular continuation on the top level for quite some time already. }
9... d5
{ The critical continuation which makes sense − by skipping Bf1-c4, White saved time but also allowed ...d6-d5. }
10. exd5
{ For a long time  10.Qe1  was considered the main continuation. However, currently Black seems to be doing okay in that line, so the attention has moved to our choice. }
