{ White's approach is very simple: we want to neutralize Black's activity and then our superior Pawn structure will tell. Also, Black is going to experience some real problems with finding a place for the light-squared Bishop. }
12... Bxd4
{ This might be the toughest line objectively, but in my opinion, it will never become the main line. It is simply too unpleasant for Black. }
13. Qxd4 Qc7
{ Of course, Black would be happy to sacrifice the c6-Pawn, opening up another file on the Queenside. }
14. h4
{ White has a simple plan on the h-file.  14.Bc4  e5  15.Qd2  is another good option. }
14... Bf5
{ Not very human, but Black wants to provoke g2-g4 as it creates a weakness on f3. }
15. g4 Be6 16. Nxd5
{ Now  16.h5  wouldn't work well:  16...Rad8  17.hxg6  fxg6!  and Black has decent counterplay on the f-file. }
16... Bxd5 17. h5
{ The simple  17.Be2  is also possible but this is more direct. } 17... Bxf3
18. hxg6 fxg6
{ 18...Bxh1??  19.gxh7+  Kxh7  20.Bd3+  Kg8  21.Rxh1  would win too easily. }
19. Bc4+ { The next moves are forced. } 19... Bd5 20. Bxd5+ cxd5 21. Qxd5+ Kg7
22. Rde1
{ White is clearly better, Black has weaknesses all over the place. We can put one Rook on e4 and then double on the e-file, while Qd5-d2 is also unpleasant. }
