1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ The Dragon Variation is one of the most colorful lines in chess, even by Sicilian standards. It involves so many important tactical motifs that one simply has to study it if taking chess seriously. Exchange sacrifices on c3, vigorous Pawn attacks, unexpected strikes in the center − it's all there.  If I am not mistaken, it was Mikhail Botvinnik who once said that every chess player has to play at least thirty games in the Dragon. Today, these classical motifs are somewhat detached from the theory. With precise play, White simply doesn't allow Black to execute them, taking most of the fun away. That is exactly what we are about to do. }
6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O
{ Why not  9.Bc4?  The answer is simple: this is what Black is hoping for. The amount of theory is overwhelming and the final verdict is not as good as one would expect. This makes it rather difficult for White from a practical point of view. Our choice is simple and very unpleasant for Black. No wonder it has been the most popular continuation on the top level for quite some time already. }
9... d5
{ The critical continuation which makes sense − by skipping Bf1-c4, White saved time but also allowed ...d6-d5. }
10. exd5
{ For a long time  10.Qe1  was considered the main continuation. However, currently Black seems to be doing okay in that line, so the attention has moved to our choice. }
10... Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bd4
{ White's approach is very simple: we want to neutralize Black's activity and then our superior Pawn structure will tell. Also, Black is going to experience some real problems with finding a place for the light-squared Bishop. }
12... Bxd4
{ This might be the toughest line objectively, but in my opinion, it will never become the main line. It is simply too unpleasant for Black. }
13. Qxd4 Qb6
{ The most popular continuation. Black is okay to trade Queens for as long as it would fix the Pawns. }
14. Na4 { Naturally, White is not going to cooperate. } 14... Qc7
{ This is how they usually play. Now White has a number of similar continuations and most of them are quite promising. }
15. g3
{ This quiet move is relatively unknown and therefore, you are more than likely to surprise your opponent with it. Taking control over the f4-square is useful. Also @@StartBracket@@compared with  15.Nc5  @@EndBracket@@, White  keeps the c5-square unoccupied − it can be taken by both the Knight and the Queen.   15.Bc4  , which is the most popular move in the position, is also promising, though I wasn't sure about  15...Nb6  . }
15... Nb6
{ I don't think there is a single case where we take on b6 and definitely this won't be an exception. }
16. Nc3
{ Quite original but it has a point. Usually, the Knight is sitting on c5, but then the Queen has to retreat. With the Knight on c3, the Queen can take the c5-square. Additionally, the Knight controls the important d5-square. }
16... Be6
{ A natural move but the problem is that Black does not anticipate our plan. }
17. Qc5 { Achieving a perfect setup. } 17... Rfd8 18. Be2
{ It is already clear that Black is worse. We want to bring the Rook to e1 and then just push f3-f4. Notice that Black can't swap both Rooks as the Queen has to defend the c6-Pawn. }
18... Nd5 19. Nxd5
{ Sure, we have no objections now as the Pawn structure will remain unchanged. }
19... Bxd5 20. Rd3
{ This is stronger than  20.Rd2  as now the Rook can operate on the 3rd rank. }
20... Qb6 21. Rc3
{ 21.Qxe7??  Re8  would be a bad idea. White has a nice advantage thanks to the superior Pawn structure. We shall bring another Rook  to d1 and then, even with the Queens on the board, we can consider advancing the Pawns on the Queenside. a2-a4, b2-b3 is a very good setup but a2-a4-a5 would be a perfect one. In this case, even with the Queens on the board, b2-b4 is not impossible. }
