12... Bxd4
{ This might be the toughest line objectively, but in my opinion, it will never become the main line. It is simply too unpleasant for Black. }
13. Qxd4 Qb6
{ The most popular continuation. Black is okay to trade Queens for as long as it would fix the Pawns. }
14. Na4 { Naturally, White is not going to cooperate. } 14... Qc7
{ This is how they usually play. Now White has a number of similar continuations and most of them are quite promising. }
15. g3
{ This quiet move is relatively unknown and therefore, you are more than likely to surprise your opponent with it. Taking control over the f4-square is useful. Also @@StartBracket@@compared with  15.Nc5  @@EndBracket@@, White  keeps the c5-square unoccupied − it can be taken by both the Knight and the Queen.   15.Bc4  , which is the most popular move in the position, is also promising, though I wasn't sure about  15...Nb6  . }
15... Nb6
{ I don't think there is a single case where we take on b6 and definitely this won't be an exception. }
16. Nc3
{ Quite original but it has a point. Usually, the Knight is sitting on c5, but then the Queen has to retreat. With the Knight on c3, the Queen can take the c5-square. Additionally, the Knight controls the important d5-square. }
16... c5
{ Black is using the opportunity to push the Pawn to the dark square. However, it has downsides too: the Pawn is weak on c5 while our Knight on c3 has just gained another square: b5. }
17. Qe3 { Keeping an eye on both c5 and e7. } 17... Be6
{ This is cliche − usually, the Bishop comes to e6 because there is no choice. }
18. h4
{ With Black's forces not making any contact with ours, the conditions are perfect for the attack. }
18... Rad8 { 18...Qxg3?  19.h5  and White's attack is too fast. } 19. Rxd8
{ Who needs the d-file when we have the h-file. ;-@@EndBracket@@ } 19... Rxd8
20. h5 { Risky but we should know how to react. } 20... Qxg3 21. hxg6 hxg6 22.
Bd3 { Covering both the d-file and the back rank. Now, Qh6 is a real threat. }
22... Nd5 { The only move. } 23. Nxd5 Rxd5
{ This is Black's hope:  24.Qh6?  is now pointless due to  24...Qg5+  . } 24.
Bxg6
{ Using this simple tactic, White wins the Pawn back while keeping the attack. }
24... Rg5
{ 24...Qg5  would be met with  25.Bh7+!  Kf8  26.f4  − no Queen trade. } 25.
Be4
{ Almost everything in Black's position is weak. Obviously, the King is still weak while the Queenside Pawns are easy targets too. First, though, we should hide our King so b2-b3 and Kc1-b2 is the plan. }
