[Black "Keres Attack 6.g4 Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen Variation is a great system, but mostly for educational reasons. One should simply study the structure and play some games with it. However, at least in this move order, it is not really playable. }
6. g4
{ If Black develops the pieces as if nothing happened, White will quickly build a strong attack. This is a good example. }
6... Nc6 7. g5 Nd7 8. Be3 Be7 9. h4
{ 9.Rg1  followed  by Rg1-g3 is also possible. The idea of placing the Rook on the 3rd rank will be discussed in more detail in the next line. }
9... O-O 10. Be2
{ It is good to start with this.  10.Qd2  Nde5!  and Black is  threatening ...Ne5-g4.  Now after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1nbppp/2npp3/6P1/3NP2P/2N1B3/PPP1BP2/R2QK2R b KQ - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nde5  , we can chase it away with  11.f4  . }
10... a6 11. f4 Nxd4
{ With the Queen on d2, it is always a hard choice, but if the Queen is still on d1, we should just take with the Queen. }
12. Qxd4 b5 13. O-O-O { We will push the h-Pawn. White has a great advantage. }
