[Black "Keres Attack 6.g4 e5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen Variation is a great system, but mostly for educational reasons. One should simply study the structure and play some games with it. However, at least in this move order, it is not really playable. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is by far the most dangerous weapon against the Scheveningen and the main reason for Black to stay away from the whole system. Since Black has not put any pressure on the center yet, White can afford to push the Pawn aggressively.  If you compare it with the 6.h3 Najdorf, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  a6  6.h3  e6  7.g4  ,  White saved a tempo by skipping h2-h3 completely. What's more important in the opening than a tempo? }
6... e5
{ A pretty important line because, unlike the other ones, we actually need to know a few moves. }
7. Nf5 { Stronger than  7.Bb5+  . We now want to bring the  Bishop to g5. }
7... h5 { Black is ready to meet  8.g5?!  with  8...Nxe4! } 8. Bg5
{ Now White, once again, wins control over the d5-square. } 8... hxg4 9. Nd5
Bxf5 10. Bxf6 { 10.exf5?  Qa5+!  and the Knight has to come back. } 10... gxf6
11. exf5
{ With such a dominant Knight, we just have to be better here, and the Bishop will also be great on g2. }
11... Nc6 12. c3
{ An all-around good positional move, which, short-term, prevents a check on a5 in case we take on g4, and long term, it takes away the d4-square from the c6-Knight. }
12... Bh6
{ Now we can just take the Pawn as Black is too late with ...Bh6-g5, which would be strongly met by h4. }
13. Qxg4
{ White has a winning advantage. We can bring the Rook to d1 and fianchetto the Bishop. }
