1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ The Scheveningen Variation is a great system, but mostly for educational reasons. One should simply study the structure and play some games with it. However, at least in this move order, it is not really playable. }
6. g4
{ The Keres Attack is by far the most dangerous weapon against the Scheveningen and the main reason for Black to stay away from the whole system. Since Black has not put any pressure on the center yet, White can afford to push the Pawn aggressively.  If you compare it with the 6.h3 Najdorf, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  a6  6.h3  e6  7.g4  ,  White saved a tempo by skipping h2-h3 completely. What's more important in the opening than a tempo? }
6... h6 { The best response − Black slows down our attack. } 7. Rg1 g5
{ The classical approach − Black is fighting for the dark squares. This plan is not doing very well in the computer era. Black's King is weak and White learned many new ways of exploiting it. }
8. h4 { We could also start with  8.Be3  but I see no reason to delay this. }
8... gxh4 { Not the best moment for Pawn consumption. } 9. g5 hxg5 10. Bxg5
{ I guess Black won't be castling short anymore. :-@@EndBracket@@ } 10... Be7
11. Qd2
{ White has an enormous advantage. We will castle long and then either bring the Bishop to h3 or try Qd2-e3, threatening e4-e5. The h4-Pawn doesn't matter. }
