3... g6 4. Bxc6 dxc6
{ I must admit that this was one of the hardest lines to cover. Not because of the amount of theory or my inability to find a good response, but because it is difficult to comprehend. Black has many typical moves: ...b7-b6, ...h7-h6, ...Nf6-d7, ...Nf6-Ne8, ...Qd8-c7.  These moves can be used in various orders, and although the positions usually remain almost identical, it is difficult to present them in variation form. Therefore, I tried to be more relaxed, especially since my general feeling was that no matter what we do, Black's position remains a bit uncomfortable, mainly because of the inferior Pawn structure. }
5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 Nh6 { A dubious line. } 7. a4
{ This is very clever − we are threatening a4-a5, but what we really want is that Black stops us. }
7... a5 8. Be3
{ This was not so strong on the previous move, but now that the b6-square is weak, it is just brilliant. }
8... Bxb2
{ Funnily enough, the engines believe that the best move for Black is  8...Ng8  back. We are not going to check it, sorry. }
9. Nbd2 Ng8 10. Rb1 Bd4 { 10...Bg7  11.Bxc5  would be equally bad for Black. }
11. Bxd4 cxd4 12. Qc1
{ The most accurate way.  12.Nb3  c5  13.Nxc5  is also nice, although Black would play  13...Qc7  14.Nb3  e5  , with some chances for surviving. }
12... c5
{ 12...Nf6  13.Nb3  and the difference with the Queen on c1 instead of d1 is that after  13...c5  14.Nxc5  Qc7  15.Nb3  e5  , White has  16.Qa3  . }
13. Nc4 Qc7 14. O-O Be6 15. Na3
{ Although we didn't win the Pawn back, our position is probably just winning. We have so many good moves like Na3-b5, Qc1-d2, Nf3-g5, and Black can't even castle as after ...Ng8-f6 we can bring the Queen to h6. }
