3... g6 4. Bxc6 dxc6
{ I must admit that this was one of the hardest lines to cover. Not because of the amount of theory or my inability to find a good response, but because it is difficult to comprehend. Black has many typical moves: ...b7-b6, ...h7-h6, ...Nf6-d7, ...Nf6-Ne8, ...Qd8-c7.  These moves can be used in various orders, and although the positions usually remain almost identical, it is difficult to present them in variation form. Therefore, I tried to be more relaxed, especially since my general feeling was that no matter what we do, Black's position remains a bit uncomfortable, mainly because of the inferior Pawn structure. }
5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 b6
{ Quite a clever move order as Black doesn't yet reveal the intentions. We normally like to delay castling for a bit @@StartBracket@@also, in some cases, the long castle plans are possible@@EndBracket@@ so we develop the Knight first. However, here, after  7.Nc3  e5!  is strong.   You have already seen the 6...e5 line so you know that the best reaction for White is to prepare b2-b4. The Bishop should go to e3, the Queen's Knight to c4, and the Pawns: a2-a3 and b2-b4. The correct move order is a technical matter. With the Knight on c3, this plan doesn't work so well.    8.Be3  Ne7  9.a3  f5!  and Black is quickly grabbing counterplay. Intuitively, one might think that in  case of ...f7-f5, it is better to have the Knight on c3 as the Bishop is not endangered. However, once the Pawn is on f5, we often want to move the Knight to c4 and the Bishop to c3. }
7. O-O Nf6
{ Now we will be be facing one of the two maneuvers ...Nd7-f8-e6 or ...Ne8-c7-e6. }
8. Re1
{ Actually, I believe this is quite an important nuance. The fact that White has already castled gives Black additional opportunities. If we continue normally with  8.Nc3  Nd7  9.Be3  Nf8  10.Qd2  , then instead of  10...h6  @@StartBracket@@transposing to our lines@@EndBracket@@, Black could try  10...Ne6!?  11.Bh6  Bf6!  having ...g6-g5 ideas in mind. This was indeed played once by a big Rossolimo expert, GM Rauf Mamedov, and a couple of times by IM Nataliya Buksa, who happens to be his wife. }
8... Nd7 9. e5 { This is why we placed the Rook on e1. } 9... Nf8 10. a4 a5 11.
Qe2 Ne6 12. Qe4
{ We will move the Knight to c4, while Qe4-h4 and Bc1-h6 look good. White has a long-term advantage as Black is struggling to find some active plan. }
*

