{ Now, after  22...Kd7  23.d4!  Qe4  24.Qg3  , Black's position will collapse. }
22... Qd6 23. Bf4 Qd7 24. Ng4
{ I guess it will collapse anyway.  24...fxg4  25.Qxg4  and we will win the piece back, but @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/p2q2b1/1pp1b1p1/2p2p2/2P2BN1/3P1Q1P/PP4P1/4RRK1 b kq - 6 24@@EndFEN@@  24...O-O-O  25.Ne5  Bxe5  26.Rxe5  would be a positional disaster for Black.  The problems manifest themselves after, for example,  26...Rde8  27.Rfe1  Bf7  when  28.Re7  is already better for White, but  28.b4!  would be more accurate. The subtle nuance will be revealed soon:  28...cxb4  and only now  29.Re7  Rxe7  30.Rxe7  Qxe7  31.Qxc6+  Kd8  32.Qa8+  Kd7  33.Qxa7+  Ke8  34.Qb8+  Qd8  35.Qe5+  Kd7  when compared to 28.Re7, White is no longer blocked by the Pawn on c5 and can deliver the deadly check  36.Qb5+  .  Black is unable to avoid mate or the loss of Queen. }
