[White "8. Rossolimo 2. Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 g6 4.Bxc6 dxc6"]
[Black "Rossolimo 4.Bxc6 dxc6 − 6.h3 Nf6 #16"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Perhaps I should start with some explanations on why would we choose Bb5 against ...Nc6. Surely, you will find many repertoires that involve a Bb5 setup, for instance, in the Sicilian with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.Bb5+  or, as is the case here, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  3.Bb5  . You will also find a lot of repertoires where the attention shifts to  3.d4  instead.  I wanted to be as flexible as possible and my goal was to suggest the most challenging solution. The sad truth is that the Sveshnikov Variation is not posing Black serious problems at the moment, which shouldn't come as a surprise, as there aren't many topical games in this opening anymore. On the few occasions when White does go for the Sveshnikov, we will witness some boring draw, unless Black simply forgets the line. Besides the fact that White ran out of ideas, modern engines revealed that Black is okay in more than one way.  The Rossolimo though still has some poison in it, and this is also the trend at top-level chess. There are many games played by very strong GMs and it would be a shame to not include it in your repertoire based on the mere fact that you might go for 3.d4 in different lines.  We do have quite some work ahead though as we have to go through many lines, but I believe it is worth the effort and I am sure you will enjoy playing the Rossolimo with White. }
3... g6 4. Bxc6 dxc6
{ I must admit that this was one of the hardest lines to cover. Not because of the amount of theory or my inability to find a good response, but because it is difficult to comprehend. Black has many typical moves: ...b7-b6, ...h7-h6, ...Nf6-d7, ...Nf6-Ne8, ...Qd8-c7.  These moves can be used in various orders, and although the positions usually remain almost identical, it is difficult to present them in variation form. Therefore, I tried to be more relaxed, especially since my general feeling was that no matter what we do, Black's position remains a bit uncomfortable, mainly because of the inferior Pawn structure. }
5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 Nf6 { The most natural and the most popular move. } 7. Nc3 Nd7
{ This line is a little bit different as Black hasn't castled yet, which means that the black King can still move in both directions. }
8. Be3 e5
{ An important move as Black now fully controls the d4-square. Naturally, it does not come for free: the dark-squared Bishop is essential @@StartBracket@@covering the dark squares@@EndBracket@@ and passive too. }
9. Qd2 h6 10. O-O b6
{ The new main line − it is not a new plan though, just a more precise execution. }
11. Nh2 Nf8 12. f4 exf4 13. Bxf4 Ne6 14. Be3
{ I think it's a better try than  14.Bg3  Qg5  . } 14... Nd4 15. Rae1 Be6 16.
e5 { We cannot allow Black to build a solid blockade on the dark squares. }
16... Nf5 { This is how Black should play. } 17. Bf2 Qc7 18. Nf3 O-O-O
{ Both sides completed their developments and we can now stop for a moment and asses: Black's minor pieces are well placed but so are ours. There is also potential in our Rooks but let's agree that there is a relative balance in this regard. Both Kings are rather safe.  The Pawn structure is rather tricky: Black's Queenside Pawns are not that great and if Black is dreaming of ...c5-c4 then we will easily prevent it with b2-b3 @@StartBracket@@our next move@@EndBracket@@. Our e5-Pawn is sort of weak but on the other hand, it gives a lot of value to White's position. Black has weak d6 and f6-squares and can never win this Pawn without opening the h2-b8 diagonal, which would surely make our Bishop happy.  I think that White's position simply has more potential. We can bring the Knight to e4 and then even consider g2-g4. Yes, our King is safe enough to do it in more cases − just imagine Black's Knight chased away from f5, allowing our Bishop to move to g3. }
19. b3 Rhe8 20. a4 { It never hurts to do this. } 20... a5 21. Ne4
{ White is ready to advance the g2-Pawn. } 21... Bd5
{ One of the ways of anticipating our next move. } 22. g4 Nd4 23. Bxd4 Bxe4
{ 23...cxd4  24.Nd6+  . } 24. Rxe4 cxd4 25. Qf4
{ White is slightly better. We want to move the Rook from f1 to e1 and provoke ...c6-c5 this way. If we succeed, then we can bring the Knight to c4 and Black's problems may become quite serious. Black also has to watch out for the simple Re4xd4. In most of the endgames, Black will face some problems. }
*

