{ A logical reply. Black figures that having the Bishop pair, the position should be opened up completely. }
6. exd5 Qxd5 7. Nc3 { On the other hand, White now has some moves with tempo. }
7... Qc4 8. Qe2 Qxe2+ 9. Nxe2 f6
{ 9...cxd4  10.Nexd4  Bd7  11.Be3  f6  transposes. } 10. Be3
{ Now Black has a dilemma. If White takes the Pawn instead  10.dxc5  , then after  10...e5  11.Be3  Ne7  , the Knight will  come to d5, ensuring Black good compensation. }
10... Nh6
{ Black is sacrificing the Pawn in order to catch up with development. } 11.
dxc5 Nf5 { Black will also get rid of our Bishop. } 12. Nc3 Nxe3 13. fxe3 e5
{ Attacking the Pawn on c5. } 14. Ne4 { 14.Na4  Ba6  15.b4  Bb5  16.Nc3  a5! }
14... Bf5 15. Nfd2 Bxe4 16. Nxe4 f5 { Forcing another trade. } 17. Nd6+ Bxd6
18. cxd6 Kd7 19. O-O-O
{ A very interesting endgame. With accurate play, Black should be able to defend it, but I don't think it's simple. We want to double on the d-file and then activate one of the Rooks on the 3rd rank. }
