3... g6 4. Bxc6 bxc6 5. d4
{ I will give you one good reason why I think it's a good idea: half of your opponents will be out of book already! Those of you who are looking for quality rather than surprise − it's there too! By quickly advancing the central Pawn, White immediately challenges Black. }
5... cxd4 6. Qxd4 f6
{ A solid but passive approach. In general, I am not a fan of this setup. Black has the Bishop pair and Bishops like space. }
7. O-O d6 8. Be3
{ A novelty. Our point is explained in the following line:  8.c4  @@StartBracket@@the main and most natural move@@EndBracket@@  8...c5  and we can't  retreat the Queen to d2 without blocking the Bishop. }
8... e5 9. Qd3 d5
{ Black is trying to use the fact that our Pawn hasn't yet landed on c4. } 10.
Rd1 { However, now Black's Pawn center must be defended. } 10... Be6 11. exd5
cxd5 12. c4 { Black can win a piece in two ways. } 12... e4 13. Qd4 exf3 14.
cxd5 { Black is a piece up but the position is just wrong. } 14... Bf5
{ 14...Bd7  15.d6  would be easier. Black is basically paralyzed and we just have to develop our pieces. }
15. d6 Qd7 16. Nc3 Rd8 { Threatening to win our d6-Pawn. } 17. Ne4 Kf7
{ 17...Bxe4  wouldn't help.  18.Qxe4  Kf7  19.Rac1  Bxd6  20.Rc6!  and White wins. }
18. Rac1 Kg7 19. Rd3
{ White is threatening Rd3-c3-c7, which is slow but serious as Black's King doesn't really have any squares available. Black can go  19...g5  but then  20.h4  gxh4  21.gxf3  and the King is naked. White should be just winning. }
