5... Bg7 { The most solid continuation. } 6. dxc5 Qa5+
{ 6...Ba6?!  7.Nbd2  Qa5  8.Rb1  transposes. } 7. Nbd2 Qxc5 8. O-O d6 9. Re1
{ White is preparing e4-e5. } 9... Nf6 { The next few moves need no comments. }
10. Nb3 Qb6 11. e5 dxe5 12. Nxe5 O-O
{ This position has only appeared three times in practice, which to me is a clear sign that Black players simply don't want it. But can you blame them? Objectively, the line holds, but Black's Pawn structure is unpleasant enough to make it rather impractical. }
13. Qf3 { A new try. } 13... Bb7 14. Be3 { Now Black has a decision to make. }
14... c5
{ Black needs to activate the light-squared Bishop even at the cost of a Pawn. }
15. Bxc5 Qc7
{ Black has decent compensation for the Pawn, but White can still press. } 16.
Qe3 a5 { 16...Nd5  17.Qg3  . } 17. Bd4 { The best chance. } 17... Nd5 18. Qg3
f6 { The best move. } 19. c4 { Now things are getting tense. } 19... fxe5 20.
cxd5
{ Unless Black comes up with something extraordinary, White will be slightly better at least. }
20... a4 21. Nd2 a3
{ 21...Bxd5  22.Bxe5  Bxe5  23.Qxe5  would be just better for White. } 22. bxa3
Qc2
{ This is why Black had to get rid of the b2-Pawn first, we can't retreat the Bishop to c3. }
23. Be3 Bxd5 24. Rac1 Qxa2 25. Nb1
{ Perhaps it's a bit easier to play with White, but there is no need to pretend that we have any advantage. Black solved all the opening problems. }
*

