3... e6
{ This is a very rich continuation, and many positions are strategically complex. Some really strong grandmasters enjoy playing it regardless of its objective strength. }
4. Bxc6
{ White takes on c6 right away in order to damage Black's Pawn structure. }
4... bxc6 5. d3 d6 6. e5 { This is too simple... } 6... Ne7
{ If Black decides to live with doubled Pawns then this is the way to do it. It's certainly better than  6...dxe5  7.Nxe5  . }
7. exd6 Nf5 8. O-O Bxd6 9. Nc3 O-O 10. b3
{ White is better. We want to bring the Knight to e4 and then decide what to do with the Bishop. In most cases, Bc1-a3 should be fine. Black's dark-squared Bishop is not great but it is protecting the c5-Pawn so if we get a chance to swap it, we should at least consider it. }
