3... e6
{ This is a very rich continuation, and many positions are strategically complex. Some really strong grandmasters enjoy playing it regardless of its objective strength. }
4. Bxc6
{ White takes on c6 right away in order to damage Black's Pawn structure. }
4... bxc6 5. d3 d6 6. e5 { This is too simple... } 6... d5 7. Be3
{ The most accurate. Now even ...Ng8-e7 will be a problem for Black. } 7... Qb6
8. c4 Ne7 { 8...Qxb2  9.Nbd2  would give White too much. } 9. O-O Nf5
{ 9...Ng6  just  10.Re1  −  the e5-Pawn is safe and the Knight is misplaced on g6. }
