3... e6
{ This is a very rich continuation, and many positions are strategically complex. Some really strong grandmasters enjoy playing it regardless of its objective strength. }
4. Bxc6
{ White takes on c6 right away in order to damage Black's Pawn structure. }
4... bxc6 5. d3 Qc7
{ I think this is how Black should react. It's not a surprise that it was played by Gelfand against my former boss, Vishy Anand, in Legends of Chess 2020. }
6. O-O d6
{ Black is trying to be flexible, either go for ...e6-e5 or ...Ne7-g6, which is also possible. }
7. Nfd2
{ A rare idea in this system but I am not sure why. White wants to play f2-f4 and now the ...Ne7-g6 setup makes no sense as Black would only get chased away with f4-f5.   7.Re1  can also be played, depending on one's preference.  7...e5  8.c3  Ne7  9.d4  Ng6  , which transposes. }
7... e5 8. Nc4 { Black can't stop f2-f4. } 8... Ne7
{ 8...d5  9.exd5  cxd5  10.Nxe5! } 9. f4 exf4 10. Bxf4 Ng6 11. Bg3 Be7 12. Ne3
{ It's an instructive example − Black's dark-squared Bishop may be passive, but it defends the key d6-Pawn. This is why we want to get rid of it. }
12... O-O 13. Nf5 Be6
{ 13...Bxf5?  14.exf5  and the Knight has to go to the corner. } 14. Nd2 Rfe8
15. Nxe7+ Rxe7 16. b3
{ White has a small advantage. It won't be easy to make progress but we should never complain about such positions. It's going to take a while especially since we have to pay attention to ...d6-d5, but our long-term plan will be to bring the Knight to f5. }
