3... e6
{ This is a very rich continuation, and many positions are strategically complex. Some really strong grandmasters enjoy playing it regardless of its objective strength. }
4. Bxc6
{ White takes on c6 right away in order to damage Black's Pawn structure. }
4... bxc6 5. d3 Qc7
{ I think this is how Black should react. It's not a surprise that it was played by Gelfand against my former boss, Vishy Anand, in Legends of Chess 2020. }
6. O-O Ne7 7. Re1
{ Main theory goes  7.h4  e5  8.h5  d6  9.Nh2  h6!  After  10.f4  exf4  11.Bxf4  g5!  the position looks great at first, but once you start going deeper, it's becoming totally unclear @@StartBracket@@believe me@@EndBracket@@. It is also a direction that Black is expecting from us so it makes even more sense to deviate. }
7... Ng6 { This is how everyone replied so far but now h2-h4 works well. } 8.
h4 h5 9. e5 f6
{ Naturally, Black wouldn't mind opening the g-file.  9...d6  10.b3  f6  would transpose. }
10. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto. } 10... d5
{ Now White has full control in the center. } 11. Qe2 Be7 12. Nbd2 f5
{ Black's idea is that after  13.g3  , it will be possible to play  13...f4!  However, we don't need to defend the Pawn. }
13. c4 Nxh4 14. Nxh4 Bxh4 15. Nf3 Be7 16. Bg5
{ White has a great compensation for the Pawn. Black's Bishop is not much better than the Pawns and the dark squares are weak. We will have to find the way through, though. We will have to combine our efforts on the Kingside with possible breakthroughs in the center. }
