1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Perhaps I should start with some explanations on why would we choose Bb5 against ...Nc6. Surely, you will find many repertoires that involve a Bb5 setup, for instance, in the Sicilian with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.Bb5+  or, as is the case here, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  3.Bb5  . You will also find a lot of repertoires where the attention shifts to  3.d4  instead.  I wanted to be as flexible as possible and my goal was to suggest the most challenging solution. The sad truth is that the Sveshnikov Variation is not posing Black serious problems at the moment, which shouldn't come as a surprise, as there aren't many topical games in this opening anymore. On the few occasions when White does go for the Sveshnikov, we will witness some boring draw, unless Black simply forgets the line. Besides the fact that White ran out of ideas, modern engines revealed that Black is okay in more than one way.  The Rossolimo though still has some poison in it, and this is also the trend at top-level chess. There are many games played by very strong GMs and it would be a shame to not include it in your repertoire based on the mere fact that you might go for 3.d4 in different lines.  We do have quite some work ahead though as we have to go through many lines, but I believe it is worth the effort and I am sure you will enjoy playing the Rossolimo with White. }
3... e6
{ This is a very rich continuation, and many positions are strategically complex. Some really strong grandmasters enjoy playing it regardless of its objective strength. }
4. Bxc6
{ White takes on c6 right away in order to damage Black's Pawn structure. }
4... bxc6 5. d3 Ne7
{ This is by far the main continuation, although I am not sure if it's the best one. }
6. Nbd2
{ The latest trend, already played by Grischuk and Giri. The point is exactly the same as after  6.Qe2  , which is one of the well-known moves. We are delaying castling in order to  keep the h2-h4 advance possible in case of ...Ne7-g6. Compared to 6.Qe2, our choice works well against 6...d6 too. }
6... d6 { One move away from ...e6-e5. } 7. e5 { One too many! } 7... d5
{ White has a better Pawn structure and, sooner or later, Black's weakness on c5 will tell. However, we shouldn't rush things. The most important thing is to make sure that Black won't be able to open up the position with something like ...f7-f6. }
8. b3
{ Making space for the Bishop and also improving our control over the c4-square. }
8... h5 9. h4 { Stop right there! } 9... Nf5 10. Nf1
{ The Knight is coming to g3, to trade off Black's best piece. } 10... c4
{ It looks like a great move! Suddenly, after  11.dxc4  Ba6!  , Black's pieces are very active. }
11. Ng3 { Ignoring it is the best reaction. } 11... cxd3
{ Black managed to fix the Pawn structure on the Queenside. } 12. Nxf5 exf5
{ The intermediate capture  12...dxc2  is answered in a similar fashion:  13.Nxg7+  Bxg7  14.Qxc2  with a big advantage for White. }
13. Qxd3
{ But now Black's Pawn structure on the Kingside is bad, and the worst part is that the light-squared Bishop will now suffer. We want to swap the dark-squared Bishops so Bc1-g5 is a very likely follow-up in order to increase control over the dark squares. }
