8... h5 9. h4 { Stop right there! } 9... Nf5 10. Nf1
{ The Knight is coming to g3, to trade off Black's best piece. } 10... Be7
{ Now  11.Bg5  f6!  is not clear at all. } 11. Ng3 Nxh4
{ 11...Nxg3?  12.fxg3  would be horrible for Black. The funny Pawn structure on the Kingside only improves our attacking chances. }
12. Nxh4 Bxh4 13. Nxh5 g6 14. Ng3 { White is threatening Qg4. } 14... f5
{ The best defense. } 15. Qf3
{ White is slightly better. We want to bring the Knight to e2 and chase Black's Bishop away with g2-g3. Let's just see what if Black decides to go ballistic. }
15... Kf7 16. Ne2 Bxf2+
{ Black wins the exchange but the positional problems will now increase severely. The next couple of moves will be simple for White and forced for Black. }
17. Kxf2 Rxh1 18. Bg5 Qh8 19. Bf6 Qh2 20. Rxh1 Qxh1 21. Qe3 d4
{ The only move. } 22. Qg5 Qh5 23. Qc1
{ The Queen will try from the other side. Honestly, I don't want to find out whether Black can defend with accurate play. From a practical point of view, it just doesn't matter. }
