3... e6
{ This is a very rich continuation, and many positions are strategically complex. Some really strong grandmasters enjoy playing it regardless of its objective strength. }
4. Bxc6
{ White takes on c6 right away in order to damage Black's Pawn structure. }
4... bxc6 5. d3 Ne7
{ This is by far the main continuation, although I am not sure if it's the best one. }
6. Nbd2
{ The latest trend, already played by Grischuk and Giri. The point is exactly the same as after  6.Qe2  , which is one of the well-known moves. We are delaying castling in order to  keep the h2-h4 advance possible in case of ...Ne7-g6. Compared to 6.Qe2, our choice works well against 6...d6 too. }
6... Qc7
{ Black is preparing ...Ne7-g6 @@StartBracket@@or just ...e6-e5@@EndBracket@@ and, at the same, is avoiding e4-e5 ideas which we we are going to see after 6...d6. }
7. h4 { Anticipating ...Ne7-g6. } 7... e5
{ Quite a typical idea, making sure that Black won't have to face e4-e5. Black's Pawn center is strong but the Bishops aren't.   7...d5  8.h5  f6  9.Qe2  e5  10.Nh2  transposes. }
8. h5 d5 { 8...f6  9.Qe2  d5  transposes. } 9. Qe2 f6
{ Black had to support the central Pawn. } 10. Nh2
{ Improving the position of the Knight is an important part of the plan, but right now we mainly wanted to avoid ...Bc8-g4. One more idea to keep in mind: f2-f4 is now legal. }
10... Be6
{ Black is developing the Bishop but not really improving the position. } 11.
O-O { Suddenly, f2-f4 is on the table. } 11... g5
{ Quite a radical way to prevent f2-f4. } 12. b4
{ Now that Black's position on the Kingside is weakened, we need to open it before Black finishes the fortress. }
12... cxb4 13. a3 bxa3 { This is just greedy. } 14. Ng4 Kf7 15. Bxa3 Qd7 16. f3
{ Black's position is probably just lost. We are threatening d3-d4! which would destroy Black's defenses. If Black plays  16...d4  , then we can go either  17.Nb3  or  17.Nc4!?  Either way, we will find a way. }
