3... d6
{ Black intends to develop the Bishop to d7 and then push us back with ...a7-a6. I used to like this system a lot, but that was more than ten years ago... }
4. O-O Bg4
{ A dubious move as Black hasn't yet dealt with the pinned Knight on c6. } 5.
c3 a6 { 5...Nf6  6.d4! } 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 e6 9. Nc3
{ And just like that, White has better development and a strong Pawn center. Black's Bishop pair doesn't matter. }
9... Ne7
{ This secures the c6-Pawn, but other than that, it is not really an ideal square for the Knight. }
10. h3 Bxf3
{ Black could not afford to retreat the Bishop to h5, not with the Knight on e7. }
11. Qxf3
{ White is better. Black can go  11...Ng6  to which we can reply with  12.Qe2  ,  preparing f2-f4-f5. The other option  is @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/4nppp/p1ppp3/8/3PP3/2N2Q1P/PP3PP1/R1B2RK1 b kq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...d5  and then  12.Re1  is fine. After  12...dxe4  13.Nxe4  , White has one weak  Pawn on d4 but Black has two  @@StartBracket@@a6 and c6@@EndBracket@@. Moreover, White's development is superior. }
