{ This is critical. White should have the initiative on the Kingside but the position is not without risk as Black has play as well. }
16. a3 { I tried various moves here and this one caught my attention. } 16...
a5 17. a4
{ At first sight, this looks odd. Didn't we just push our Pawn to a3? The answer is found on the a5-square. Black played 16...a5, taking that square away from, potentially, the c6-Knight.   Effectively, it means that Black's counterplay on the Queenside will be much slower. Had we played @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/3nbppp/p1n1p3/1p1pP3/2pP4/2P2N1P/PP3PP1/R1BQRBK1 w - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.a4  , then  16...Na5  would have given Black the upper hand. }
