{ Not only protecting the e4-Pawn but also releasing the f1-square for the Bishop. }
5... Nf6 6. c3 a6 7. Bf1 Bg4 8. d4
{ This is straightforward and effective. White simply grabs the center. } 8...
cxd4 9. cxd4 Bxf3 { This way Black forces us to recapture with the Pawn. } 10.
gxf3 d5
{ The most reasonable way. This line has been know for quite time already but despite its relative correctnes it is hardly used and I am not surprised - it is quite sad for Black. }
11. Nc3 e6 12. Bg5 Be7
{ If we want to fight for advantage, now we must force the events. } 13. Bxf6
Bxf6 14. exd5 Nxd4 15. Re4
{ The key move − the Knight won't be able to hold any longer in the center. }
15... Qb6 { This is a bad idea, Black still hasn't castled! } 16. Qa4+ Kf8 17.
Rd1 Nxf3+ { 17...e5  18.f4+- } 18. Kg2 Ne5 { 18...Qxb2  just  19.Re3  . } 19.
Qa3+ Kg8 20. Rde1
{ There are no good options for Black. Allowing Re4xe5 is not ideal but there is no way to stop it.  20...Ng6  21.dxe6  fxe6  22.Bc4  would be completely winning for White. }
