Bxf6 14. exd5 Nxd4 15. Re4
{ The key move − the Knight won't be able to hold any longer in the center. }
15... Nf5 16. dxe6 O-O
{ Black is a Pawn down but with the opposite-colored Bishops and White's damaged Pawn structure, Black has reasonable chances of holding it. }
17. exf7+ Kh8 18. Qxd8 Raxd8 19. Rd1
{ It's better to trade a pair of Rooks than give Black the d-file. } 19... Rxd1
20. Nxd1 g6 21. Bc4
{ This way we can get rid of the Bishops. The next moves are rather forced. }
21... Nd6 22. Re6 Nxc4 23. Rxf6 Kg7 24. Rf4 Ne5 25. Kg2
{ The King will definitely be useful, after all, we are already in the endgame. Black will win one Pawn back but we still have another one. I am sure it is defendable, but this is hardly a reason to avoid the line with White. Our plan will be to somehow advance the Pawn to f5. }
