4. O-O Bd7
{ The alternatives are covered in the relevant chapter, so I don't think this move requires any specific explanation. It stays consistent with Black's plan of playing 3...d6. }
5. Re1
{ Not only protecting the e4-Pawn but also releasing the f1-square for the Bishop. }
5... Nf6 6. c3 a6 7. Bf1 Bg4 8. d4
{ This is straightforward and effective. White simply grabs the center. } 8...
cxd4 9. cxd4 e5
{ The most direct continuation. It starts aggressively, but soon Black will be begging for a draw. }
10. d5 Nd4 11. Be3 Nxf3+ 12. gxf3 Bc8
{ Too passive, now the Knight will get to c4. } 13. Nd2
{ The problem with the Bishop on c8 is that Black can't put the Pawn on b5.  13...b5?!  14.a4!  and Black is already collapsing on the Queenside. }
13... Be7 14. Nc4 Nd7 { Covering the b6-square. } 15. a4 O-O 16. a5
{ White is dominating on the Queenside, which leaves Black with no option but to look for direct counterplay on the other side. }
16... f5 17. exf5 Rxf5 18. Rc1
{ It doesn't seem like Black achieved much of a counterplay, does it? After  18...Qf8  , we can defend the Pawn with  19.Bg2  . With the Knight tied to  the b6-square, I don't really see what Black can do other than waiting. We can hide the King on h1, put the Pawn on b4, and activate our King's Rook. White is much better. }
