3... a6
{ This is quite similar to  3...d6  4.O-O  a6  , a variation we checked in the Rossolimo chapter dedicated to  the 3.Bb5 d6 line. Since we want to take on c6 anyway, playing ...a6 does nothing else but help us out. }
4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O Bg4
{ This is the only sensible explanation for going 3...a6 and then capturing on c6 with the d-Pawn. Black develops the Bishop and plans to continue with ...e5 setups. It is, however, a worse version of an Anti-Berlin, not only because exchanging the light-squared Bishop is not so great for Black, but also placing the Pawns on c6 and c5 is not so good either. }
6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 e5
{ Now it looks like a bad Anti-Berlin @@StartBracket@@with the Pawn on c5 instead of c7@@EndBracket@@ − for Black of course. }
8. a4 a5 { Allowing a4-a5 would not be in Black's best interest. } 9. Qb3
{ Before playing d2-d3, we are improving the position of the Queen. } 9... Qc7
10. d3 Nf6 11. Nd2 Bd6 12. Nc4
{ We can develop the Bishop to e3, provoking ...Nf6-d7, and then just take on d6 and go f2-f4. White is much better. }
