1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black delays moving the Pawn to d6 in order to have some more active options for the dark-squared Bishop. The Taimanov Variation has been for many years one of my favorite weapons for Black. However, the computer revolution did not serve it well and, although the line is objectively correct, new challenges keep popping up putting in question its practical value. }
6. Be3 a6 7. g4
{ Currently, this aggressive move is one of the main challenges for Black. In some ways, it is similar to the  7.Qd2  line,  but there f2-f3 is played automatically, whereas here, at least in some lines, we can skip it and save time. }
7... Nxd4 8. Qxd4 b5
{ Not a popular line but it was tested in the game between Nils Grandelius and Magnus Carlsen, Tata Steel 2022, so it's kind of important. }
9. O-O-O Bb7 10. f3 Rc8
{ This is why Black invited our Queen to d4, to enable ...b5-b4. } 11. Qd2 Bb4
12. Bd4 f6 { Now Black is threatening ...e6-e5. } 13. g5 Bd6
{ Perhaps with the Knight on g6 it would be reasonable, but not here. Also,  13...e5  is not advisable since our last move has opened the h3-c8 diagonal.  Following  14.Be3  ,  White threatens to develop the light-squared Bishop to h3 and has a serious advantage. }
14. Ne2 h6 15. gxf6 Nxf6 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Kb1
{ White is much better. If Black defends the Bishop with  17...Ke7  , then we will  move the Rook to g1. If the Bishop moves to c5, then we will improve our pressure in the center with Bf1-h3, Rh1-e1, and Ne2-f4 or Ne2-d4. }
