[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black delays moving the Pawn to d6 in order to have some more active options for the dark-squared Bishop. The Taimanov Variation has been for many years one of my favorite weapons for Black. However, the computer revolution did not serve it well and, although the line is objectively correct, new challenges keep popping up putting in question its practical value. }
6. Be3 a6 7. g4
{ Currently, this aggressive move is one of the main challenges for Black. In some ways, it is similar to the  7.Qd2  line,  but there f2-f3 is played automatically, whereas here, at least in some lines, we can skip it and save time. }
7... Nge7
{ Black wants to recapture with the Knight. This plan can be met in different systems but it is usually dubious. Quite often White simply retreats the Knight to b3 and the black Knight is not that well placed on e7. This is precisely what we can do here. }
8. Nb3 Ng6 { The Knight is too exposed on g6. } 9. h4 b5 10. h5 Nge5 11. f4 Nc4
{ Rather unwillingly, Black made four moves with the Knight out of the last five moves. }
12. Bxc4 bxc4 13. Nd4 Rb8
{ Black had to do something. The normal  13...Be7  14.Qf3  followed by long castle would be too good for White. }
14. Nxc6 dxc6
{ The engines are desperate enough to suggest this but it actually makes sense. Black wants to move this Pawn to c5. }
15. h6 g5
{ Black is putting a fight.  15...gxh6  16.e5  followed by Nc3-e4 would be clearly better for White. }
16. e5 c5 17. Ne4 Be7
{ Black is ready to move the Bishop to b7 − we have to act now. } 18. Nd6+ Bxd6
19. Qxd6 { 19.exd6  is also possible but I think our choice is better. } 19...
Qxd6 20. exd6 Rxb2 21. Kd2
{ White is better since our d6-Pawn is a great asset. We want to bring the King to c3. If Black takes on f4 and tries to cut our Bishop off with ...f7-f6 @@StartBracket@@preparing ...e6-e5@@EndBracket@@, then we must quickly go g4-g5. }
