[Black "Taimanov 6.Be3 a6 7.g4 h6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black delays moving the Pawn to d6 in order to have some more active options for the dark-squared Bishop. The Taimanov Variation has been for many years one of my favorite weapons for Black. However, the computer revolution did not serve it well and, although the line is objectively correct, new challenges keep popping up putting in question its practical value. }
6. Be3 a6 7. g4
{ Currently, this aggressive move is one of the main challenges for Black. In some ways, it is similar to the  7.Qd2  line,  but there f2-f3 is played automatically, whereas here, at least in some lines, we can skip it and save time. }
7... h6
{ This was a novelty in the game between Anish Giri and Ian Nepomniachtchi during the Online Olympiad in 2021. I suspect that Black might have mixed up the lines. Against the immediate @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppqp1ppp/2n1p3/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.g4  h6!?  is really interesting. The point is that Black  skips ...a7-a6 instead of counterattacking in the center with ...Ng8-f6 and ...Bf8-b4. Here, ...a7-a6 is already on the board. }
8. h4 Nf6 9. Nxc6
{ One of the ideas that decades ago would have been considered incorrect. After all, we are opening the b-file and improving Black's Pawn center. However, without the Knights looking at each other, we can develop much smoother. }
9... Qxc6 { Naturally, this can't be ignored completely. } 10. f3
{ We would prefer to go  10.Bg2  but  10...Ba3  is annoying. } 10... Ba3
{ 10...b5  11.Qd2  Bb7  would transpose. } 11. bxa3
{ Now the King can hide on f2. } 11... Qxc3+ 12. Kf2 d5 13. exd5
{ Why not? Black is so badly developed. } 13... Nxd5 14. Bd4 Qxa3 15. c4
{ 15...e5  is met with  16.Qe1!  so I am sorry but the Knight has to come back. }
15... Nf6 16. Qb3 Qxb3 17. axb3
{ Despite the limited material, White has nice compensation for the Pawn. We can push the Pawn to b5, making it much harder for the black Bishop to find a place on the board. The other idea is to put the Bishop on c2 and then try g4-g5. }
