{ The position is sharp but this doesn't mean that the positional aspects don't matter. We would still love to swap the dark-squared Bishops and put our Knight on c5. We are still playing in such a way that in case of the Queens' exchange, we could dominate Black's light-squared Bishop. Therefore, b2-b3 is perfectly healthy, it doesn't weaken any light squares and it supports Nc3-a4. Besides, the Pawn was under attack! :-@@EndBracket@@ }
15... Bc5
{ The most challenging move as now our f2-Pawn is in trouble. However, with accurate play, we can punish Black for challenging us. }
16. Qh8+ Ke7 17. O-O-O Nxf2 18. Qxg7 { White is threatening g5-g6. } 18... Ba3+
{ The idea is to take on c3 with a check. } 19. Kb1 Nxd1
{ It is funny that even now  20.g6!?  Nxc3+  21.Ka1!  is possible, though objectively unclear. }
20. Nxd1
{ White is much better. We are still threatening g5-g6 and after  20...Qg3  or  20...Qh2  , we can go  21.Bc3  ,  preparing Bc3-f6. Black is an exchange up but with the King that weak and the Rook that passive, it just doesn't matter. }
*

