[Black "Taimanov 6.Be3 a6 7.g4 b5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black delays moving the Pawn to d6 in order to have some more active options for the dark-squared Bishop. The Taimanov Variation has been for many years one of my favorite weapons for Black. However, the computer revolution did not serve it well and, although the line is objectively correct, new challenges keep popping up putting in question its practical value. }
6. Be3 a6 7. g4
{ Currently, this aggressive move is one of the main challenges for Black. In some ways, it is similar to the  7.Qd2  line,  but there f2-f3 is played automatically, whereas here, at least in some lines, we can skip it and save time. }
7... b5 { By far the most popular continuation. } 8. Nxc6 Qxc6
{ Black is now threatening ...b5-b4. } 9. Qd2
{ Let Black take the Pawn, development is more important to us. } 9... Bb7 10.
O-O-O Nf6 { Black ignores the Pawn and simply develops the pieces. } 11. f3
{ Here I owe you an explanation. @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/3p1ppp/p1q1p3/1p6/4P1P1/2N1B3/PPP2P1P/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.f3  could be met with  9...h5!  with a great position for Black.  Of course, with the Knight on f6, we don't care, as we have g4-g5. }
11... d6 { Too passive. } 12. g5 Nd7 13. a3
{ They used to teach us that we should not move the Pawns in front of our King, especially with opposite side castlings. Today I would rather say: 'be careful'. It may slow down your opponent's counterplay but it might also speed it up. I think here it just stops it. }
13... Be7 14. f4
{ White is so much better, Black shouldn't even castle short.  14...O-O  15.Rg1  followed by f4-f5 and it's really hard to defend it with Black. }
*

