{ Black delays moving the Pawn to d6 in order to have some more active options for the dark-squared Bishop. The Taimanov Variation has been for many years one of my favorite weapons for Black. However, the computer revolution did not serve it well and, although the line is objectively correct, new challenges keep popping up putting in question its practical value. }
6. Be3 a6 7. g4
{ Currently, this aggressive move is one of the main challenges for Black. In some ways, it is similar to the  7.Qd2  line,  but there f2-f3 is played automatically, whereas here, at least in some lines, we can skip it and save time. }
7... b5 { By far the most popular continuation. } 8. Nxc6 Qxc6
{ Black is now threatening ...b5-b4. } 9. Qd2
{ Let Black take the Pawn, development is more important to us. } 9... b4 10.
Ne2 Qxe4 { 10...Bb7  11.O-O-O  Nf6  12.f3  would transpose. } 11. Rg1
{ The Queen is pretty exposed on e4, but that goes without saying. } 11... Qc4
{ The main move in the position. } 12. Ng3 Qc7
{ This is how Black played so far. } 13. O-O-O Nf6
{ I think this is the cleanest example of White benefiting from placing the Knight on g3 rather than f4. }
14. Bf4 { Black is facing an unpleasant choice. } 14... Qc5 15. g5 Nd5 16. Be5
{ Now Black can't move the dark-squared Bishop. } 16... Bb7 17. Nh5 Rg8 18. Kb1
{ White has great compensation for the Pawn. We can activate the Rook with Rg1-g3 and advance the f-Pawn. If Black pushes the Pawn to a4, threatening ...a4-a3, then we can always bring the Knight back to f4.   18...d6  19.Bd4  Qc7  20.f4  only makes it harder for Black. }
