[Black "Taimanov 6.Be3 a6 7.g4 b5 #20"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black delays moving the Pawn to d6 in order to have some more active options for the dark-squared Bishop. The Taimanov Variation has been for many years one of my favorite weapons for Black. However, the computer revolution did not serve it well and, although the line is objectively correct, new challenges keep popping up putting in question its practical value. }
6. Be3 a6 7. g4
{ Currently, this aggressive move is one of the main challenges for Black. In some ways, it is similar to the  7.Qd2  line,  but there f2-f3 is played automatically, whereas here, at least in some lines, we can skip it and save time. }
7... b5 { By far the most popular continuation. } 8. Nxc6 Qxc6
{ Black is now threatening ...b5-b4. } 9. Qd2
{ Let Black take the Pawn, development is more important to us. } 9... b4 10.
Ne2 Qxe4 { 10...Bb7  11.O-O-O  Nf6  12.f3  would transpose. } 11. Rg1
{ The Queen is pretty exposed on e4, but that goes without saying. } 11... Qc4
{ The main move in the position. } 12. Ng3 Qc7
{ This is how Black played so far. } 13. O-O-O Ne7
{ This was tried in a game between Esipenko and Shankland in Tata Steel 2022. Black's point is that now after  14.Bf4  , there is  14...e5! }
14. Nh5 { Be3-f4 is one idea... } 14... Nd5 15. Bd4 { And this is another. }
15... Rg8 16. Qd3 g6 17. Bg2
{ We are still following the game. Black has no choice now. } 17... gxh5 18.
Bxd5 Bb7 { 18...exd5??  19.Rge1+  would end quickly. } 19. Bxb7 Qxb7 20. g5
{ Esipenko took on h5 which was weaker. } 20... Qd5
{ The Queen is attacking the Pawns on g5 and a2.  20...Qb5  21.Qe4! } 21. h4
Qxa2 22. b3 Rc8 { Black has to play actively as Qd3xh7 is a serious threat. }
23. Rg3 { After  23.Bb2  d5  24.Qxh7  , Black had  24...Qxb3  . } 23... Rc7
{ Black is anticipating Bd4-b2. Another possibility was  23...Rg6  24.f4  , with nice compensation for the Pawn. It's just difficult to make moves with Black. }
24. Rd2 { Once again, Qd3xh7 is a threat. } 24... Bg7 25. Bxg7
{ 25.Qxh7??  Bxd4!  26.Qxg8+  Ke7  and Black wins. } 25... Rxg7 26. Qd4
{ I could just stop here claiming that White has good compensation. In reality, White does have good compensation after  26...Rg8  27.Rgd3  . However, Black can save the day with a ridiculous idea. }
26... f6
{ I would never expect it over the board. The point is that after  27.gxf6  Rxg3  28.fxg3  Kf7  or  28...d6  , White can't improve the position. }
27. Re3 { The best try. } 27... e5
{ We now can't take  28.gxf6  because of  28...Rg1+  . } 28. Kd1 Qb1+ 29. Ke2
Rxc2 30. gxf6 Rxd2+ 31. Qxd2 Rg4
{ The Rook needs to control the e4-square. Other moves were losing. } 32. Rxe5+
Kd8 33. Qd6
{ White would be winning with the black Rook on g1, for example, but now Black has: }
33... Re4+ 34. Rxe4 Qxe4+ 35. Kd2
{ After  35...Ke8  36.Qxa6  , the position is equal. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Sicilian 5.Nc3 a6/d6"]
[Black "Taimanov 5.Nc3 d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3
{ As the title of the chapter goes, in this section, we will be focusing on  5...d6  and  5...a6  . To be honest, I am not sure if this is still the Taimanov Variation or perhaps just an unusual version of the Sicilian Defense, but I don't think it matters much. }
5... d6
{ Quite an interesting line to get a fighting position − Black is avoiding the main theory. It is very similar to the Keres Variation, the only difference being that the Knight is still on g8, which, perhaps, is a bit more flexible compared to having the Knight on f6. However, it doesn't really change much. First of all,  6.Be3  followed by f4 and Qf3 is a very good line for White, but I see no reason to not stick to the g4 plan, which works pretty well. }
6. g4 { Advancing the g2-Pawn is the most serious response. } 6... h6 7. Be3
Nf6 8. Rg1 { Transposes to the Keres Attack. } *

