1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3
{ As the title of the chapter goes, in this section, we will be focusing on  5...d6  and  5...a6  . To be honest, I am not sure if this is still the Taimanov Variation or perhaps just an unusual version of the Sicilian Defense, but I don't think it matters much. }
5... d6
{ Quite an interesting line to get a fighting position − Black is avoiding the main theory. It is very similar to the Keres Variation, the only difference being that the Knight is still on g8, which, perhaps, is a bit more flexible compared to having the Knight on f6. However, it doesn't really change much. First of all,  6.Be3  followed by f4 and Qf3 is a very good line for White, but I see no reason to not stick to the g4 plan, which works pretty well. }
6. g4 { Advancing the g2-Pawn is the most serious response. } 6... a6
{ 6...Nge7  7.Be3  a6  transposes. } 7. Be3 Nge7
{ This is the point of Black's setup. } 8. f4
