1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3
{ As the title of the chapter goes, in this section, we will be focusing on  5...d6  and  5...a6  . To be honest, I am not sure if this is still the Taimanov Variation or perhaps just an unusual version of the Sicilian Defense, but I don't think it matters much. }
5... a6
{ Historically, this move hasn't been considered more appealing than  5...Qc7  and the reasoning was that after  5...a6  6.Nxc6  bxc6  7.Bd3  , the resulting positions were evaluated as unpleasant for Black. I actually believe that Black is doing not so bad here, even though White can challenge the position in many different ways.  Overall, I think this line is more playable for Black than many people would expect. On the other hand, different tries for White have emerged, and one of them that is particularly dangerous and my recommendation is  7.Qd3  . }
6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Qd3
{ We have some high-level games in this line already, which is a clear sign that I am not offering you a shaky variation, which is in fact a very good and dangerous weapon. The main idea is to activate the Queen and bring it to g3. }
7... d5 8. Qg3 d4 9. Nb1 Nf6
{ Now White should be easily better.  9...h5  10.h4  would transpose. } 10. Nd2
h5 { Black is late with this advance, but it's still the best chance. } 11. e5
h4 12. Qf4 Nd7
{ This is too passive, especially since Black won't be able to win the Pawn on e5. }
13. Qxd4 Qa5 14. f4 Bb7 15. c3
{ White is threatening Nd2-c4 and after  15...c5  , we can  retreat the Queen to f2 with advantage. }
