7... d5 8. Qg3 Nf6 9. Be2 { Preventing ...Nf6-h5. } 9... d4 10. e5
{ With the Knight on f6, this is almost always the case. } 10... Nd7 11. Ne4
Qa5+ { Otherwise, Black is just busted. } 12. c3 dxc3
{ Since Black is suffering anyway, at least suffer for the Pawn, right? } 13.
Nxc3 Qxe5 14. Bf4 Qf6 15. Bf3
{ The flaw in Black's logic is that there are different levels of suffering. }
15... Bb7 16. O-O-O { Now the Rook is joining the game. } 16... Qg6 17. Bg5
{ White is threatening Qg3-c7 despite the Bishop on g5! } 17... Rc8 18. Qh4
{ Now we are threatening Bf3-h5. } 18... h6
{ 18...Nf6  wouldn't be helpful due to White's Ne4 and Rhe1 ideas. } 19. Rxd7
{ Otherwise, Black might survive. } 19... Kxd7 20. Qd4+ Bd6 21. Ne4
{ 21...hxg5  22.Qxd6+  Ke8  23.Qc5  is completely winning for White, leaving Black no choice. }
21... e5 22. Qb6 f5
{ The final try. After  23.Nxd6?  Qxg5+  or @@StartFEN@@2r4r/1b1k2p1/pQpb2qp/4ppB1/4N3/5B2/PP3PPP/2K4R w - - 0 23@@EndFEN@@  23.Qxb7+?  Rc7  followed by ...f5xe4, Black is suddenly fine! }
23. h4
{ Black can't take  23...fxe4  due to  24.Bg4+  and we are now  threatening Ne4xd6. }
23... hxg5 24. Nxd6 Qxd6 25. Rd1 Qxd1+ 26. Bxd1
{ I think that White is just technically winning. After  26...Rc7  27.hxg5  , Black has too many weaknesses. }
