1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Variation has been my love for many years and gave me some nice wins with Black. However, looking back, I realize I did well not because the opening was good, but because my opponents didn't know how to react. }
5. c4
{ Believe me, you want to do it. I never score well against it and many players with Black just hate it. Besides, the alternatives are not that great.  5.Bd3  Bc5  I like for Black, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  b5  I like for Black too. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.a3  is interesting, but this would mean that Kan is as serious as Taimanov and it's not.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c4  , Black has one correct way of playing that is pretty close to equality, but it also leads to a position that is very impractical, as you shall see. The point of our last move is to improve White's control in the center and  anticipate ...b7-b5 or ...d7-d5. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7 { Black gives up on ...Bf8-b4, which is good news for us. }
7. a3
{ White makes sure that ...Bf8-b4 will not happen anymore. Besides, the Pawn is useful on a3 as we will often play b2-b4. }
7... Nxe4 { This move does not really work. } 8. Nxe4 Qe5 9. Bd3 Qxd4 10. Qe2
{ White has a great advantage in development but also Black has some weak dark squares. }
10... Be7 11. Be3 Qe5 12. f4 Qc7 13. c5
{ White's advantage is unquestionable. After  13...f5  , we can just go  14.Nd6+  Bxd6  15.cxd6  Qxd6  16.g4!  with a very strong attack. }
