[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Variation has been my love for many years and gave me some nice wins with Black. However, looking back, I realize I did well not because the opening was good, but because my opponents didn't know how to react. }
5. c4
{ Believe me, you want to do it. I never score well against it and many players with Black just hate it. Besides, the alternatives are not that great.  5.Bd3  Bc5  I like for Black, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  b5  I like for Black too. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.a3  is interesting, but this would mean that Kan is as serious as Taimanov and it's not.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c4  , Black has one correct way of playing that is pretty close to equality, but it also leads to a position that is very impractical, as you shall see. The point of our last move is to improve White's control in the center and  anticipate ...b7-b5 or ...d7-d5. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7 { Black gives up on ...Bf8-b4, which is good news for us. }
7. a3
{ White makes sure that ...Bf8-b4 will not happen anymore. Besides, the Pawn is useful on a3 as we will often play b2-b4. }
7... b6
{ Before developing the other pieces, Black wants to attack the e4-Pawn and provoke f2-f3. }
8. f4
{ This is a rare continuation @@StartBracket@@it hasn't been mentioned in Neiksan's & Kovalenko's LTR on the Kan@@EndBracket@@ but it seems to work really well and it comes with a nice bonus: Black is probably out of book already and has to solve concrete problems. }
8... Bb7 { 8...d6  9.Bd3  Bb7  transposes. } 9. Bd3 d6
{ Now White benefits from playing this aggressively. } 10. O-O
{ 10.f5!?  was also interesting. } 10... Nbd7 11. Qe2 Be7 12. b4
{ The good thing about our position is that we don't actually need to memorize anything, as long as we understand the ideas and plans for White, our move order does not matter. Here, once again,  12.f5  deserved attention. }
12... O-O 13. Bb2 Rac8
{ The following moves are rather illustrative as I want to explain a few things about White's plan. }
14. Rad1 Rfe8 15. Nc2
{ The Knight is heading to e3. From there it will defend the c4-Pawn and anticipate ...d6-d5, but also in some cases, Ne3-g4 will be possible. We want to advance our Kingside Pawns but we have to consider ...d6-d5 and ...e6-e5 all the time. We don't to be countered in the center. If Black brings the Knight to g6, which is a typical plan, we might consider g2-g3 and h2-h4-h5. }
