5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7 { Black gives up on ...Bf8-b4, which is good news for us. }
7. a3
{ White makes sure that ...Bf8-b4 will not happen anymore. Besides, the Pawn is useful on a3 as we will often play b2-b4. }
7... b6
{ Before developing the other pieces, Black wants to attack the e4-Pawn and provoke f2-f3. }
8. f4
{ This is a rare continuation @@StartBracket@@it hasn't been mentioned in Neiksan's & Kovalenko's LTR on the Kan@@EndBracket@@ but it seems to work really well and it comes with a nice bonus: Black is probably out of book already and has to solve concrete problems. }
8... Bb7 { 8...d6  9.Bd3  Bb7  transposes. } 9. Bd3 Nc6
{ The most critical response. } 10. Nxc6
{ 10.Nf3?!  Na5!  or @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/1bqp1ppp/ppn1pn2/8/2PNPP2/P1NB4/1P4PP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 3 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Nb3  d6  followed by ...g7-g6 and ...Bf8-g7 would be okay for Black. }
10... Bxc6
{ I wouldn't really expect that. Most of the time, Black automatically recaptures with the Queen. However, it's not a bad move so we shouldn't neglect it. }
11. e5 Ng8 12. Qe2
{ It wasn't an easy decision for me as other tries also seemed promising. }
12... Nh6 { Normally, it's a sound idea but in this case, it works badly. } 13.
b4 Be7 14. Bb2
{ White is much better and yes, we will castle long, our King will be perfectly safe on the Queenside. Although the Pawns are advanced, they cannot really be challenged, and also our King will be surrounded by other pieces. It's actually a very nice example of how strong the Bishops can be − both defending and attacking. }
