{ Believe me, you want to do it. I never score well against it and many players with Black just hate it. Besides, the alternatives are not that great.  5.Bd3  Bc5  I like for Black, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  b5  I like for Black too. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.a3  is interesting, but this would mean that Kan is as serious as Taimanov and it's not.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.c4  , Black has one correct way of playing that is pretty close to equality, but it also leads to a position that is very impractical, as you shall see. The point of our last move is to improve White's control in the center and  anticipate ...b7-b5 or ...d7-d5. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4
{ The main continuation, although grandmasters Artur Neiksans and Igor Kovalenko don't recommend it in their LTR on the Kan, which pretty much confirms that the best line, objectively, might not be the best practical choice. }
7. Qd3 { The Queen defends both the Knight and the e4-Pawn. } 7... O-O
{ Not a very popular move but it has been used by some fantastic players @@StartBracket@@and also great Kan experts@@EndBracket@@: Caruana, Svidler, and Andreikin. }
8. e5
{ And this is the reason for its lack of popularity. Black's position looks pretty bad at the moment but Black will be able to challenge our central Pawn soon. }
8... Ne8 { 8...Ng4?  9.Qg3  . } 9. Bf4 d6
{ 9...f6??  10.Nxe6!  would be unfortunate. } 10. exd6 Bxd6 11. Bxd6 Qxd6
{ 11...Nxd6  12.O-O-O  and the Knight is  shaky on d6. } 12. O-O-O Nf6
{ 12...Qc7?!  13.Qg3!  The resulting endgame after  13...Qxg3  14.hxg3  will favor White due to the more active pieces, open files for the Rooks, and Black finding it hard to comfortably finish development. }
13. Be2
{ White is slightly better. After  13...Qc7  , we can attack with  14.g4  or quietly transit to the endgame:  14.Nc2  Nc6  15.Qd6  . One of the nicer things about the 5.c4 line is that quite often White is not better thanks to some specific moves, but is better thanks to positional trumps. This kind of advantage, usually, stays with us longer. }
