{ 14.Qg3!?  was also possible but I like the clarity of White's plan. } 14...
cxd5 15. Bf4
{ In my opinion, this is more accurate than  15.Be3  as the Bishop takes away  the b8-square from Black's Rook. We will move the Rooks to d1 and c1. The light-squared Bishop can be placed on f3 while the other one can be moved to e5, taking the d4-square under control.  I have no doubt that with accurate play Black should be able to defend this. Advancing the a-Pawn is a good way of defending, although we can always stop it with a2-a4. The bottom line is that Black is forced to defend and while we can sometimes accept such a scenario in the game, deliberately aiming for it straight from the opening is an entirely different story. }
