[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. Nimzowitsch Variation 2.Nf3 Nf6"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch Variation 2.Nf3 Nf6 − 4.Nc3 e6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Nimzowitsch Variation is still quite popular, even at the top level. However, it has nothing to do with its objective strength. Chess players simply like to have fun sometimes. With the last move, Black is provoking us to push our central Pawn to e5. }
3. e5 { We don't mind at all. } 3... Nd5 4. Nc3 e6
{ Black is willing to allow the breaking of the Pawn structure in order to catch up in development. }
5. Ne4 { A better try than  5.Nxd5  , in my opinion. } 5... d6
{ This is too soft − White should be easily better. } 6. exd6 Bxd6 7. Bb5+
{ Black's Pawn structure is about to get wrecked. } 7... Nc6 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9.
Nxd6+
{ Just to make sure that Black will not try to sacrifice the c5-Pawn and save the Bishop pair. }
9... Qxd6 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1
{ The simple  11.d3  would be better for White on a general basis, but it's a matter of accuracy for us. Let Black work for this  Pawn on e5. }
11... f6 12. d3 e5 13. Nd2
{ We will focus on the c5-Pawn: b2-b3, Ne4 and Bc1-e3 or Bc1-a3. All kinds of endgames are better for White so we don't need to worry about simplifications. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. Nimzowitsch Variation 2.Nf3 Nf6"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch Variation 2.Nf3 Nf6 − 4.Nc3 e6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Nimzowitsch Variation is still quite popular, even at the top level. However, it has nothing to do with its objective strength. Chess players simply like to have fun sometimes. With the last move, Black is provoking us to push our central Pawn to e5. }
3. e5 { We don't mind at all. } 3... Nd5 4. Nc3 e6
{ Black is willing to allow the breaking of the Pawn structure in order to catch up in development. }
5. Ne4 { A better try than  5.Nxd5  , in my opinion. } 5... Nc6
{ If you think about it, it's really a c3 Sicilian without c2-c3, just an extra tempo for White. }
6. c4 f5
{ This is a new move and since it might gain some more popularity, we should anticipate it, even though objectively it is not strong. }
7. cxd5 fxe4 8. dxc6 exf3 9. Qxf3 dxc6
{ Why would anyone even consider such a line with Black? Both Bishops are bad. }
10. Be2
{ As bad as the 6...f5 line is, it is quite demanding from us, for instance,  10.Bd3  Qd4!  was already not so clear. After  11.Qg3  Bd7!  followed by long castle,  the Bishop looks stupid on d3. }
10... Be7
{ 10...Qd4  wouldn't help now:  11.Qc3!  followed  by d2-d3 and Bc1-e3 and Black's position is horrible. }
11. d3
{ Closing one Bishop but opening up another one. We will manage to activate the light-squared Bishop if we need to. }
11... Qd4 12. Qg3 g6 13. O-O
{ White has a clear advantage, although it makes sense to stop and think for a bit. The position is rather unusual. We want to develop the Bishop to e3, even at the cost of a Pawn. For instance,  13...Bd7  14.Be3  Qxb2  15.Bf3  and White is clearly better. If  Black castles short, then sooner or later we will be able to attack with h4-h5. }
*

