[Black "Nimzowitsch Variation 2.Nf3 Nf6 − 4.Nc3 e6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Nimzowitsch Variation is still quite popular, even at the top level. However, it has nothing to do with its objective strength. Chess players simply like to have fun sometimes. With the last move, Black is provoking us to push our central Pawn to e5. }
3. e5 { We don't mind at all. } 3... Nd5 4. Nc3 e6
{ Black is willing to allow the breaking of the Pawn structure in order to catch up in development. }
5. Ne4 { A better try than  5.Nxd5  , in my opinion. } 5... Nc6
{ If you think about it, it's really a c3 Sicilian without c2-c3, just an extra tempo for White. }
6. c4 Ndb4 { It doesn't make much sense, but some players do it anyway. } 7. a3
Qa5 8. Be2
{ Since  8.Rb1  would be met with  8...Na2  , it is best to ignore this guy. }
8... Nd4 9. O-O
{ 9.Nxd4  cxd4  10.O-O!  Qxe5  11.d3  is also possible, but I am trying to keep things as simple as possible. }
9... Nbc6 { 9...Nxf3+  10.Bxf3  Nd3  11.Bh5!  and Black is in huge trouble. }
10. b4 Nxb4 { This is too greedy. } 11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. axb4 Qxa1 13. d3
{ The calm  13.Qb3  should also win. } 13... Bxb4 14. Bh5
{ With half of the pieces cut off on the enemy side and the other half in their starting positions, Black will not be able to defend against White's threats. On the next move, we will most likely move the Queen to g4, but to be honest, I see many nice moves for White, including c4-c5. }
*

