[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. Nimzowitsch Variation 2.Nf3 Nf6"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch Variation 2.Nf3 Nf6 − 4.Nc3 Nxc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Nimzowitsch Variation is still quite popular, even at the top level. However, it has nothing to do with its objective strength. Chess players simply like to have fun sometimes. With the last move, Black is provoking us to push our central Pawn to e5. }
3. e5 { We don't mind at all. } 3... Nd5 4. Nc3 Nxc3 5. dxc3 Nc6
{ 5...e6  6.Bf4  Nc6  transposes. } 6. Bf4
{ This is the most natural square for the Bishop, defending our central Pawn and also anticipating ...d7-d6. }
6... Qc7
{ Once you see our reply to  6...e6  , this will make more sense.  However, White can also benefit from this move order and develop the Queen to e2. }
7. Bd3 e6 8. Qe2
{ Now our e5-Pawn is secured while the Queen won't be exposed on the d-file. }
8... b6 9. O-O-O Bb7 10. h4
{ A typical plan in this structure. We want to fix the Pawn structure on the Kingside, creating permanent weaknesses in Black's camp. }
10... O-O-O 11. Be4 h6
{ The whole assumption is that once Black manages to play ...d7-d6 and get rid of our e5-Pawn, Black will solve the opening problems and enjoy a Pawn advantage on the Kingside. I believe that this assumption is simply wrong. }
12. h5 d6 13. exd6 Bxd6 14. Rxd6 Rxd6 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. b3
{ In case of  16...Qf4+  , we can hide  the King on b2. At first sight, Black's position looks acceptable. However, once you think for a bit longer, the problems become apparent: the King on c8 is much weaker than ours, Black has no access to most of the central squares, and the Knight is a far worse piece than it usually is. Also, the Kingside Pawns are weak as well − the g7-Pawn is a great target. Our plan is quite simple: bring the Rook to g3 and let Black worry about defending the Pawn. }
*

