1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 a6
{ The O'Kelly Variation used to have a dubious reputation which could be summarized in the following way: if White doesn't know the line and goes  3.d4?!  then after  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5  , Black is fine. If White does know the line, White will go either @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p7/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.c3  or  3.c4  and get an advantage easily. Today, we know that this is not that simple. I think that Black is quite okay after  3.c3  d5  , so let's just go for another option. }
3. c4 Nc6 { Black is threatening ...e7-e5 so we can't wait with d2-d4. } 4. d4
cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5
{ Black is fighting for the dark squares. This interesting move has been repeatedly used by Vladislav Artemiev, one of the most interesting players of the new generation. }
6. Nf5
{ The calmer  6.Nc2  would allow Black to go  6...Bc5  , with decent chances. }
6... d6
{ Although it is connected with a specific idea, the objective value of Black's last move is not high. }
7. Ne3 { 7.Nc3  would most likely transpose. } 7... g6
{ This is Black's point, getting rid of the dark-squared Bishop.  7...Nf6  8.Nc3  would transpose. }
8. Nc3 Bh6 9. Be2 Be6 10. O-O Nf6
{ These moves are too natural to discuss them but also, even if we change something, the key points will remain the same. }
11. Nc2 Bxc1 12. Rxc1
{ As bad as the Black's dark-squared Bishop was, it was defending Black's biggest weakness: the d6-Pawn. Furthermore, in order to exchange the Bishop, Black had to play ...g7-g6 so now there are some weak dark squares, and f2-f4 looks appealing.  White has an easy game − let's start with moving the Queen to d2 and them bringing the Queen's Rook to d1. We don't want to touch the Rook on f1 as we will go f2-f4 at some point. }
