[Black "Sicilian 2.Nf3 a6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 a6
{ The O'Kelly Variation used to have a dubious reputation which could be summarized in the following way: if White doesn't know the line and goes  3.d4?!  then after  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5  , Black is fine. If White does know the line, White will go either @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1ppppp/p7/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.c3  or  3.c4  and get an advantage easily. Today, we know that this is not that simple. I think that Black is quite okay after  3.c3  d5  , so let's just go for another option. }
3. c4 Nc6 { Black is threatening ...e7-e5 so we can't wait with d2-d4. } 4. d4
cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5
{ Black is fighting for the dark squares. This interesting move has been repeatedly used by Vladislav Artemiev, one of the most interesting players of the new generation. }
6. Nf5
{ The calmer  6.Nc2  would allow Black to go  6...Bc5  , with decent chances. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3 d5
{ Objectively, the strongest continuation. Pushing the Pawn to d5 is quite a typical reaction to White's Knight moving to f5. }
8. cxd5 Nxe4
{ A rare move but it was played by Aleksandra Goryachkina. Black is using the fact that after  9.Nxe4  Bxf5  , the  Knight on e4 will be attacked as well. }
9. Nxg7+ Bxg7 10. Nxe4 Nd4 11. Nc3 O-O
{ The last couple of moves were rather obvious. Black has a strong Knight but it is not enough to compensate for the damaged Pawn structure. }
12. Bd3 f5 13. O-O f4 { Otherwise, White was ready to move the Bishop to e3. }
14. f3
{ Stopping the f4-Pawn and securing White's control over the e4-squrae. } 14...
Rf6
{ So war we were following the game Brankovic-Goryachkina, Titled Tuesday 2021. }
15. Rf2
{ White is now ready to meet  15...Rh6  with  16.g4!  In fact, we could have  played 15.g4 right away but I prefer to wait for ...Rf6-h6 first. Otherwise, we can move the Bishop to d2, the Rook to c1 − White still has useful moves. Long-term, we should try to simplify the position. The Knight vs. the dark-squared Bishop ending would be a dream, but to be honest, any minor piece will do well against it. }
