[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Sicilian − Various 2nd Moves"]
[Black "Sicilian 2.Nf3 g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ I have had a small dilemma here. Advancing the Pawn to g6 on the second move is not very popular, so we don't expect to meet it too often. Therefore, I was rather reluctant to enter the Maroczy Bind − it is a big system with many possible setups for Black. Why do all this work when we might not need it all?  I like challenges, but once I started checking the Maroczy, I got quickly discouraged. It is pretty healthy for Black, and proving White's advantage turned out to be more difficult than I expected. I decided to try  3.c3  instead. It is a much smaller line, but it doesn't mean it's worse, it's just different. White definitely has some chances for advantage, so perhaps it's simply a good line. }
3. c3 d5 4. e5 a6
{ It's a rare move but it was used many times by the Uzbek grandmaster, Jakhongir Vakhidov and then his countryman and the surprising World Rapid Champion from Warsaw 2022, Nodirbek Abdusattorov used it as well.   4...Bg7  5.d4  a6  6.Be2  transposes. }
5. d4 Bg7
{ Black doesn't need to worry about Bf1-b5+ now but is it worth a tempo?  5...Nc6  6.Be2  f6  7.O-O  Bg7  transposes. }
6. Be2 f6 7. O-O Nc6 8. exf6 Nxf6 9. dxc5
{ Why not? It is a free Pawn after all. } 9... O-O 10. Bg5 e5 11. c4
{ White wants to win the light squares. } 11... d4 12. Nfd2 Bf5 13. Bf3
{ White is slightly better. We will take on f6 and place the Pawns on a3 and b4. The Knight belongs to e4. }
*

