[White "20. Sicilian − Various 2nd Moves"]
[Black "Sicilian 2.Nf3 g6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ I have had a small dilemma here. Advancing the Pawn to g6 on the second move is not very popular, so we don't expect to meet it too often. Therefore, I was rather reluctant to enter the Maroczy Bind − it is a big system with many possible setups for Black. Why do all this work when we might not need it all?  I like challenges, but once I started checking the Maroczy, I got quickly discouraged. It is pretty healthy for Black, and proving White's advantage turned out to be more difficult than I expected. I decided to try  3.c3  instead. It is a much smaller line, but it doesn't mean it's worse, it's just different. White definitely has some chances for advantage, so perhaps it's simply a good line. }
3. c3 d5 4. e5 d4
{ This idea is frequently seen in the Sicilians. Black is preventing us from completing our desired Pawn chain. However, now Black's Pawns will be exposed while White gains some nice squares in the center. }
5. Bb5+ Bd7 { 5...Nd7?!  6.e6! } 6. Bxd7+ Nxd7 7. Na3
{ The Knight will come to c4. } 7... e6 8. O-O Ne7 9. Nc4 Nc6 10. d3 b5
{ Black could not develop the Bishop freely, it had to control the d6-square, while  10...Be7  would be met with  11.Bh6  . }
11. Nd6+ Bxd6 12. exd6 O-O
{ 12...dxc3  13.bxc3  O-O  14.Bh6  Re8  15.a4  b4  16.d4!  and White is clearly better. }
13. cxd4 Nxd4
{ After  13...cxd4  ,  the Knight on c6 would become the  target:  14.Bh6  Re8  15.Rc1  . }
14. Nxd4 cxd4 15. Qg4
{ After  15...Qb6  16.Bf4  , the Queen  on g4 is preventing Black from playing ...e6-e5. White has the initiative. }
*

