Qb6 { Black wants to recapture with the Queen. } 6. Bxc6+ Qxc6 7. O-O Bg4
{ After  7...Bf5  8.d3  , the Bishop would be  misplaced on f5 − this square belongs to the Knight. }
8. d4
{ The main position of the line. It resembles the Caro-Kann more than Sicilian but it's okay. }
8... e6 9. dxc5 { 9.h3  is also possible. } 9... Bxf3
{ Forcing White to recapture with the Queen. } 10. Qxf3 Qxc5 11. Nd2
{ We want to bring the Knight to d4 but c3-c4 is also a sound idea. } 11... Bg7
12. c4 Ne7
{ 12...Bxe5?  13.cxd5  and Black can't recapture the Pawn as the e-file would open. }
13. cxd5 exd5 { Now Black controls the e4-square. } 14. Nb3 Qc7
{ From here the Queen protects the Knight. } 15. Bf4 O-O 16. Rfe1 Nc6
{ Black is close to equalizing here and in order to put any pressure we need to play accurately. }
17. Rac1
{ 17.Qxd5  Rfe8  and Black will win the Pawn back.  We can now go Qf3-g3 and bring the Knight to d3. Then one idea is to retreat the Bishop to d2 and push the f2-Pawn, while another one is to go h2-h4. Once we provoke ...h7-h6 then e5-e6 ideas will get stronger. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Sicilian − Various 2nd Moves"]
[Black "Sicilian 2.Nf3 g6 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ I have had a small dilemma here. Advancing the Pawn to g6 on the second move is not very popular, so we don't expect to meet it too often. Therefore, I was rather reluctant to enter the Maroczy Bind − it is a big system with many possible setups for Black. Why do all this work when we might not need it all?  I like challenges, but once I started checking the Maroczy, I got quickly discouraged. It is pretty healthy for Black, and proving White's advantage turned out to be more difficult than I expected. I decided to try  3.c3  instead. It is a much smaller line, but it doesn't mean it's worse, it's just different. White definitely has some chances for advantage, so perhaps it's simply a good line. }
3. c3 d5 4. e5 Nc6
{ The most natural move.  4...Bg4  5.Bb5+  Nc6  6.Bxc6+  transposes. } 5. Bb5
Qb6 { Black wants to recapture with the Queen. } 6. Bxc6+ Qxc6 7. O-O Bg4
{ After  7...Bf5  8.d3  , the Bishop would be  misplaced on f5 − this square belongs to the Knight. }
8. d4
{ The main position of the line. It resembles the Caro-Kann more than Sicilian but it's okay. }
8... e6 9. dxc5 { 9.h3  is also possible. } 9... Bxf3
{ Forcing White to recapture with the Queen. } 10. Qxf3 Qxc5 11. Nd2
{ We want to bring the Knight to d4 but c3-c4 is also a sound idea. } 11... Ne7
{ This move order is clearly directed against c3-c4, however, Black doesn't put any pressure on the e5-Pawn. }
12. Nb3 Qc7 13. Nd4
{ The Pawn is poisoned:  13...Qxe5?  14.Nb5!  and Black is in trouble. } 13...
Nc6
{ 13...Nf5  14.Bf4  and the  Knight is not so well placed on f5. Black has to consider Nd4xf5 all the time while if Black takes on d4, then after c3xd4, White will always have some pressure due to the weakness of the dark squares in Black's camp. }
14. Nb5 Qd7 15. Qg3 Na5
{ Kicking our Knight back. From Black's perspective, it's an important nuance.  15...a6  16.Nd6+  Bxd6  17.exd6  would be nice for White.  17...O-O  18.b3  and the Bishop can protect  the Pawn from a3. After the text move, we can't go for the same line as Black would have ...Na5-c4. }
16. Nd4 h6 17. h4
{ White is slightly better. Black can't freely castle short which means castle long should be played. White has the following plan then: b2-b3, move the Rook to d3, the Bishop to e3, double the Rooks on the d-file, and then c2-c4. }
