[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. Steinitz 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.e5 Nfd7 − 7.Be3 7th Moves"]
[Black "Steinitz 3.Nc3 Nf6 − 7.Be3 b6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... Nf6
{ The Classical Variation is considered the second-best line against 3.Nc3, behind  3...Bb4  . With  3...Nf6  Black  provokes e4-e5, hoping to undermine White's Pawn center with ...c7-c5. }
4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4
{ Before developing the Knight, it is a good idea to improve our Pawn center. }
5... c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3
{ In most of the lines in the Steinitz Variation, the biggest part of the action is focused around the d4-square. It is our most exposed asset, so it makes sense for Black to target it. However, this isn't enough, usually. Therefore, Black often tries to attack us from the other side: ...f7-f6 or even ...g7-g5 are quite common in this line. Anything that could destroy our powerful center will bring Black's attention.  As you have probably noticed, I am focusing on Black attacking White, shouldn't it be quite the opposite? It seems that Black has given White so much in the beginning that our main task in the opening @@StartBracket@@with some natural exceptions@@EndBracket@@ will be to hold it − this is all we need. }
7... b6
{ A bad move. These are the main plans for Black on the Queenside: bringing the Queen to b6, advancing the Pawns with ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5 or simply exchanging pieces on the d4-square. In this regard, Black's last move is only interrupting.  The only possible explanation is that Black wants to develop the dark-squared Bishop without worrying about d4xc5 as now there is ...b6xc5. However, given that there is no pressure on the d4-Pawn, we are completely fine with it. }
8. h4
{ The most accurate, although almost any move would be better for White here. }
8... Be7 9. Bb5
{ Not only a tempo move but also we don't mind swapping the Bishop at some point. }
9... Qc7 { 9...Bb7  would be met with the same reaction. } 10. h5
{ 10.Qe2  or  10.Qd2  was also possible. } 10... h6
{ Black is stopping our h-pawn. After  10...O-O  we could just go  11.Qd2  and it's not clear how Black should react.  11...a6  12.Bxc6  Qxc6  13.g4  gives White a powerful attack while @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/p1qnbppp/1pn1p3/1BppP2P/3P1P2/2N1BN2/PPPQ2P1/R3K2R b KQ - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...cxd4  12.Nxd4  is just miserable. }
11. Bxc6 { This gives White a comfortable edge. } 11... Qxc6 12. Qe2
{ 12.Qd2  is possible too but, this is more accurate, preventing 12...Ba6. }
12... Bb7
{ 12...a5  would be met by  13.a4  Ba6  14.Nb5  with a big advantage. } 13. g4
{ White has a clear edge. The only thing to remember is not to rush the long castle. For instance  13.O-O-O?!  c4!  followed by  14.--  b5  and Black is getting some reasonable counterplay.  Our plan is to achieve f4-f5 or g4-g5 but before that, we might consider Be3-f2-h4 − swapping the dark-squared Bishops is always a good idea. }
*

