11. Nxd4 Nxd4 { A better choice compared with  11...a6  . } 12. Bxd4 Be7
{ Black is waiting for White to move the Bishop first. } 13. Bd3 Nb8
{ Now it actually makes sense! In the database, you will find lots of games after  13...O-O  14.O-O  . Black tried many moves but the result was the same: White's advantage was huge. With 13...Nb8, at least Black is trying to fight. }
14. O-O Nc6 15. Bf2
{ 15.Bb5  would be too much.  15...O-O  16.Bxc6  Qxc6  17.Nc5  b6!  and the Bishop gets out just in time. }
15... b6
{ 15...O-O?  allows  16.b5!  Na5  17.b6!  with an enormous advantage, for example,  17...axb6  18.Nxb6  Rb8  19.f5! }
16. Rc1
{ White is better. We want to advance the Pawn to c4, so we will first prepare it with a2-a3. }
