{ This is stronger than  15.g3  . Development is the most important factor in the position. }
15... b5 16. Nb2 gxf4 17. O-O
{ Once again, development first. White's @@StartBracket@@winning@@EndBracket@@ advantage is based on the superiority of the pieces and on the weakness of the dark squares in Black's camp. Our Knights are not so great but their positions can easily be improved while Black's light-squared Bishop is just useless.  To make it more clear: if you change the position of Black's Bishop from c8 to e7, then there will be no problems at all, perhaps Black will even fight for the advantage here. With the Bishop on c8, Black's position is just hopeless. }
17... Nxe5 18. Rxf4
{ We can bring the Knight to f3 neutralizing Black's only active piece. Black's King is terribly weak, the pieces have no coordination, and Black won't be able to fix these problems within the next few moves. }
