Na4 { The only good reaction. } 8... Qa5+ 9. c3
{ No need to worry about the Knight, it is not going to get lost. } 9... c4
{ Forcing our hand... } 10. b4 Qc7
{ This leads to an easy game for White who has a great space advantage. } 11.
Be2 { There are no urgent businesses so we can just finish our development. }
11... Be7
{ 11...b5  should be met with  12.Nc5  .  In principle, ...b7-b5 should be met with Na4-c5. For this reason, we should keep the Knight on a4. }
12. O-O O-O
{ The last two moves were not forced but I wanted to show you how to proceed in this kind of position. There are many moves of course and our general plan is to attack on the Kingside, with g2-g4 being a natural beginning of it. However, the immediate  13.g4?!  would be answered with  13...b5!  14.Nc5  Nxc5  and both  15.dxc5  a5  16.a3  f6!  and @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/p1q1bppp/2n1p3/1pnpP3/1PpP1PP1/2P1BN2/P3B2P/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.bxc5  b4  , give Black undeserved counterplay. }
13. Qd2
{ After this quiet improving move, White needs not to worry about ...b7-b5 anymore.   After  13...b5  14.Nc5  Nxc5  15.bxc5  is fine as there is  no ...b5-b4.  15.dxc5  might be even stronger.  15...a5  16.a3  f6  no longer works.  17.Nd4!  fxe5  18.fxe5!  with great advantage. Notice how useful our 13th move is: the dark-squared Bishop is defended, the Rooks are connected, and everything is in harmony.   Naturally,  13...b5  is not forced but how else can Black continue?! It is not a problem for White as we have many good moves,  both prophylactic @@StartBracket@@such as a2-a3, which is always useful@@EndBracket@@ and attacking. Here the list is much longer: g2-g4, h2-h4, or Kg1-h1. Even Be2-d1-c2 doesn't seem that slow. }
