{ Since ...b6-b5 was a threat, we didn't really have a choice either.  11.b3  b5  would be fine for Black. }
11... Qa6
{ I can't really understand Black's attraction to this line. White basically gets a freeroll on the Kingside and there is not much to worry about on the other side. We only need to be always ready to meet ...b6-b5 with Na4-c5 and if Black takes on c5 then there is no rule as both b4xc5 and d4xc5 might be okay, depending on the circumstances.  I would only like to point out two things to consider: if the black Queen is still on a6 and we recapture with the b-pawn, then he might move it to a3, preparing b5-b4. This is an argument for d4xc5 but also for the prophylactic a2-a3, which takes away an a3-square from the Queen and is a useful move in general. The second thing is that after recapturing with the d-pawn, we should be ready to face ...f7-f6. }
12. Be2 Be7 13. O-O
{ There are too many moves for both sides to go any deeper. White has a big advantage and the plan in most @@StartBracket@@perhaps all@@EndBracket@@ cases will involve advancing the Kingside Pawns.   After  13...Qb7  , we might consider waiting for a bit, let's see if Black intends to castle at all. We can make some little useful moves like  14.Qc2  or  14.Qe1  .  Once our Queen has left its starting position Na4-b2-d1-e3 seems like a nice maneuver.  And in case of @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/p2nbppp/qpn1p3/3pP3/NPpP1P2/2P2N2/P2BB1PP/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 4 13@@EndFEN@@  13...O-O  , we can just push  14.g4  . }
