{ The only serious move. Black is gaining space on the Queenside. The Bishop can now be developed to b7 but, as you will see, it is not the only upside. }
12. Bxc5
{ The most direct way of moving forward. We want to develop our Bishop to d3 and for that, the Knight on c5 had to be gone. Notice that  12.Qf2  would be met with  12...Na4! }
12... Bxc5 13. Bd3 f6
{ A reasonable choice but with the Pawn on g2, White should be easily better. }
14. exf6 Rxf6
{ 14...Qxf6  wouldn't improve Black's position. Both  15.Ne2  and  15.g3  are much better for White. }
15. Rhe1
{ The Pawn structure has changed and White is no longer obliged to attack on the Kingside as we can also play in the center. }
15... b4 16. Na4
{ Once more, the Knight is useful here as it is blocking the black Pawns. }
16... Bd6 17. g3
{ White has a big advantage. we can bring the Knight to g5 provoking ...h7-h6 and then random tricks might appear, for instance, Bd3-h7+ and Ng5-e4. Also, we can try h2-h4 and Nf3-h2-g4 or simply move the Queen to e3, preparing Na4-c5. }
