11. dxc5 f6
{ The most natural response. Black is trying to undermine our Pawn center. }
12. exf6
{ The more aggressive  12.O-O-O  fxe5  13.Qg3  was also possible but we are trying to avoid complications when simple means are sufficient. }
12... Nxf6 13. Qd2
{ Black was threatening ...Nf6-g4, as well as ...e6-e5, and our last move defends against both. }
13... Qa5
{ Black is intending to win our c5-Pawn without moving the Knight from f6. }
14. Ne2
{ But this allows us to regroup, solve the problem of the c3-Knight and take control over the d4-square. }
14... b4 15. Ned4 Nxd4 16. Bxd4
{ If it can't be attacked by the Knight, it's generally better to take with the Bishop. }
16... Bxc5 { Now the only problem for White is how to continue. } 17. Qe3
{ Controlling the center is the key. White is not worried about  17...Ng4  18.Qg1!  while after @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/6pp/p3pn2/q1bp4/1p1B1P2/3BQN2/PPP3PP/R3K2R b KQ - 1 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Bxd4  18.Nxd4  , we have a clear edge. }
