[Black "Steinitz 8.Qd2 a6 9.Bd3 O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... Nf6
{ The Classical Variation is considered the second-best line against 3.Nc3, behind  3...Bb4  . With  3...Nf6  Black  provokes e4-e5, hoping to undermine White's Pawn center with ...c7-c5. }
4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4
{ Before developing the Knight, it is a good idea to improve our Pawn center. }
5... c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3
{ In most of the lines in the Steinitz Variation, the biggest part of the action is focused around the d4-square. It is our most exposed asset, so it makes sense for Black to target it. However, this isn't enough, usually. Therefore, Black often tries to attack us from the other side: ...f7-f6 or even ...g7-g5 are quite common in this line. Anything that could destroy our powerful center will bring Black's attention.  As you have probably noticed, I am focusing on Black attacking White, shouldn't it be quite the opposite? It seems that Black has given White so much in the beginning that our main task in the opening @@StartBracket@@with some natural exceptions@@EndBracket@@ will be to hold it − this is all we need. }
7... Be7 8. Qd2 a6
{ Black is preparing the b-Pawn advance while delaying castling. } 9. Bd3
{ 9.Be2  is much more popular but I am not sure why.  The Bishop on d3 works clearly better against Black's typical setups simply because the Bishop is better placed on d3. }
9... O-O
{ Objectively the best but I don't think you will find too many opponents who will willingly enter this wild line. }
10. dxc5 Nxc5
{ 10...Bxc5  is no difference as Black falls under the same tactical shot with  11.Bxh7+  Kxh7  12.Bxc5  Nxc5  13.Qf2  and Black is unable to defend  the Knight on c5 and parry the Ng5 idea at the same time. }
11. Bxh7+
{ Once again, we are using this typical motif.  11.Bxc5  Bxc5  12.Bxh7  Kxh7  would transpose. The next moves are forced. }
11... Kxh7 12. Bxc5 Bxc5 13. Ng5+ Kg8 14. Qd3 f5 { A losing mistake. } 15. Qh3
Rf7
{ Black might think that this is a saving resource. Now after  16.Qh7+  Kf8  there is no good follow-up for White. }
16. O-O-O
{ Securing our own King is nice but also new motifs will now appear. } 16...
Kf8 { The best attempt − the black King is trying to leave the danger zone. }
17. Qh5 { The Rook cannot move due to Qh5-h8+. } 17... Qe8
{ After  17...g6  , instead of  18.Qxg6  Qe7  where things are not that simple, we could play @@StartFEN@@r1bq1k2/1p3r2/p1n1p1p1/2bpPpNQ/5P2/2N5/PPP3PP/2KR3R w - - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18.Qh8+!  Ke7  19.Nxf7  with a winning position. The point is that after  19...Qxh8  20.Nxh8  the Knight will come out. }
18. Rhe1
{ We want to sacrifice the Knight or even the Rook on d5 and then push the e-pawn. It's a deadly threat and one that cannot be stopped. }
18... Nd8 { This only makes things easier. } 19. Rxd5
{ This is even stronger than  19.Nxd5  . } 19... Bb6
{ 19...exd5  20.Nxd5  and Black can't prevent mate. } 20. Rxd8 Bxd8 21. Nd5
{ Beautiful tactics! One way or another we are forcing Black to take on d5. }
21... exd5 22. e6
{ 22...Bxe6  is losing to  23.Qh8+  Ke7  24.Rxe6  while @@StartFEN@@r1bbqk2/1p3rp1/p3P3/3p1pNQ/5P2/8/PPP3PP/2K1R3 b - - 0 22@@EndFEN@@  22...Bxg5  meets a similar end:  23.Qh8+  Ke7  24.exf7+  . }
22... Rc7 23. e7+ { White will mate on the next move. } *

