{ 9.Be2  is much more popular but I am not sure why.  The Bishop on d3 works clearly better against Black's typical setups simply because the Bishop is better placed on d3. }
9... O-O
{ Objectively the best but I don't think you will find too many opponents who will willingly enter this wild line. }
10. dxc5 Nxc5
{ 10...Bxc5  is no difference as Black falls under the same tactical shot with  11.Bxh7+  Kxh7  12.Bxc5  Nxc5  13.Qf2  and Black is unable to defend  the Knight on c5 and parry the Ng5 idea at the same time. }
11. Bxh7+
{ Once again, we are using this typical motif.  11.Bxc5  Bxc5  12.Bxh7  Kxh7  would transpose. The next moves are forced. }
11... Kxh7 12. Bxc5 Bxc5 13. Ng5+ Kg8 14. Qd3 f5 { A losing mistake. } 15. Qh3
Rf7
{ Black might think that this is a saving resource. Now after  16.Qh7+  Kf8  there is no good follow-up for White. }
16. O-O-O
{ Securing our own King is nice but also new motifs will now appear. } 16...
Kf8 { The best attempt − the black King is trying to leave the danger zone. }
17. Qh5 { The Rook cannot move due to Qh5-h8+. } 17... Qe8
{ After  17...g6  , instead of  18.Qxg6  Qe7  where things are not that simple, we could play @@StartFEN@@r1bq1k2/1p3r2/p1n1p1p1/2bpPpNQ/5P2/2N5/PPP3PP/2KR3R w - - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18.Qh8+!  Ke7  19.Nxf7  with a winning position. The point is that after  19...Qxh8  20.Nxh8  the Knight will come out. }
18. Rhe1
{ We want to sacrifice the Knight or even the Rook on d5 and then push the e-pawn. It's a deadly threat and one that cannot be stopped. }
18... Nd4 { At least now we can't take with the Rook. } 19. Nxd5
{ Nevertheless, this is good enough. } 19... exd5 20. e6 Bxe6
{ 20...Nxe6  21.Rxd5  and with Rd8 coming, Black is dead lost. } 21. Rxe6 Nxe6
22. Re1
{ A surprising resource! White is winning as there is no defense against Qh5-h8+ and Re1xe6+.  22...Rf6  23.Qh8+  Ke7  24.Qxg7+  . }
