18. Ne2
{ I had a hard time deciding what the best try would be here and eventually decided to settle for this one.  18.Rd3  would be another possibility. }
18... Bc5 { There is no fun for Black having to be nice all the time. } 19.
Rhe1
{ This wasn't the only try, but it's very dangerous and less obvious than  19.Qh8+  or  19.c4  . Naturally, we are assuming our opponent willingly entered this sharp line, otherwise, any of these moves should do the job. }
19... Ke7
{ Basically, the only move I can think of, but at the same time, it is not an easy decision. Black has to evacuate the King. }
20. Nc3
{ 20.Qxf7+  Kd8  wasn't worth it. With the text move, White is intending to strike in the center. }
20... d4
{ Another bold decision. Not only is Black allowing  21.Nce4  but also... } 21.
Nd5+ { Nice trick! } 21... exd5 22. Qxf7+ Kd8 23. Qxd5+ Bd7
{ All of Black's moves are forced. } 24. Qxc5 Bg4
{ An extremely difficult move for Black to find, leaving the King exposed in the center. However, the problem for Black is that there wasn't a good way to defend against the Ng5-f7+ threat.   24...Re7  was possible but then  25.g3!  and White is  threatening e5-e6, so it seems that anyway  Black has to go  25...Bg4  . After  26.Rd2  we are reaching a similar position but, as  we go down the main line, you will quickly understand why Black does not want the Rook on e7. }
25. Rd2 Qe7
{ It's clear now. The Queen's move is essential for Black's survival. The problem with the immediate  25...Kc8  was that after  26.h3!  there was no good square for the Bishop.  26...Be6  27.Nxe6  Rxe6  28.Qf8+  Qd8  29.Qxd8+  Kxd8  30.c3  winning another Pawn. }
26. Qb6+ Kc8 { 26...Qc7?  27.Qb3! } 27. h3 Be6 28. Nf3
{ We will win the Pawn on d4 but with a Bishop, Black should be able to hold this position. Naturally, White is pressing here. }
