9. Qd2 Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Bxd4 11. Qxd4 Qb6
{ Probably the most straightforward way of simplifying the position that Black can choose. }
12. Nb5
{ 12.Qxb6  is more popular but objectively weaker.  Dragging the Knight to b6 only makes it easier for Black as the d7-square will be quickly occupied by the Bishop, while the Knight's position can be easily improved @@StartBracket@@...Nb6-a4-c5, ...Nb6-c4 or even ...Nb6-c8-e7@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Qxd4 13. Nxd4 Ke7 14. h4
{ This Pawn advance is quite typical, however, in this case, the timing is essential. For instance, if White starts with  14.O-O-O  instead, then after  14...Nc5  15.h4  , Black can go  15...h5  , neutralizing a part of White's initiative.   In case you wondered, I could easily recommend  14.Bd3  Nc5  15.Kd2  here, finishing the line as better for White, but I think it is always good to go a bit deeper, especially when long-term plans are involved. }
14... h5 { Let's see why  14...h5  is not the best choice now. } 15. Rh3
{ It turns out that now Black is unable to finish development normally as the white Rook interferes. }
15... Nc5
{ Without White's Rook on h3, this would be the most natural way of developing, but now it's just a losing mistake. }
16. Rc3 Nd7
{ A sad necessity. After  16...Ne4  17.Rc7+  , White is completely winning while @@StartFEN@@r1b4r/pp2kpp1/4p3/2npP2p/3N1P1P/2R5/PPP3P1/R3KB2 b Q - 3 16@@EndFEN@@  16...b6  17.b4  only makes it easier. }
17. a4
{ The most accurate way. The Pawn will further restrict Black's activity on the Queenside while the Queen's Rook is ready to enter the game via a3. }
17... f6 { Trying to get any counterplay at all. } 18. Rc7
{ The Rook cannot be easily thrown back as the e6-Pawn needs to be defended first. }
18... fxe5 19. fxe5 Re8 { Black is preparing ...Ke7-d8. } 20. Bb5
{ Once again,  20...Kd8  is not possible, this time due to  21.Bxd7  . } 20...
Rb8 21. Ra3 Kd8 22. Rcc3
{ After  22...Re7  , White can defend the Pawn with  23.Re3  . Huge positional trumps @@StartBracket@@there are so many weaknesses in Black's camp!@@EndBracket@@ combined with a huge lead in development gives White a winning advantage. }
