{ In most of the lines in the Steinitz Variation, the biggest part of the action is focused around the d4-square. It is our most exposed asset, so it makes sense for Black to target it. However, this isn't enough, usually. Therefore, Black often tries to attack us from the other side: ...f7-f6 or even ...g7-g5 are quite common in this line. Anything that could destroy our powerful center will bring Black's attention.  As you have probably noticed, I am focusing on Black attacking White, shouldn't it be quite the opposite? It seems that Black has given White so much in the beginning that our main task in the opening @@StartBracket@@with some natural exceptions@@EndBracket@@ will be to hold it − this is all we need. }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bc5
{ This continuation gained some popularity in the nineties as it was frequently used by French experts such as Mikhail Gurevich and Evgenij Bareev. Black's plan of clearing the situation in the center and subsequently developing the dark-squared Bishop to the square from which it will very likely be exchanged, basically states that Black is okay with being slightly worse in a typical position @@StartBracket@@for example, the ending with the light-squared  Bishops on d3 and c8/b7/d7 and the Knights on d4 and c5/d7@@EndBracket@@. In my opinion, this is a sad statement. }
9. Qd2 Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Bxd4 11. Qxd4 Qb6
{ Probably the most straightforward way of simplifying the position that Black can choose. }
12. Nb5
{ 12.Qxb6  is more popular but objectively weaker.  Dragging the Knight to b6 only makes it easier for Black as the d7-square will be quickly occupied by the Bishop, while the Knight's position can be easily improved @@StartBracket@@...Nb6-a4-c5, ...Nb6-c4 or even ...Nb6-c8-e7@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Qxd4 13. Nxd4 Ke7 14. h4
{ This Pawn advance is quite typical, however, in this case, the timing is essential. For instance, if White starts with  14.O-O-O  instead, then after  14...Nc5  15.h4  , Black can go  15...h5  , neutralizing a part of White's initiative.   In case you wondered, I could easily recommend  14.Bd3  Nc5  15.Kd2  here, finishing the line as better for White, but I think it is always good to go a bit deeper, especially when long-term plans are involved. }
14... f6
{ Reacting in the center makes sense, however, Black doesn't have enough forces to create serious counterplay. }
15. Nf3
{ 15.exf6+  is possible, but keeping the center is healthier, in my opinion. }
15... fxe5 16. fxe5 Nc5
{ At least now Black doesn't have to worry about Rh3-c3. } 17. Bd3 Bd7 18. Kd2
{ White has a typical advantage. We can bring the King's Rook to the g-file. It would be perfectly placed on g4 from where it could operate on the whole board @@StartBracket@@Rg4-b4, for instance@@EndBracket@@. }
*

