7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bc5
{ This continuation gained some popularity in the nineties as it was frequently used by French experts such as Mikhail Gurevich and Evgenij Bareev. Black's plan of clearing the situation in the center and subsequently developing the dark-squared Bishop to the square from which it will very likely be exchanged, basically states that Black is okay with being slightly worse in a typical position @@StartBracket@@for example, the ending with the light-squared  Bishops on d3 and c8/b7/d7 and the Knights on d4 and c5/d7@@EndBracket@@. In my opinion, this is a sad statement. }
9. Qd2 Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Bxd4 11. Qxd4 Qb6
{ Probably the most straightforward way of simplifying the position that Black can choose. }
12. Nb5
{ 12.Qxb6  is more popular but objectively weaker.  Dragging the Knight to b6 only makes it easier for Black as the d7-square will be quickly occupied by the Bishop, while the Knight's position can be easily improved @@StartBracket@@...Nb6-a4-c5, ...Nb6-c4 or even ...Nb6-c8-e7@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Qxd4 13. Nxd4 Ke7 14. h4
{ This Pawn advance is quite typical, however, in this case, the timing is essential. For instance, if White starts with  14.O-O-O  instead, then after  14...Nc5  15.h4  , Black can go  15...h5  , neutralizing a part of White's initiative.   In case you wondered, I could easily recommend  14.Bd3  Nc5  15.Kd2  here, finishing the line as better for White, but I think it is always good to go a bit deeper, especially when long-term plans are involved. }
14... Nc5
{ Once you see what happens after  14...h5  15.Rh3  Nc5  16.Rc3!  , this seems reasonable. There is a cost, though. White can grab space on the Kingside. }
15. h5 Bd7 16. Kd2
{ We don't need to worry about  16...Ne4+  as White can go  17.Ke3  followed by 18.Bd3, kicking the Knight back. Having said that, @@StartFEN@@r6r/pp1bkppp/4p3/2npP2P/3N1P2/8/PPP3P1/R3KB1R w KQ - 1 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Bd3  would be equally strong and most likely transpose.  If Black stands still, then we can develop the Bishop to d3 and then further advance the h-pawn, fixing Black's weakness on h7. }
16... g5
{ Let's see what to do if Black doesn't wait. Taking  17.fxg5  is out of the question. Black will easily win the Pawn back and we will only be left with weaknesses on e5, h5, and g2. }
17. hxg6 hxg6 18. Bd3 Rag8 { Once again, Black is trying to get ...g6-g5 in. }
19. Nf3
{ Not this time... White has a long-term advantage, although converting it won't be easy as there is limited material on board. We would be happy to advance the Pawn to g5, fixing Black's Pawns on the light squares. This would also create the opportunity to install the Rook on h6 and, subsequently, win the dispute over the h-file.  After that, the Knight can start jumping − there are new outposts available: f6 and h6 @@StartBracket@@f7-Pawn!@@EndBracket@@. In general, the Knight doesn't belong to f3, it only has a work to do there @@StartBracket@@stopping ...g6-g5@@EndBracket@@, so don't feel too attached to this location. }
