{ This continuation gained some popularity in the nineties as it was frequently used by French experts such as Mikhail Gurevich and Evgenij Bareev. Black's plan of clearing the situation in the center and subsequently developing the dark-squared Bishop to the square from which it will very likely be exchanged, basically states that Black is okay with being slightly worse in a typical position @@StartBracket@@for example, the ending with the light-squared  Bishops on d3 and c8/b7/d7 and the Knights on d4 and c5/d7@@EndBracket@@. In my opinion, this is a sad statement. }
9. Qd2 O-O
{ Historically, this is one of the main lines, but it seems that it is exactly where this line is heading − history. It is just not doing very well. }
10. O-O-O Qe7
{ Objectively, a weak continuation, but it has been used by a few great players in the past, with Viktor Korchnoi among them, so let's see a few moves. }
11. Kb1 { 11.Be2  would be also fine. } 11... f6
{ The point of Black's previous move. Some players tried  11...Nxd4  here, but it makes no sense to me, it just looks like a worse version of the @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1n1ppp/2n1p3/2bpP3/3N1P2/2N1B3/PPPQ2PP/2KR1B1R b - - 4 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nxd4  11.Bxd4  a6  line. }
12. exf6 Qxf6 13. Ncb5
{ White's position in the center is secured, plus Black has to watch out for Nb5-c7. After  13...Nxd4  14.Nxd4  e5  @@StartBracket@@what else?@@EndBracket@@  15.fxe5  Nxe5  , we can go  16.h3  with a great advantage, as Black will most likely lose the isolani sooner or later. All this was great, but by no means necessary. The simple @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp1n2pp/2n1pq2/2bp4/3N1P2/2N1B3/PPPQ2PP/1K1R1B1R w - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.g3  would also be clearly better for White. }
