[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Steinitz 7.Be3 cxd4 8.Nxd4 Bb4/Bc5"]
[Black "Steinitz 8.Nxd4 Bc5 9.Qd2 O-O #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... Nf6
{ The Classical Variation is considered the second-best line against 3.Nc3, behind  3...Bb4  . With  3...Nf6  Black  provokes e4-e5, hoping to undermine White's Pawn center with ...c7-c5. }
4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4
{ Before developing the Knight, it is a good idea to improve our Pawn center. }
5... c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3
{ In most of the lines in the Steinitz Variation, the biggest part of the action is focused around the d4-square. It is our most exposed asset, so it makes sense for Black to target it. However, this isn't enough, usually. Therefore, Black often tries to attack us from the other side: ...f7-f6 or even ...g7-g5 are quite common in this line. Anything that could destroy our powerful center will bring Black's attention.  As you have probably noticed, I am focusing on Black attacking White, shouldn't it be quite the opposite? It seems that Black has given White so much in the beginning that our main task in the opening @@StartBracket@@with some natural exceptions@@EndBracket@@ will be to hold it − this is all we need. }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bc5
{ This continuation gained some popularity in the nineties as it was frequently used by French experts such as Mikhail Gurevich and Evgenij Bareev. Black's plan of clearing the situation in the center and subsequently developing the dark-squared Bishop to the square from which it will very likely be exchanged, basically states that Black is okay with being slightly worse in a typical position @@StartBracket@@for example, the ending with the light-squared  Bishops on d3 and c8/b7/d7 and the Knights on d4 and c5/d7@@EndBracket@@. In my opinion, this is a sad statement. }
9. Qd2 O-O
{ Historically, this is one of the main lines, but it seems that it is exactly where this line is heading − history. It is just not doing very well. }
10. O-O-O a6
{ The most logical follow-up. White can't develop the Bishop to d3 while, compared with the  10...Nxd4  11.Bxd4  a6  line,  the e3-square is not available for the Queen. }
11. Nb3
{ However, this turns out to be really strong. Not only do we welcome the dark-squared Bishop's trade, but also retreating the Knight from d4 releases some tension in the center, making it easier for White to develop the remaining pieces. }
11... Be7
{ Ambitious, but now the race is about to start and White is going to be faster. }
12. h4 b5
{ If you ever meet  12...a5?  @@StartBracket@@here or in a similar position@@EndBracket@@, usually the simple  13.a3  a4  14.Nd4  is enough, leaving Black with no perspectives on the Queenside. }
13. h5
{ It is a very important moment, as remembering our lines means an easy advantage while forgetting them quite likely means losing control. So the big question is: how to remember them?  The main plan for Black is to bring the Knight to b6, develop the Bishop to d7, and then perhaps ...b5-b4 will be possible or, in some cases, ...Nb6-c4. However, we should not forget about ...f7-f6.   Therefore, I prefer to keep our Bishop on f1 for a bit longer and move the King to b1 instead. In some cases, ...f7-f6 won't be possible because of Nc3xd5!, while in others it will be weaker, as you shall see. }
13... Qc7
{ A flexible move as it enables ...f7-f6, while ...Ra8-b8 and ...Nd7-b6 are still possible. }
14. Kb1
{ 14.Bd3  f6!  wouldn't be so clear. But how is our choice any better? } 14...
f6
{ Let's now see how a small nuance such as moving the King to b1 instead of the Bishop to d3, can make a real difference. }
15. exf6 Nxf6 16. h6 g6 { This is rather automatic. } 17. Be2
{ This is the first difference. The Bishop is now controlling the g4-square, while we want to improve its position further by moving it to f3, from where it would also control the sensitive e4-square. There is also another, less obvious difference.  With the King on c1, Black could have now played ...Nc6-a5, creating some real counterplay on the Queenside @@StartBracket@@...Na5-c4 or ...Bc8-d7 and ...b5-b4 look really serious, don't they?@@EndBracket@@.   Black won't have this option now.  17...Na5??  quickly loses to  18.Nxa5  Qxa5  19.Nxd5!  Even if we miss this rather simple tactic, we can still go  19.Bf3  with a great advantage, and here, once again, having  the King on b1 proves useful as we don't need to worry about the a2-Pawn. }
17... b4 { I imagine this might still look dangerous over the board. } 18. Na4
Ne4 19. Qe1
{ Black has had 2 minutes of glory and can now start worrying about Be2-f3 or Be2-d3, although it might be a bit late for that. White has a great advantage, but we should stay alert as in dynamic positions, it is always easy to lose control.   For instance, after  19...Rb8  20.Bd3?  allows  20...e5!  and the position is becoming unclear. For this reason @@StartFEN@@1rb2rk1/2q1b2p/p1n1p1pP/3p4/Np2nP2/1N2B3/PPP1B1P1/1K1RQ2R w - - 4 20@@EndFEN@@  20.Bf3!  should be played and  20...e5  is not possible due to  21.Rxd5  . }
*

