11... Ndb8
{ This is just terrible. If you count the Knight moves, it turns out that it took Black 4 moves to bring the Knight from g8 to c6... }
12. O-O { The simplest. } 12... a6
{ A logical follow-up, but Black is just too slow and can be punished immediately. }
13. f5 { White's attack is worth much more than a piece. } 13... axb5 14. fxe6
Bxe6
{ Recapturing with the Bishop doesn't change much as we will see. White wins in the same way as after  14...fxe6  @@StartBracket@@which we'll examine next@@EndBracket@@, although we will take the Pawn with another Knight. }
15. Ncxb5 Qa5 16. Nxe6 fxe6 { 16...Qxd2  17.Nec7+!  and White is winning. } 17.
Qf2 { 18.Bb6 and 18.Qf7+ are the threats. } 17... Nd7 18. Qf7+ Kd8 19. Qxe6
{ The material doesn't matter here. Nd6 or simply Qxd5 are too big threats to handle. }
