{ No real choice for White here, as other moves allow Black to equalize rather easily. }
9... Qxb2 10. Rb1 Qa3 11. Bb5
{ The only challenging move. White developed the Bishop with tempo. Now Black does have some choice, although most of the moves are bad. }
11... Nxd4
{ This is played automatically by almost everyone. Black is solving the problem of the Knight on c6 by swapping it. }
12. Bxd4 Bb4
{ Black's last move is a big mistake, but it has become clear only in recent years. }
13. O-O
{ The simplest response is usually best, however, the more aggressive  13.f5!?  would be possible too. }
13... O-O { This gives White time to prevent ...a7-a6. } 14. Rb3 Qa5 15. Qe3
{ Now  15...a6  is not possible due to  16.Bxd7  Bxd7  17.Bb6  , trapping the Queen. }
15... Nb6
{ Historically, this was the most popular move. The engines suggest  13...f5  , admitting that after  14.Rfb1  , White is much better. }
16. Qg3
{ This strong move is already winning. White is threatening 17.f5 and there is no good defense. }
16... Bd7
{ Black is hoping for  17.f5?!  Rfc8!  , which would give chances of surviving. After @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp3ppp/1n2p3/qB1pP3/1b1B1P2/1RN3Q1/P1P3PP/5RK1 b - - 8 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Nc4  instead,  17.f5!  Rd8  18.Rf4!  the Rook would have joined the attack via the 4th rank with deadly effect. }
17. a3 { Dragging the Bishop to e7 first. } 17... Be7 18. f5 Rfc8
{ Now White will be able to push the Pawn to f6 with a much stronger effect: the dark-squared Bishop will be attacked, so there will be no time for ...g7-g6. }
19. f6 Bf8 20. fxg7 Bxg7 21. Rf4
{ Due to the Rf4-g4 threat, White is winning. In case of  21...h5  , we can simply go  22.Be2  . }
