{ The only challenging move. White developed the Bishop with tempo. Now Black does have some choice, although most of the moves are bad. }
11... Nxd4
{ This is played automatically by almost everyone. Black is solving the problem of the Knight on c6 by swapping it. }
12. Bxd4 a6
{ Clearly, the best choice for Black. White is more or less forced to take the Knight. }
13. Bxd7+ Bxd7 14. Rb3
{ Before winning the Pawn back, we should force the Queen to retreat to an awkward location. }
14... Qe7 15. Rxb7 { An important moment as Black finally gets to choose. }
15... Qh4+
{ Quite a similar line to  15...Qd8  16.O-O  Qc8  . Black is trying to survive a sad endgame. }
16. Qf2 Be7
{ This move is already known to be losing, but just a few years ago it was still used by some of the top players. }
17. g3 Qh3 { Other retreats wouldn't change anything. } 18. Kd2 Bd8
{ This move makes perfect sense once you have seen what happens after  18...Bc8  19.Rxe7+!  Still, it is just too slow. }
19. Rhb1 Bc6 20. Bc5
{ Once again, keeping Black's King in the center is more important than material. }
20... d4 { An important moment as we should not get distracted. } 21. Ne2
{ We would still prefer to take on d4 with the Queen, but the 2nd rank has to be covered first.  21.Qxd4??  Qg2+  22.Ne2  Bxb7  wouldn't end well. }
21... Qg2 { Forcing the Queen's exchange won't save Black. } 22. Qxg2 Bxg2 23.
Nxd4 { Even in the endgame, we are okay with this exchange sacrifice. } 23...
Bxb7 24. Rxb7 Ba5+ 25. Ke2 O-O-O
{ This is the only way for Black to finish development. However, it doesn't solve all the problems as the pieces still can't coordinate. }
26. Ra7
{ White is completely winning due to the multiple threats: Rxa6, Nc6, or even c4, and there is absolutely nothing that Black can do to prevent them. }
