20... Bxb7 21. Rxb7 Rc8
{ So far we have been following a game between Sergey Karjakin and Simen Agdestein from Norway Chess 2014. The Russian superstar played  22.Kc1  here, which is strong enough. However, there was something even better. }
22. Bd6 Ba5
{ Clearly, this must have been the reason why Karjakin started with @@StartFEN@@r2bk2r/1b3ppp/p3p3/2BpP3/5P2/2N3Pq/P1PK1Q1P/1R6 w kq - 0 21@@EndFEN@@  22.Kc1  , instead. }
