{ No real choice for White here, as other moves allow Black to equalize rather easily. }
9... Qxb2 10. Rb1 Qa3 11. Bb5
{ The only challenging move. White developed the Bishop with tempo. Now Black does have some choice, although most of the moves are bad. }
11... Nxd4
{ This is played automatically by almost everyone. Black is solving the problem of the Knight on c6 by swapping it. }
12. Bxd4 a6
{ Clearly, the best choice for Black. White is more or less forced to take the Knight. }
13. Bxd7+ Bxd7 14. Rb3
{ Before winning the Pawn back, we should force the Queen to retreat to an awkward location. }
14... Qe7 15. Rxb7 { An important moment as Black finally gets to choose. }
15... Qh4+
{ Quite a similar line to  15...Qd8  16.O-O  Qc8  . Black is trying to survive a sad endgame. }
16. Qf2 Qxf2+ 17. Kxf2 Be7
{ The best choice for Black, trying to finish development as soon as possible. }
18. Rhb1 Bd8 { Black is now threatening  19.--  Bc6  . } 19. Rb8
{ Anticipating the threat, but now Black will be able to castle. } 19... Rxb8
20. Rxb8 O-O 21. Rb7 Bc6
{ 21...Bc8??  would save the Pawn but lose the game. After  22.Ra7  ,  Black is almost in zugzwang while White has a simple follow-up: Nc3-a4. }
22. Ra7 Ba5
{ Black will manage to swap the passive Bishop, which should yield good drawing chances. }
23. Rxa6 Bxc3 24. Bxc3 Rc8 25. Ke3
{ Despite the presence of the opposite-colored Bishops on the board, White maintains winning chances − Pawn up, plus there are Rooks too. }
25... Bb7
{ In a game between Rasmus Svane and David Gavrilescu, European Championship Reykjavik 2021, Black played  25...Bb5  and after  26.Rb6  Ba4!  targetting the c2-Pawn, he managed to defend quite easily.  However, @@StartFEN@@2r3k1/5ppp/R3p3/1b1pP3/5P2/2B1K3/P1P3PP/8 w - - 3 26@@EndFEN@@  26.Ra5!  instead would give White an advantage as Black basically wasted time with the Bishop's move. The text move is stronger as White is forced to retreat the Rook to a passive position. }
26. Ra3
{ White should focus on restoring the coordination between the pieces. We can secure the Pawns with g2-g3, move the King to d2/d3 protecting the Bishop and the c2-Pawn, and then activate the rest of the pieces. Winning chances are slim but not null − we have a passed Pawn and Black won't be able to activate the King too quickly as the f7-Pawn needs attention as well. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25. Steinitz 7.Be3 cxd4 8.Nxd4 Qb6"]
[Black "Steinitz 8.Nxd4 Qb6 − 11.Bb5 Nxd4 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... Nf6
{ The Classical Variation is considered the second-best line against 3.Nc3, behind  3...Bb4  . With  3...Nf6  Black  provokes e4-e5, hoping to undermine White's Pawn center with ...c7-c5. }
4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4
{ Before developing the Knight, it is a good idea to improve our Pawn center. }
5... c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3
{ In most of the lines in the Steinitz Variation, the biggest part of the action is focused around the d4-square. It is our most exposed asset, so it makes sense for Black to target it. However, this isn't enough, usually. Therefore, Black often tries to attack us from the other side: ...f7-f6 or even ...g7-g5 are quite common in this line. Anything that could destroy our powerful center will bring Black's attention.  As you have probably noticed, I am focusing on Black attacking White, shouldn't it be quite the opposite? It seems that Black has given White so much in the beginning that our main task in the opening @@StartBracket@@with some natural exceptions@@EndBracket@@ will be to hold it − this is all we need. }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Qb6
{ Black is immediately creating pressure on White's position both in the center @@StartBracket@@d4@@EndBracket@@ and on the queenside @@StartBracket@@b2@@EndBracket@@. In a way, this reminds me of the Poisoned Pawn Variation in the Najdorf − in both lines, White sacrifices the Pawn on b2 in order to finish development quickly, and both variations seem to work for Black.  However, there is one big difference: the Poisoned Pawn is pretty cool for both sides, whereas here only White gets to have fun. I will be completely honest with you − no matter what we do, Black will equalize and probably even in more than one way.  Notwithstanding this, the price Black has to pay is very high. It is one of the most difficult and unpleasant lines for Black that I can think of. Long and difficult lines make it really easy to mix them up @@StartBracket@@which many players frequently do!@@EndBracket@@. Additionally, and contrary to the Poisoned Pawn, this line gives Black almost no winning chances. }
9. Qd2
{ No real choice for White here, as other moves allow Black to equalize rather easily. }
9... Qxb2 10. Rb1 Qa3 11. Bb5
{ The only challenging move. White developed the Bishop with tempo. Now Black does have some choice, although most of the moves are bad. }
11... Nxd4
{ This is played automatically by almost everyone. Black is solving the problem of the Knight on c6 by swapping it. }
12. Bxd4 a6
{ Clearly, the best choice for Black. White is more or less forced to take the Knight. }
13. Bxd7+ Bxd7 14. Rb3
{ Before winning the Pawn back, we should force the Queen to retreat to an awkward location. }
14... Qe7 15. Rxb7 { An important moment as Black finally gets to choose. }
15... Qd8
{ Whatever Black chooses, the Queen can't stay on e7.  15...Rc8  16.O-O  Qd8  transposes. }
16. O-O Rb8
{ This is too loose, Black is wasting important time while the white Rook can easily be replaced by another one. }
17. Rxb8 Qxb8 18. Rb1 Qc7 19. Qe3
{ One of the most typical moves in the line, the Queen takes control over the c5-square but also prepares f4-f5. }
19... Be7 20. f5
{ Once again, Black is in trouble as there is no good way of dealing with the f5-f6 threat. }
*

