13. Bxd7+ Bxd7 14. Rb3
{ Before winning the Pawn back, we should force the Queen to retreat to an awkward location. }
14... Qe7 15. Rxb7 { An important moment as Black finally gets to choose. }
15... Qd8
{ Whatever Black chooses, the Queen can't stay on e7.  15...Rc8  16.O-O  Qd8  transposes. }
16. O-O Rc8
{ Objectively, the strongest continuation. Black's last move has yielded some flexibility − the dark-squared Bishop can be developed to e7 or c5, but also the Queen's Rook can go to c4 or even @@StartBracket@@in some cases@@EndBracket@@ get sacrificed by taking the Knight on c3.  However, it comes with a price as White has some options too, and after most of them, Black has some unique reactions; not the most comfortable situation, as that means there is a lot to memorize. }
17. Qe3
{ White prevents 17...Bc5, threatens 18.Bb6, and prepares 18.f5 while also avoiding ...Rc8xc3, which would be the case after  17.Qf2  Rxc3!  18.Bxc3  Qc8  19.Rb3  Ba4  and Black wins the exchange back, basically equalizing. }
17... Rc4
{ The only move. Black is now ready to meet both  18.Bb6  and  18.f5  with  18...Qc8  . }
18. Rfb1
{ The point of our last move is to prevent ...Qd8-c8. We now have Rb7-b8. }
18... Be7 19. f5
{ Usually, achieving this advance gives White a big advantage. Here, however, things are not that simple. Black's Rook on c4 is really annoying, and we would really like our Rook on f1 right now... }
19... Bg5 20. Qd3
{ 20.Qf2  would now be answered with  20...exf5  and  21.Bb6  gives nothing as the Queen can easily retreat. }
20... O-O
{ 21.f6  is generally considered to be the main line here, but I believe this is a perfect moment to deviate. }
21. Ne4
{ This move has only been seen in correspondence chess so far, and as long as it's not part of common knowledge, I believe it's a good try. White has created multiple threats with the last move: Nxg5 followed by Rxd7, f6, or even Nd6.   The Knight cannot be taken due to the weakness of the Rook on c4 while  21...Rxd4  doesn't work because of  22.Qxd4  dxe4  23.Rxd7  . }
21... Bc8
{ This quiet retreat turns out to be the only good move for Black. The point is that now the Rook and Knight are hanging, and also, compared to  21...Bc6  , there is no  22.Rb8  attacking the Queen. }
22. Bb6
{ But what about this? Now the black Queen has only one square to retreat to. }
22... Qe8 { But retreating there is a bad idea. } 23. Nxg5 Bxb7 24. fxe6
{ Due to the mating threat on h7, Black cannot recapture. } 24... g6 25. exf7+
Rxf7 26. Nxf7 Qxf7 27. Be3
{ Black has no way of defending against White's simple threats: Be3-h6, Rb1-f1, and then the Queen can be easily included in the attack, and there is always e5-e6 too. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25. Steinitz 7.Be3 cxd4 8.Nxd4 Qb6"]
[Black "Steinitz 8.Nxd4 Qb6 − 11.Bb5 Nxd4 #22"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... Nf6
{ The Classical Variation is considered the second-best line against 3.Nc3, behind  3...Bb4  . With  3...Nf6  Black  provokes e4-e5, hoping to undermine White's Pawn center with ...c7-c5. }
4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4
{ Before developing the Knight, it is a good idea to improve our Pawn center. }
5... c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3
{ In most of the lines in the Steinitz Variation, the biggest part of the action is focused around the d4-square. It is our most exposed asset, so it makes sense for Black to target it. However, this isn't enough, usually. Therefore, Black often tries to attack us from the other side: ...f7-f6 or even ...g7-g5 are quite common in this line. Anything that could destroy our powerful center will bring Black's attention.  As you have probably noticed, I am focusing on Black attacking White, shouldn't it be quite the opposite? It seems that Black has given White so much in the beginning that our main task in the opening @@StartBracket@@with some natural exceptions@@EndBracket@@ will be to hold it − this is all we need. }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Qb6
{ Black is immediately creating pressure on White's position both in the center @@StartBracket@@d4@@EndBracket@@ and on the queenside @@StartBracket@@b2@@EndBracket@@. In a way, this reminds me of the Poisoned Pawn Variation in the Najdorf − in both lines, White sacrifices the Pawn on b2 in order to finish development quickly, and both variations seem to work for Black.  However, there is one big difference: the Poisoned Pawn is pretty cool for both sides, whereas here only White gets to have fun. I will be completely honest with you − no matter what we do, Black will equalize and probably even in more than one way.  Notwithstanding this, the price Black has to pay is very high. It is one of the most difficult and unpleasant lines for Black that I can think of. Long and difficult lines make it really easy to mix them up @@StartBracket@@which many players frequently do!@@EndBracket@@. Additionally, and contrary to the Poisoned Pawn, this line gives Black almost no winning chances. }
9. Qd2
{ No real choice for White here, as other moves allow Black to equalize rather easily. }
9... Qxb2 10. Rb1 Qa3 11. Bb5
{ The only challenging move. White developed the Bishop with tempo. Now Black does have some choice, although most of the moves are bad. }
11... Nxd4
{ This is played automatically by almost everyone. Black is solving the problem of the Knight on c6 by swapping it. }
12. Bxd4 a6
{ Clearly, the best choice for Black. White is more or less forced to take the Knight. }
13. Bxd7+ Bxd7 14. Rb3
{ Before winning the Pawn back, we should force the Queen to retreat to an awkward location. }
14... Qe7 15. Rxb7 { An important moment as Black finally gets to choose. }
15... Qd8
{ Whatever Black chooses, the Queen can't stay on e7.  15...Rc8  16.O-O  Qd8  transposes. }
16. O-O Rc8
{ Objectively, the strongest continuation. Black's last move has yielded some flexibility − the dark-squared Bishop can be developed to e7 or c5, but also the Queen's Rook can go to c4 or even @@StartBracket@@in some cases@@EndBracket@@ get sacrificed by taking the Knight on c3.  However, it comes with a price as White has some options too, and after most of them, Black has some unique reactions; not the most comfortable situation, as that means there is a lot to memorize. }
17. Qe3
{ White prevents 17...Bc5, threatens 18.Bb6, and prepares 18.f5 while also avoiding ...Rc8xc3, which would be the case after  17.Qf2  Rxc3!  18.Bxc3  Qc8  19.Rb3  Ba4  and Black wins the exchange back, basically equalizing. }
17... Rc4
{ The only move. Black is now ready to meet both  18.Bb6  and  18.f5  with  18...Qc8  . }
18. Rfb1
{ The point of our last move is to prevent ...Qd8-c8. We now have Rb7-b8. }
18... Be7 19. f5
{ Usually, achieving this advance gives White a big advantage. Here, however, things are not that simple. Black's Rook on c4 is really annoying, and we would really like our Rook on f1 right now... }
19... Bg5 20. Qd3
{ 20.Qf2  would now be answered with  20...exf5  and  21.Bb6  gives nothing as the Queen can easily retreat. }
20... O-O
{ 21.f6  is generally considered to be the main line here, but I believe this is a perfect moment to deviate. }
21. Ne4
{ This move has only been seen in correspondence chess so far, and as long as it's not part of common knowledge, I believe it's a good try. White has created multiple threats with the last move: Nxg5 followed by Rxd7, f6, or even Nd6.   The Knight cannot be taken due to the weakness of the Rook on c4 while  21...Rxd4  doesn't work because of  22.Qxd4  dxe4  23.Rxd7  . }
21... Bc8
{ This quiet retreat turns out to be the only good move for Black. The point is that now the Rook and Knight are hanging, and also, compared to  21...Bc6  , there is no  22.Rb8  attacking the Queen. }
22. Bb6
{ But what about this? Now the black Queen has only one square to retreat to. }
22... Be3+
{ A great solution to a great problem! Needless to say, it would not be an easy task for Black to figure it out over the board. }
23. Qxe3 Qh4
{ Temporarily, White is a piece up, but luckily for Black, we can't keep it. }
24. Nf6+ { 24.Rc7  Rxe4  is fine for Black. } 24... gxf6 25. Rc7 exf5
{ Black still had to be careful here. After  25...fxe5??  26.Bc5!  , unsolvable problems would suddenly appear  due to the Rb1-b8 threat. }
26. Rxc4 dxc4 27. exf6 Be6
{ The Pawn on f6 looks nice, but it brings no real danger to Black's position. For instance, after  28.Bd4  h6  ,  Black can bring the King to h7 and even create some counterplay on the g-file. Therefore, it is a perfect moment to abort. }
28. Qd4
{ Black is not forced to swap the Queens, but at the same time, it is hard to imagine that something like  28...Qg5  29.Re1  helps. The position is objectively equal. }
