11. O-O-O Rb8
{ This was Matthias Bluebaum's choice, and the German grandmaster is currently one of the leading experts in the French Defense, so we should take it seriously. Black is preparing the advance of the b-Pawn. }
12. h4 Bxd4
{ 12...Nxd4?!  13.Bxd4  b5  would be met with  14.Bxc5  Nxc5  15.b4!  Not only stopping the attack but also fixing Black's Pawns on the light squares. This is a very typical idea in the French Defense. }
13. Bxd4 b5 { 14.b4  won't work now as Black can immediately go  14...a5! } 14.
Rh3
{ The Rook is great on the 3rd rank as it can defend and attack at the same time. }
14... Nxd4 { Bluebaum's choice, but I just don't like it. } 15. Qxd4 Qe7 16. b4
{ We are stopping Black's b-Pawn advance by advancing our own Pawn. Notice that this method works best when the black Knight is away from the c6-square, as it makes it virtually impossible to get ...a6-a5 work. White controls the situation on the board, the Bishop can be developed to d3, and then we can start thinking of the Kingside attack. }
