{ White is leaving the e4-square for the Knight, but also e1 is a perfect square for the Queen − it can now join the attack from both flanks. }
20... b5 21. Ne4 b4 { Black is looking for counterplay. } 22. Bc4 bxa3 23. b3
{ A typical motif. Maybe saying that the a3-Pawn is one of our defenders would be too much, but certainly, it is not dangerous. White has an easy plan: g4-g5 and Ne4-f6+. How Black can defend is not clear.   23...Bb4  will be easily refuted with  24.c3  Ba5  25.Ka2  . The engines recommend  25...Qc7  but, apart from being a very difficult move,  26.Nf6+  Kh8  27.Rf1  still looks nice for White! }
