[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26. Steinitz 7.Be3 a6"]
[Black "Steinitz 7.Be3 a6 8.a3 cxd4 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... Nf6
{ The Classical Variation is considered the second-best line against 3.Nc3, behind  3...Bb4  . With  3...Nf6  Black  provokes e4-e5, hoping to undermine White's Pawn center with ...c7-c5. }
4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4
{ Before developing the Knight, it is a good idea to improve our Pawn center. }
5... c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3
{ In most of the lines in the Steinitz Variation, the biggest part of the action is focused around the d4-square. It is our most exposed asset, so it makes sense for Black to target it. However, this isn't enough, usually. Therefore, Black often tries to attack us from the other side: ...f7-f6 or even ...g7-g5 are quite common in this line. Anything that could destroy our powerful center will bring Black's attention.  As you have probably noticed, I am focusing on Black attacking White, shouldn't it be quite the opposite? It seems that Black has given White so much in the beginning that our main task in the opening @@StartBracket@@with some natural exceptions@@EndBracket@@ will be to hold it − this is all we need. }
7... a6
{ The most popular line of the Classical System. Black is delaying the development of the dark-squared Bishop while, at the same time, preparing ...b7-b5. }
8. a3
{ I usually recommend the main lines, but here I really like  8.a3  . It is challenging while also easier to absorb than the main line @@StartBracket@@that would be  8.Qd2  @@EndBracket@@  . A nice thing about White's  8.a3  is that it works really well against  8...b5  @@StartBracket@@which was Black's main plan@@EndBracket@@ while being a useful move in general, so there is no simple antidote.   So, what is the point of White's last move? We would love to develop our light-squared Bishop to d3, which would, however, weaken our control over the key d4-square. For that reason,  8.Bd3?!  is not a good option, as  8...Qb6  would create an immediate challenge to White's position. With 8.a3 we are delaying the development of  that Bishop while anticipating ...b7-b5-b4 at the same time. It is exactly the same strategy as Black used a move earlier! }
8... cxd4
{ This is a bit better now than it was on move 7, but it's still pleasant for White. }
9. Nxd4 Bc5 10. Qd2 g5
{ A very interesting attempt to solve Black's problems. The idea of fighting back in the center by undermining the f4-Pawn rather than the e5-Pawn directly @@StartBracket@@...f7-f6@@EndBracket@@ is quite common. Still, in this exact position, it's a relatively new and surprising idea. }
11. Nf3
{ White is strengthening control in the center. There are other tries as well,  11.Nxc6  or  11.f5  , but this modest retreat would be my choice. }
11... d4
{ A strong move, but it's not like Black had a choice.  11...Bxe3  12.Qxe3  gxf4  13.Qxf4  would be clearly better for White. The next couple of moves are forced. }
12. Bxd4
{ 12.Nxd4?  is the wrong recapture, handing Black the advantage after  12...gxf4! }
12... Nxd4 13. Nxd4 gxf4 14. Qxf4 Nxe5 15. O-O-O
{ The King is safe, and the Knight is defended.  15.Ndb5  was another option. }
15... Ng6 16. Qe4 Qh4 { Black wants to trade the Queens, but not at any cost. }
17. g4
{ Given Black's development problems, we can still create some challenges in the middlegame too.  17.Qxh4  was still possible, but with the King on c1, it wouldn't be as convincing as in the 16...Qg5+ line. }
17... O-O 18. Kb1
{ This move is useful in general, but here it has a specific point: ...Bc5xa3 is a potential idea for Black. For instance,  18.Nf3  Qe7  and we have to  consider ...Bc5xa3 all the time. It's best to walk away from possible checks. }
18... Rb8 { Looking for quick counterplay. } 19. Nf3 Qe7 20. Qe1
{ White is leaving the e4-square for the Knight, but also e1 is a perfect square for the Queen − it can now join the attack from both flanks. }
20... b5 21. Ne4 Bb7
{ This is a good line for Black, but also a demanding one. } 22. Rd7
{ Black will have to give away the Queen for a start. } 22... Bxe4
{ 22...Qxd7??  23.Nf6+  and White wins. } 23. Rxe7
{ The next moves are forced. } 23... Bxf3 24. Qc3 Bxh1 25. Qxc5 Nxe7 26. Qxe7
Be4
{ The only move. From here the Bishop is defending the King, but it is also targeting the c2-Pawn. }
27. Kc1 { Now we will be able to solve the c-Pawn problem with c2-c3. } 27...
Rfd8 28. Be2 Rbc8 29. c3
{ Black should hold, but from a practical point of view, White's chances are preferable. We have a simple plan to put the Queen on f6 and advance the h-Pawn. }
