[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Winawer 3.Nc3 Bb4 4.e5 b6/Ne7"]
[Black "Winawer 3.Nc3 Bb4 4.e5 b6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... Bb4
{ The Winawer Variation is quite unique, even for the French. In most of the lines, the Bishop captures the Knight, and the arising Pawn structure is so specific that most of the players struggle to cope with it, especially since Black's dark squares are so weak that we tend to overestimate White's position. }
4. e5 b6
{ Black wants to trade the light-squared Bishop with ...Bc8-a6. The plan is strategically sound, but it takes time, and just a quick glance at the Kingside makes it clear: it is not a good moment for time-consuming operations.   4...Qd7  5.h4  b6  transposes. }
5. h4
{ It's not like White wouldn't be better after other moves, but I especially like this one for a couple of reasons:   The h-Pawn advance is very useful as we are intending to break Black's Pawn structure on the Kingside.  On many occasions, the Rook will be developed via h3.  By keeping the Knight on g1 White maintains the possibility of Qd1-g4.     It is also possible to go  5.Qg4  to which Black should reply with  5...Bf8!  and  then ...h7-h5 can be played with tempo. }
5... Ba6 { Black goes on with the initial plan, but it won't bring any good. }
6. Bxa6 Nxa6
{ Black could throw in  6...Bxc3+  , but after  7.bxc3  Nxa6  8.Qg4  , White would be much better. }
7. Qd3 { One more reason to keep the Queen on d1. } 7... Qc8 8. a3
{ Now Black won't even get to break our Pawn structure. } 8... Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3
Ne7 10. Bg5
{ Black's King's Knight has nowhere to go, while after the relatively best  10...c5  , White can go  11.Bxe7  Kxe7  12.Ne2  with great advantage. }
