{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... Bb4
{ The Winawer Variation is quite unique, even for the French. In most of the lines, the Bishop captures the Knight, and the arising Pawn structure is so specific that most of the players struggle to cope with it, especially since Black's dark squares are so weak that we tend to overestimate White's position. }
4. e5 c5 5. a3 Ba5
{ Instead of taking the Knight, Black simply retreated the Bishop. The point is to avoid improving White's Pawn center while the dark-squared Bishop can be quite useful for Black. The main continuation in the position is  6.b4  cxd4  7.Nb5  and for a long time it had been considered better for White. However, recently, new ideas for Black have emerged which, in my opinion, are strong enough to shift our attention towards another possibility. }
6. Qg4 { After all, it is the Winawer! } 6... Ne7
{ The best reaction. The argument is that after  7.Qxg7  Rg8  8.Qxh7  cxd4  9.b4  Bc7!  10.Nb5  a6!  Black is doing fine and I agree. }
7. dxc5
{ It is a good moment to come back a bit. Why didn't we take on c5 right away? After @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/pp3ppp/4p3/b1ppP3/3P4/P1N5/1PP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.dxc5  Bxc3+  7.bxc3  Qc7!  , Black is forcing us to move the Knight  to f3, and the Queen won't get activated at all. }
7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 O-O
{ It certainly makes more sense than moving the King to f8. } 9. Nf3 Nd7 10.
Bd3 Nf5 11. a4
{ It is very important to start with this. If you go  11.O-O  first @@StartBracket@@like most did@@EndBracket@@, then after  11...Nxc5  12.a4  Bd7  13.Ba3  , Black is just in time with  13...Rc8  . A nuance perhaps, but such details affect the evaluation. }
11... Nxc5 12. Ba3 b6 13. Qh5
{ We are not creating any real threats, but it's a good square for the Queen and g2-g4 ideas will have to be considered by Black. One more good point is that by playing 12...b6, Black indicated the intention of taking the Bishop on d3 and then bringing the Bishop to a6   This would, of course, mean that Black would have to move the Rook to e8 first. This is when our Queen on h5 comes in: Black can't just move the Rook and allow Nf3-g5, right? }
13... g6
{ Black is right to push our Queen back, but by doing so, the dark squares get weakened. }
14. Qh3 Qc7
{ Black is hoping for  15.O-O  h5!  and, although I am still not a fan, I can understand the logic. It is not easy for White to find the right plan. The immediate @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p4p1p/1p2p1p1/2npPn2/P7/B1PB1N1Q/2P2PPP/R3K2R b KQ - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14...h5  would be met by  15.g4!  with a strong attack. }
15. Bxf5 exf5 16. Qh6 Ne6 { This loses by force. } 17. O-O-O Ba6
{ 17...Qxc3  18.Rd3  Qc4  19.Nd2!  and White wins. } 18. h4
{ Nothing can stop White now. } 18... Be2 19. Ng5 Nxg5 20. hxg5 Bh5 21. Rd3
Rfe8 { 21...Qxe5  22.Re3!  followed by Be7. } 22. Bd6
{ After  22...Qd7  , we will just  bring the Rook to h4 and then take down the Bishop with f2-f3 and g2-g4. Black is helpless. }
