[White "29. Winawer 5.a3 Bxc3+ 6.bxc3 c4/Nc6"]
[Black "Winawer 5.a3 Bxc3+ 6.bxc3 c4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... Bb4
{ The Winawer Variation is quite unique, even for the French. In most of the lines, the Bishop captures the Knight, and the arising Pawn structure is so specific that most of the players struggle to cope with it, especially since Black's dark squares are so weak that we tend to overestimate White's position. }
4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c4
{ A big mistake. Black is releasing the pressure from the center while receiving nothing in return. }
7. Qg4 g6 { This is just horrible, but would  7...Kf8  8.a4  be any better? }
8. h4 Qa5 { At least Black can catch a breath for a moment. } 9. Ne2
{ 9.Kd2!?  would be equally strong. } 9... h6
{ Black is now ready to meet  10.h5  with  10...g5  . A typical mistake from White would be to continue with  11.f4?  f5!  and after  12.exf6  Nxf6  followed by ...g5-g4, Black is already OK! }
10. a4 { Making space for the Bishop. } 10... Nc6 11. Qf3 Bd7 12. Ba3
{ I dare to say that White has a winning advantage here. The King will be safe on d2. On the Kingside, we can advance the Pawn to g4 and then develop the light-squared Bishop to h3. After that, we will probably move our attention to the Queenside, although generally speaking, we can and should be playing on both sides. }
*

[Event "?"]
