{ Black is getting ready for h4-h5. If we just develop our pieces here, for instance,  9.Nf3  , then Black can go  9...Qa5  10.Bd2  Qa4  and the position is becoming unclear. We could anticipate it with @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp3p2/2n1p1pp/2ppP3/3P2QP/P1P5/2P2PP1/R1B1KBNR w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.a4  , but after  9...Qa5  10.Bd2  Bd7  followed by ...Rh8-h7 and long castle, White's advantage isn't that great and it could be quite difficult to handle it. }
9. h5 { I say we attack right away! } 9... g5 10. f4 f5
{ It is based on the small trap:  10.exf6?  e5!  and White's in trouble! } 11.
Qg3 g4 12. dxc5
{ We can't allow Black to close the position on the Queenside as well. } 12...
Qa5 13. Rb1 { Preparing Rb1-b5. } 13... Qxc5
{ Black wins the Pawn back, but this opens two diagonals for our Bishop. } 14.
a4 a6 15. Bd3 { A tempo is more important than the Pawn, at least that Pawn. }
15... Qxc3+
{ Otherwise, we could just bring the Knight to e2 on the next move. } 16. Bd2
Qc5 17. Ne2 Nge7 18. Qf2
{ We don't mind the endgame as White has more than enough compensation for the Pawn. We control all the dark squares and all Black's Pawns are weak. I mean, not right now, but if e6 is weak, then d5, f5, and g4 are potentially weak too. We have the b-file and we have space as well. }
