[White "29. Winawer 5.a3 Bxc3+ 6.bxc3 c4/Nc6"]
[Black "Winawer 5.a3 Bxc3+ 6.bxc3 Nc6 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... Bb4
{ The Winawer Variation is quite unique, even for the French. In most of the lines, the Bishop captures the Knight, and the arising Pawn structure is so specific that most of the players struggle to cope with it, especially since Black's dark squares are so weak that we tend to overestimate White's position. }
4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nc6
{ Quite an interesting line that has been recently brought back to life by some new generation players, most notably Richard Rapport. }
7. Qg4 g6
{ This is the point of the line. Black is giving up on the dark squares, but it won't be easy to take advantage of that as Black will get some counterplay on the Queenside. }
8. h4 h6
{ Black is getting ready for h4-h5. If we just develop our pieces here, for instance,  9.Nf3  , then Black can go  9...Qa5  10.Bd2  Qa4  and the position is becoming unclear. We could anticipate it with @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp3p2/2n1p1pp/2ppP3/3P2QP/P1P5/2P2PP1/R1B1KBNR w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.a4  , but after  9...Qa5  10.Bd2  Bd7  followed by ...Rh8-h7 and long castle, White's advantage isn't that great and it could be quite difficult to handle it. }
9. h5 { I say we attack right away! } 9... g5 10. f4 Qa5
{ This time we have to defend the c3-Pawn. } 11. Bd2 f5
{ It makes sense! In a previous line, Black pushed the white Queen to g3 first, so the c3-Pawn was already protected. }
12. Qg3 g4 13. c4
{ I would normally think that White's advantage should be overwhelming here. Black's King is weak and we are opening up the position with a tempo by having the Bishop pair. However, mostly the light squares will become available, and that will reduce the effect. }
13... Qa4 { The best place for the Queen. } 14. dxc5 Nge7
{ Black has to focus on development. I won't take  14...dxc4  seriously, just  15.Ne2  followed by Ne2-c3. }
15. Qb3
{ With this move, White can fix the Pawn structure and keep the Pawn for good. }
15... Qxb3 16. cxb3 b6 { The only reasonable move here. } 17. cxd5
{ I don't want to burden you with details you don't need but, despite the engine's initial evaluation, I don't think that  17.cxb6  Nd4!  would be better than our choice. }
17... Nd4
{ 17...Nxd5?  would allow us to finish development.  18.Rc1  Nd4  19.Bc4!  bxc5  20.Ne2  with a great advantage.  Now Black is threatening both 18...Nc2+ and 18...Nxb3, forcing our Rook to take an inferior position. }
18. Rb1 Nxd5 19. Ne2 bxc5 20. Kf2 { Played with a small trap. } 20... Bb7
{ This allows an unexpected trick. } 21. b4 Nxe2 22. bxc5
{ White wins the piece back while keeping the Pawn.  22...Nexf4??  would be unfortunate, as after  23.Rxb7  , the Knight is trapped  on f4 and it won't take much effort to win it. }
