4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qa5
{ Black is attacking the c3-Pawn, but the main plan is to place the Queen on a4. It is one of the most typical ideas in the Winawer, and it makes a huge difference whether White can place the Pawn on a4 or not, as we usually want to place the dark-squared Bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal. }
7. Bd2 Qa4 { The Queen has arived to a4. } 8. Qg4
{ Black is missing some support on the Kingside, so we are taking advantage of that. }
8... Kf8 9. h4
{ The good thing is that we are consistent: Qd1-g4 is almost always followed by the h-Pawn advance. }
9... Qxc2
{ Played with peaceful intentions: Black is hoping to simplify the position. }
10. h5
{ The plan is simple: h5-h6. Another bonus is the h4-square for the Rook. }
10... b6
{ We can't go h5-h6, so it makes sense to ignore it. The other thing is that it doesn't really change anything. }
11. Rc1 Qe4+ 12. Qxe4 dxe4 13. Rh4 { White will easily win the Pawn back. }
13... Bb7 14. Ne2 Ne7 15. Ng3
{ That Pawn should be given away, but let's see what happens if Black tries to save it. }
15... Nf5
{ Black should have gone  15...h6  16.Nxe4  with a big advantage for White. }
16. Nxf5 exf5 17. g4
{ This is even stronger than  17.h6  played in an online game Wagner-Zierk, Titled Tuesday 2021. }
17... fxg4 18. Rxg4
{ The e4-Pawn is not relevant, we can win it back at any time. For now, Black has much bigger worries: we can push the h-Pawn, but the bigger threat is Bf1-c4 followed by Rg4-f4. How is Black going to defend the f7-Pawn? White is winning. }
