[White "30. Winawer 5.a3 Bxc3+ 6.bxc3 Qa5"]
[Black "Winawer 6.bxc3 Qa5 7.Bd2 Qa4 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... Bb4
{ The Winawer Variation is quite unique, even for the French. In most of the lines, the Bishop captures the Knight, and the arising Pawn structure is so specific that most of the players struggle to cope with it, especially since Black's dark squares are so weak that we tend to overestimate White's position. }
4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qa5
{ Black is attacking the c3-Pawn, but the main plan is to place the Queen on a4. It is one of the most typical ideas in the Winawer, and it makes a huge difference whether White can place the Pawn on a4 or not, as we usually want to place the dark-squared Bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal. }
7. Bd2 Qa4 { The Queen has arived to a4. } 8. Qg4
{ Black is missing some support on the Kingside, so we are taking advantage of that. }
8... Kf8 9. h4
{ The good thing is that we are consistent: Qd1-g4 is almost always followed by the h-Pawn advance. }
9... Ne7
{ In case you wondered, there are some important nuances that distinguish  9...Ne7  from  9...Nc6  . Therefore, we have to adjust our reaction. }
10. h5 h6 11. Rh3
{ This was not possible with the Knight on c6 as Black had ...Nc6xe5. Once we understand all the nuances, there is no risk of mixing up the lines.   Let's quickly see why the solution we used against 9...Nc6 does not work here. The next few moves were already explained so need for comments here.  11.Qd1  b6  12.Nf3  Ba6  13.Bxa6  Qxa6  14.dxc5  bxc5  15.Qe2  Qxe2+!  This was bad with the Knights on c6 and g8.  16.Kxe2  Nd7!  17.Rab1  Nc6  . Black is not afraid of  18.Rb7  as there is a simple defense:  18...Ke7  . This makes a big difference and results in a different evaluation. Black is not worse here. }
11... Nbc6 12. Qf4 { Preventing ...Nc6xe5 but also targetting f7. } 12... b6
13. Rf3 Nd8
{ Black's last move looks desperate, but on the other hand, there is no obvious way of continuing the attack. Therefore, it is the right moment to open up the position. }
14. dxc5 Qxf4 15. Bxf4
{ It will soon become clear why we prefer our Rook on the 3rd rank.  15.Rxf4  is much more popular but I am not sure if it is stronger.  15...bxc5  16.Be3  c4  17.Nf3  Ndc6  .  Black is threatening ...g7-g5 and it can't really be prevented. White still fights for the advantage but the outcome is far from clear. }
15... bxc5 16. Be3 c4
{ It would be hard to take  16...Ndc6  seriously. After  17.Bxc5  Nxe5  18.Re3  is strong, but  18.Rb1!  is even stronger. }
17. Rh3
{ This is the point of keeping the Rook on the 3rd rank. Now ...g7-g5 is stopped. }
17... f6 18. f4 fxe5 19. fxe5
{ Black can attack the e5-Pawn by placing the Knights on c6 and f7, but we can easily defend it with Ng1-f3 and Be3-f4. We will probably focus on the Kingside and the Rooks can be even doubled on the g-file. }
