[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... Bb4
{ The Winawer Variation is quite unique, even for the French. In most of the lines, the Bishop captures the Knight, and the arising Pawn structure is so specific that most of the players struggle to cope with it, especially since Black's dark squares are so weak that we tend to overestimate White's position. }
4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qc7
{ The Queen does not directly attack the c3-Pawn but now ...c5xd4 will have to be taken more seriously. Additionally, the black Queen can defend on the 7th rank, although this idea works rarely. }
7. Qg4 f5
{ This move is a positional mistake. Black now has more weak dark squares, the Pawn on e6 is weak too, plus there will never be a chance to challenge White's pawn center. }
8. Qg3 { Keeping an eye on c3 but on g7 too. } 8... cxd4
{ By starting with this, Black will be able to develop the Knight to e7 without sacrificing the g7-Pawn. However, fixing our Pawn structure has a very high price. }
9. cxd4 Ne7
{ 9...Qxc2  would cost Black too many tempi. Simply  10.Bd2  Qc7  11.Rc1  Nc6  12.Bb5  with an enormous advantage. }
10. c3 O-O 11. Ne2 { The Knight is heading to f4. } 11... b6 12. Nf4
{ Black is already paying the price for the 7th move. Before touching the Bishop, Black has to defend the e6-Pawn first. }
12... Qd7 13. a4
{ Useful nuance, although  13.h4  would also be much better for White. } 13...
Ba6 14. Bb5 { The point. } 14... Bxb5 15. axb5
{ Black is positionally lost − development can't be finished without material losses. Our plan is simple: advance the h-pawn. }
