[White "31. Winawer 6.bxc3 Qc7 7.Qg4 f5/f6"]
[Black "Winawer 6.bxc3 Qc7 7.Qg4 f6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... Bb4
{ The Winawer Variation is quite unique, even for the French. In most of the lines, the Bishop captures the Knight, and the arising Pawn structure is so specific that most of the players struggle to cope with it, especially since Black's dark squares are so weak that we tend to overestimate White's position. }
4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qc7 7. Qg4 f6
{ This is not a good line, but it does create challenges for White, so it is important to know it. Black is trying to undermine our position in the center. }
8. Bb5+
{ We are taking advantage of the g7-Pawn as Black can't go  8...Bd7  . } 8...
Kf8
{ This is clearly better than  8...Nc6  and more accurate than  8...Kf7  . Still, it is not good enough. }
9. Qg3
{ Almost a novelty! The Queen is nicely placed on g3, supporting the white Pawns.  9.Nf3  is the main move and it's also challenging but I just think our choice is better. }
9... c4 { Our Bishop is in danger so this line is very important. } 10. a4
{ The tactics work in White's favor. } 10... a6 11. Ba3+ Kf7
{ But not  11...Ne7??  12.exf6!+-  . } 12. Bd6 Qd8 13. exf6
{ We will lose the Bishop but win the Knight. } 13... gxf6 14. Bc7
{ An important intermezzo. The black Queen is dragged to e7, which will allow our Bishop to return with tempo.  14.Bxb8  axb5  15.Bc7  Qf8  16.Bd6  Ne7  is also better for White, but not to the same extent. }
14... Qe7 { 14...Qf8  would allow  15.Bxc4!  dxc4  16.Bxb8  . } 15. Bxb8
{ 15.Bxc4?!  wouldn't work now.  15...dxc4  16.Bxb8  e5!  with an unclear position. }
15... axb5 16. Bd6
{ Other moves are possible here, but the priority for me is to secure the advantage without being drawn into some unnecessary complications. }
16... Qd8 17. Bc7
{ Black's Queen can retreat to d7, e7, or f8 and our reaction will be the same: a4-a5 followed by Ng1-f3. Our King can be hidden on the Kingside but also in the center. I would love to see White challenging it even further with g2-g4-g5 being played at some point. }
