[Round "?"]
[White "32. Winawer 6.bxc3 Ne7 7.Qg4 − 7th Moves"]
[Black "Winawer 6.bxc3 Ne7 7.Qg4 cxd4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... Bb4
{ The Winawer Variation is quite unique, even for the French. In most of the lines, the Bishop captures the Knight, and the arising Pawn structure is so specific that most of the players struggle to cope with it, especially since Black's dark squares are so weak that we tend to overestimate White's position. }
4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 { 6...Qc7  7.Qg4  Ne7  would transpose. } 7.
Qg4 cxd4
{ A clever move order, specifically directed against our chosen setup. } 8. Bd3
{ 8.Qxg7  Rg8  9.Qxh7  Qc7!  and White has no time to develop the  Bishop to d3. }
8... Qa5
{ White is more or less forced to sacrifice the Pawn. However, we already know that Pawn sacrifices are pretty common in the Winawer. }
9. Rb1 { 9.Ne2  would be okay but we prefer  the Knight on f3. } 9... Nd7
{ This is a good example of a strange move turning out to be a dubious one. Notice that  9...Nbc6  wouldn't change anything, as we can react in the same way. }
10. Nf3 Ng6
{ I am not sure why anyone would think that moving the Queen to the edge of the board, then spending three moves to attack the Pawn @@StartBracket@@not really@@EndBracket@@ is supposed to be good but it was played by some strong players, foremost Ian Nepomniachtchi against Anish Giri on the Internet, so we should not ignore the idea completely. }
11. O-O dxc3 12. h4
{ Or perhaps we should... It is clear that Black is in great trouble. } 12...
Qc7
{ Based on the false assumption that after  13.h5  Black can take  13...Ngxe5  14.Nxe5  Qxe5  . }
13. h5
{ In the game Sasikirian-Studer, Gibraltar 2020, the weaker  13.Re1  was played. }
13... Ngxe5 14. Nxe5 Qxe5 15. Bf4 Qf6 16. Bg5 Qe5 17. Rfe1
{ White's initiative justifies the material imbalance. } *

