4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 { 6...Qc7  7.Qg4  Ne7  would transpose. } 7.
Qg4 O-O
{ Historically, this is a great continuation. It was used thousands of times and plenty of top players played some interesting games in this variation. However, the computer revolution wasn't merciful to it. }
8. Bd3 f5
{ The main continuation. Naturally, having the Bishop pair, White has no reasons not to open up the position. }
9. exf6 Rxf6 10. Bg5
{ These moves with tempo are essential for the positive outcome of the opening for White. }
10... Rf7 11. Qh5 g6
{ For the time being, Black's King is safe. However, the dark squares have weakened permanently. }
12. Qd1
{ This Queen comes back to safe haven. It would have been more exposed on h4, possibly running under ...Ne7-f5. Also, we should remember about our Queenside. }
12... Qa5 13. Bd2
{ 13.Nf3  is also possible. However,  13...c4  14.Be2  Qxc3+  would require a lot of accuracy from White. }
13... e5
{ Black sacrifices the Pawn in order to activate the light-squared Bishop. This line is objectively incorrect, but it has some practical value, so we should not underestimate it. }
14. dxe5 Nbc6 15. f4
{ Now our King is a bit exposed, but Black has no way of exploiting it. } 15...
c4 16. Be2 Qc5 17. Nf3 Bf5 18. Qc1
{ Black doesn't really have a choice now, Bd2-e3 can't be allowed. } 18... d4
19. cxd4
{ Technically speaking,  19.a4!  preparing Qc1-a3 would be a bit more accurate. However, my choice is good enough, and it is also much simpler. }
19... Nxd4 20. Nxd4 Qxd4 21. Be3 Qc3+ 22. Kf2 Be4
{ Or  22...Be6  23.Rd1  Qxe5  24.Bf3  with a big advantage. } 23. Rd1 Qxe5 24.
Bxc4 Bd5 25. Kg1 { Winning a precious tempo. } 25... Qe6 26. Bf1
{ If Black wants to swap the Bishops, more effort has to be invested. } 26...
Bc4 { 23...Nf5  24.Bf2  . } 27. Bxc4 Qxc4 28. Rd4
{ White is a healthy Pawn up. We can retreat the Bishop to f2 and then activate our major pieces. }
