18... Qf6 19. Be3 { Tempo is important, the c3-Pawn − not so much. } 19... Qxc3
20. Rb1
{ Another file has been taken, which makes it even more difficult for Black to finish development. }
20... Nc6
{ Probably a better choice than  20...Nf5  , but the Knight has moved away from the King, which is good for us. }
21. Bh6 Bd7 { Basically, the only move. } 22. Re3
{ 22.Rxb7?  would blunder  22...Bg4! } 22... Qd4
{ 22...Qf6  23.Qd2  with a big advantage. } 23. c3 Qh4 24. Qd2
{ Thanks to this tactical trick,  24...Qxh6  25.Re8+  , White is able to coordinate all the pieces. To tell you the truth, I am not sure if Black has anything better than accepting an inferior ending with @@StartFEN@@r5k1/pp1b1r1p/2n3pB/2pp4/7q/P1PBR3/3Q1PPP/1R4K1 b - - 2 24@@EndFEN@@  24...Qxh6  25.Re8+  or @@StartFEN@@r5k1/pp1b1r1p/2n3pB/2pp4/7q/P1PBR3/3Q1PPP/1R4K1 b - - 2 24@@EndFEN@@  24...c4  25.Bf1  Qxh6  27.Re8+  .  The problem is that after the normal @@StartFEN@@r5k1/pp1b1r1p/2n3pB/2pp4/7q/P1PBR3/3Q1PPP/1R4K1 b - - 2 24@@EndFEN@@  24...Rb8  , White can simply retreat the Rook with  25.Ree1  ,  threatening Bh6-g5.  25...Qf6  will be met with  26.Bg5  and there are no good squares for the Queen.  26...Qg7  27.Bf1  and Black can't hold the weaknesses while @@StartFEN@@1r4k1/pp1b1r1p/2n2qp1/2pp2B1/8/P1PB4/3Q1PPP/1R2R1K1 b - - 6 26@@EndFEN@@  26...Qd6  is met with  27.Bc4! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "34. Winawer 7.Qg4 Qc7 Main Line"]
[Black "Winawer 7.Qg4 Qc7 8.Bd3 c4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... Bb4
{ The Winawer Variation is quite unique, even for the French. In most of the lines, the Bishop captures the Knight, and the arising Pawn structure is so specific that most of the players struggle to cope with it, especially since Black's dark squares are so weak that we tend to overestimate White's position. }
4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 { 6...Qc7  7.Qg4  Ne7  would transpose. } 7.
Qg4 Qc7
{ Black is ready to sacrifice the Kingside Pawns, claiming that this will yield sufficient compensation in the center. This is a key line of the Winawer and, as difficult as is, it seems to work in the end, although not as nicely as Black would like it to work.  White has many tries that require a very precise reaction from Black and therefore, there are not too many players that are brave enough to enter this variation frequently. It is much more common to use it as a surprise or as a targeted weapon against an opponent who does not feel too confident in messy positions. }
8. Bd3
{ Since there are many good tries and none of them offer any real advantage, we should not feel obliged to enter the sharpest and the riskiest line,  8.Qxg7  . My suggestion meets three criteria:   It is rather simple, especially the first couple of moves should be easy to remember and hard to forget.  It is safe − assuming we will forget our line at some point, we should still end up in a decent situation. By comparison, 8.Qxg7 does not offer this comfort. It is challenging − as usual, this is a must for me. Black has to play accurately in order to equalize.  
Chesswise, the point of White's last move is simple: developing the Bishop. :-@@EndBracket@@ This explanation might sound stupid but it makes more sense once you see the usual line −  8.Qxg7  Rg8  9.Qxh7  cxd4  10.Ne2  dxc3  ,  where our light-squared Bishop is shut on f1... }
8... c4
{ Black is taking the opportunity to close the position with a tempo. However, closing it with ...c5-c4 is generally a good thing for White. }
9. Be2 Qa5
{ Attacking our c3-Pawn right now will possibly transpose to the main line, but might also be connected with separate ideas. }
10. Bd2 Rg8
{ That's one possibility. Starting with @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/ppq1nppp/4p3/3pP3/2pP2Q1/P1P5/2P1BPPP/R1B1K1NR b KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Rg8  would be inaccurate, as White could consider  10.a4!?  Qa5  11.Qh3  followed by Qh3-e3, Be2-g4, Ng1-e2, and eventually the dark-squared Bishop would achieve the a3-square.   The other option would be to defend that Pawn with the King: @@StartFEN@@rnb1k1r1/pp2nppp/4p3/q2pP3/P1pP2Q1/2P5/2P1BPPP/R1B1K1NR w KQq - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Kd2  Nbc6  12.Nf3  Bd7  13.Ba3  O-O-O  14.Rhb1  and Black is not in time with  14...f6  , as White has  15.Rb5  Qa6  16.Qh5  with a big advantage. }
11. Qh3 { This plan works well with the Bishop on d2 as well. } 11... h6 12. a4
{ Making sure that Black won't block this square with the Queen. } 12... Nbc6
13. Bh5
{ This is the essence of White's plan − now Black will have a hard time castling without compromising the dark squares on the Kingside. }
13... Bd7 14. Ne2 g6 { No French player would like to make this move. } 15. Bg4
{ 15.Bf3  was also possible but then  15...Rh8  made more sense than in our line. }
15... h5
{ 15...Rh8  wouldn't really help due to  16.Qe3  followed by h2-h4-h5, with a clear advantage. }
16. Bf3 O-O-O 17. Bg5
{ We can castle on the next move. Black's position is solid but ugly. It is going to take a lot of maneuvering but White will make progress eventually. Our long-term plan is mostly on the Kingside and will most likely involve pushing the Pawn to g4.  However, White controls enough squares to play on both sides. I could easily imagine the white Queen on a3, for example, @@StartBracket@@g2-g3, Rf1-b1, and Qh3-f1-c1-a3@@EndBracket@@. }
*

