{ Black is ready to sacrifice the Kingside Pawns, claiming that this will yield sufficient compensation in the center. This is a key line of the Winawer and, as difficult as is, it seems to work in the end, although not as nicely as Black would like it to work.  White has many tries that require a very precise reaction from Black and therefore, there are not too many players that are brave enough to enter this variation frequently. It is much more common to use it as a surprise or as a targeted weapon against an opponent who does not feel too confident in messy positions. }
8. Bd3
{ Since there are many good tries and none of them offer any real advantage, we should not feel obliged to enter the sharpest and the riskiest line,  8.Qxg7  . My suggestion meets three criteria:   It is rather simple, especially the first couple of moves should be easy to remember and hard to forget.  It is safe − assuming we will forget our line at some point, we should still end up in a decent situation. By comparison, 8.Qxg7 does not offer this comfort. It is challenging − as usual, this is a must for me. Black has to play accurately in order to equalize.  
Chesswise, the point of White's last move is simple: developing the Bishop. :-@@EndBracket@@ This explanation might sound stupid but it makes more sense once you see the usual line −  8.Qxg7  Rg8  9.Qxh7  cxd4  10.Ne2  dxc3  ,  where our light-squared Bishop is shut on f1... }
8... cxd4 { The critical continuation. } 9. Ne2 Qxe5
{ Black is taking the wrong Pawn. } 10. cxd4 h5 { Basically the only move. }
11. Qh4 Qc7 12. O-O
{ White has a clear advantage in development and also the absence of Black's dark-squared Bishop is pretty noticeable. }
12... Nbc6 13. Bf4 Qd7 14. Qg3 Ng6
{ Black wants to give back the Pawn.  14...O-O  15.Rfe1  would be much better for White. }
15. h4
{ 15.Bxg6  would be better for White but we are going for the maximum profit. }
15... O-O 16. Rab1
{ White has a big advantage on both sides. After  16...b6  17.Rfe1  , it is hard to suggest a move for Black. }
*

