[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "34. Winawer 7.Qg4 Qc7 Main Line"]
[Black "Winawer 7.Qg4 Qc7 8.Bd3 cxd4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... Bb4
{ The Winawer Variation is quite unique, even for the French. In most of the lines, the Bishop captures the Knight, and the arising Pawn structure is so specific that most of the players struggle to cope with it, especially since Black's dark squares are so weak that we tend to overestimate White's position. }
4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 { 6...Qc7  7.Qg4  Ne7  would transpose. } 7.
Qg4 Qc7
{ Black is ready to sacrifice the Kingside Pawns, claiming that this will yield sufficient compensation in the center. This is a key line of the Winawer and, as difficult as is, it seems to work in the end, although not as nicely as Black would like it to work.  White has many tries that require a very precise reaction from Black and therefore, there are not too many players that are brave enough to enter this variation frequently. It is much more common to use it as a surprise or as a targeted weapon against an opponent who does not feel too confident in messy positions. }
8. Bd3
{ Since there are many good tries and none of them offer any real advantage, we should not feel obliged to enter the sharpest and the riskiest line,  8.Qxg7  . My suggestion meets three criteria:   It is rather simple, especially the first couple of moves should be easy to remember and hard to forget.  It is safe − assuming we will forget our line at some point, we should still end up in a decent situation. By comparison, 8.Qxg7 does not offer this comfort. It is challenging − as usual, this is a must for me. Black has to play accurately in order to equalize.  
Chesswise, the point of White's last move is simple: developing the Bishop. :-@@EndBracket@@ This explanation might sound stupid but it makes more sense once you see the usual line −  8.Qxg7  Rg8  9.Qxh7  cxd4  10.Ne2  dxc3  ,  where our light-squared Bishop is shut on f1... }
8... cxd4 { The critical continuation. } 9. Ne2 dxc3
{ Just like in the main line with @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/ppq1nppp/4p3/2ppP3/3P2Q1/P1P5/2P2PPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qxg7  ,  the black c-Pawn captures on d4 and c3, reaching the typical structure for this variation. }
10. Qxg7 Rg8 11. Qxh7 Qxe5
{ So this is the difference − Black wins our central Pawn and we will surely take the c3-Pawn. In the endgame, we will try to exploit our advantage on the Kingside. }
12. h4 { 12.Bf4  would most likely transpose to our line. } 12... Nbc6
{ Wrong square! } 13. Bf4 Qh8
{ 13...Qf6  14.Bg5  Qh8  15.Qxh8  Rxh8  16.Bf6  would be too easy. } 14. Qxh8
Rxh8 15. Bg5
{ The idea of bringing the Bishop to f6 is strong enough to spend a tempo on it. }
15... Ng8 { Or  15...e5  16.Nxc3  with a big advantage. } 16. Nxc3 f6 17. Bd2
{ It is just an improved version of what we should get in this line so no need to contemplate. We will advance the Pawn to h5 and make space for our King with f2-f3. }
*

