{ Black wants to drag our King to b2 before pushing the d5-Pawn. After  22.Kb2  d4  23.Ne4?!  @@StartBracket@@  23.Bxd4!?  Bxh1  24.Rxh1  is an interesting option.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@2r4r/1b1nnk2/p3pp2/1p5P/3pNPP1/P2BB3/1KP5/3R3R b - - 1 23@@EndFEN@@  23...dxe3  24.Nd6+  Kg8  25.Nxb7  Nb6!  Black has no problems. Compared with @@StartFEN@@r6r/1b1nnk2/p3pp2/1p1p3P/5PP1/P1NBB3/2P5/2KR3R b - - 0 21@@EndFEN@@  21...d4?  a key difference is that the  white Knight can't go to c5. }
22. Ne2 d4 23. Rh3
{ No, we are not blundering a piece, it's a sacrifice. :-@@EndBracket@@ } 23...
Bg2 { The best defence but clearly not obvious. } 24. Bg6+ Nxg6 25. hxg6+ Kg7
{ The King is staying away from f4-f5+. } 26. Rxh8 Rxh8 27. Nxd4 Rh1
{ Nailing it.  27...Kxg6  would be also possible, as White has nothing better than  28.Nxe6  , but this just looks more technical. }
28. Rxh1 Bxh1 29. Nxe6+ Kxg6 30. Nc7 Nb8
{ After  30...Bb7  31.Kd2  , White would still have some winning chances. The point is that the black Knight has no way of getting active, so it may as well come back home and defend the a6-Pawn while the light-squared Bishop can do the active part. }
31. Kd2
{ We can expect  31...Bf3  ,  forcing g4-g5. A strong player should confidently defend the position, but given the number of challenges Black already had to face, I think it would be a fair outcome. }
