14. Bg5 Qh8 15. Qxh8 Rxh8 16. Nxc3 a6 17. O-O-O f6
{ 18.Bd2  is not that strong now.  18...Nc5  followed by ...Bc8-d7 and ...Ke8-f7 and Black is quite solid. }
18. Be3 b5 19. h5 Bb7 { Now Black is ready for ...e6-e5. } 20. f4
{ Important move. White is preventing ...e6-e5 and slowly preparing g2-g4-g5. }
20... Kf7 { Objectively, Black should be able to equalize eventually. } 21. g4
{ This is a very good try and it only has been tried in correspondence chess so far. }
21... Rac8
{ Black wants to drag our King to b2 before pushing the d5-Pawn. After  22.Kb2  d4  23.Ne4?!  @@StartBracket@@  23.Bxd4!?  Bxh1  24.Rxh1  is an interesting option.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@2r4r/1b1nnk2/p3pp2/1p5P/3pNPP1/P2BB3/1KP5/3R3R b - - 1 23@@EndFEN@@  23...dxe3  24.Nd6+  Kg8  25.Nxb7  Nb6!  Black has no problems. Compared with @@StartFEN@@r6r/1b1nnk2/p3pp2/1p1p3P/5PP1/P1NBB3/2P5/2KR3R b - - 0 21@@EndFEN@@  21...d4?  a key difference is that the  white Knight can't go to c5. }
22. Ne2 d4 23. Rh3
{ No, we are not blundering a piece, it's a sacrifice. :-@@EndBracket@@ } 23...
Bg2 { The best defence but clearly not obvious. } 24. Bg6+ Nxg6 25. hxg6+ Kxg6
{ The most natural choice. } 26. Rxh8 Rxh8 27. f5+
{ This is why I prefer  25...Kg7  . } 27... exf5 28. Nf4+ Kf7
{ The best choice for Black, but it must be hard to figure this out over the board. }
29. Nxg2 Rh2 30. Rxd4 { 30.Ne1  didn't seem very practical. } 30... Ne5 31. Nf4
fxg4 32. Rd1
{ Black should be able to hold this, but definitely White is pressing. } *

