[White "35. French 3.Nc3 − 3rd Move Alternatives"]
[Black "French 3.Nc3 c6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... c6
{ Do you know the 3.f3 line in the Caro-Kann Defense? @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.f3!?  and now one of the possible moves for Black is  3...e6  .  I don't think I need to convince anyone that with the Knight on c3 instead of the Pawn on f3, White gets a much better version  of that line. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  would be perfectly fine, but I like our choice even more. }
4. Bd3
{ The main point of this move is that we are not afraid of sacrificing our central Pawn. }
4... Bb4 { This is what Black usually does in the Caro-Kann. } 5. e5 b6
{ Black wants to swap the light-squared Bishops. } 6. h4
{ A natural advance, but here we are also waiting for Black's next move. } 6...
Ba6 { 6...Ne7  7.Qg4!  would already be problematic for Black. } 7. Bxa6 Nxa6
8. Qd3 Nc7 9. Qg3
{ After  9...Kf8  , we can just go  10.a3  Bxc3+  11.Qxc3  , so Black won't even break our Pawn structure. It seems that the best Black can do is to retreat the Bishop with @@StartFEN@@r2qk1nr/p1n2ppp/1pp1p3/3pP3/1b1P3P/2N3Q1/PPP2PP1/R1B1K1NR b KQkq - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Bf8  , though after  10.Nf3  ,  followed by h4-h5 and Nc3-e2, White's advantage is quite serious already. }
