[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... h6
{ This move was once played by Magnus Carlsen in Banter Blitz on chess24 and that's probably the best thing we can say about it. }
4. Bd3
{ In general, we prefer to develop the Bishop first − it is more flexible as the Knight can still go to e2. Also, after  4.Nf3  , we always have to consider  4...Nf6  5.e5  Ne4  . }
4... c5
{ This move is the main point of the 3...a6 line, but here it's just wrong. }
5. exd5 exd5
{ 5...cxd4  6.Bb5+  and White is already on the verge of winning. For example, after  6...Bd7  , White can simply take on d4 or play the even stronger  7.dxe6  Bxb5  8.Qh5! }
6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. Bb5+ { And just like that, White wins the Pawn. } 7... Bd7 8.
Qxd5 Qe7+
{ In case you were worried that Black might get some compensation here. } 9.
Qe4
{ Thanks to this trick, Black won't. After  9...Qxe4+  10.Nxe4  ,  the Bishop on c5 is under attack, and  10...Bxf2+??  loses another one after  11.Kxf2  Bxb5  12.Nd6+  . }
9... Bxb5 10. Qxe7+ Nxe7 11. Nxb5
{ White is a healthy Pawn up. Finishing development is the only advice I can give you. }
*

