1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... a6
{ At least compared with  3...h6  ,  Black controls the b5-square, which is useful in some cases. Naturally, it doesn't really affect the evaluation as we should not have any problems gaining the advantage. }
4. Bd3 c5
{ I will only mention that  4...Nc6  makes as little sense as always.  5.Nf3  Nb4  6.Be2  is much better for White. }
5. dxc5 Bxc5
{ The main point of 3...a6 is that Black does not really blunder the Pawn on d5. }
6. exd5 exd5 7. Nxd5 { There was no  7.Bb5+  , but we have this trick. } 7...
Bxf2+ 8. Kxf2 Qxd5 9. Qf3
{ White will be easily better in the endgame. The Bishop pair plus the Pawn majority on the Queenside are a great combination. }
9... Ne7
{ We don't mind the Black Knight in the center − an easy target for our Pawns. }
10. Qxd5 Nxd5 11. Nf3 O-O 12. a3
{ Anticipating ...Nd5-b4, but also preparing b2-b4. } 12... Nc6 13. Re1
{ It's good to remember this idea. The natural  13.c4  would be slightly better for White, but it's more accurate to wait. The difference is that after  13.c4  Nf6  14.Re1  , Black can harass our Bishop with  14...Rd8  . }
13... Rd8 { Given my previous comment, we have to consider this move. } 14. Bg5
f6 15. Rad1
{ Simple and elegant.  15...fxg5  16.Bc4  is just hopeless. Black can go @@StartFEN@@r1br2k1/1p4pp/p1n2p2/3n2B1/8/P2B1N2/1PP2KPP/3RR3 b - - 1 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Kf7  , but then we can simply retreat  the Bishop to c1 and start advancing our Queenside Pawns. It will be much easier with our Rooks controlling central files. }
