1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... Nc6
{ The most popular of all the sidelines, but it does not really offer Black any real value other than a surprise. }
4. e5 { In my opinion, this is stronger than  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.e5  Ne4  . } 4...
f6
{ Since the Knight is blocking the c7-Pawn, this is the only way to challenge our Pawn center. }
5. Bb5
{ We generally don't want to swap our light-squared Bishop. However, here, despite having our central Pawns on the dark squares, we didn't really weaken any light squares @@StartBracket@@notice the Pawn on c2 instead of c3 and f2 instead of f4@@EndBracket@@. Combine it with a swift development and Black's terrible light-squared Bishop and it all makes perfect sense. Oh, I forgot one thing: we might still retreat that Bishop! }
5... Qd7
{ Not a popular move, but it was twice used by Richard Rapport. Black intends to chase away our Bishop and then, perhaps, move the Queen to f7 and try the castle plan. }
6. f4 { A radical solution, but it works really well here. } 6... a6 7. Be2 Nh6
{ The long-castle plan makes no sense anymore as it would be too difficult to obtain any counterplay on the Kingside with the white Pawn on f4. }
8. Nf3 Be7 9. O-O
{ White is clearly better. Our plan is to move the Bishop to d3 @@StartBracket@@in order to do it, we have to prevent ...Nc6-b4 by playing a2-a3 first@@EndBracket@@ and then the Knight will move from c3 to e2. }
