1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... dxe4
{ Black has released the tension in the center. In general, this should be good news for White. }
4. Nxe4 Nf6 { A dubious continuation. } 5. Nxf6+
{ Taking back with the Pawn breaks Black's Pawn structure. Taking back with Queen is against one of the most principled rules: we should not develop our Queen early as it can easily become a target. }
5... Qxf6 { The Queen is exposed on f6. } 6. Nf3 h6
{ After Bf1-d3, Black will anyway have to do it so we might as well start with it. }
7. Bd3 Bd6 { 7...Nc6  8.c3  Bd6  9.Qe2  Bd7  10.O-O  transposes. } 8. Qe2
{ Giving Black one more chance to lose the Queen. } 8... Bd7
{ 8...Nc6  9.c3  Bd7  10.O-O  transposes. } 9. O-O
{ We don't need to worry about  9...Bc6  10.Ne5  . } 9... Nc6 10. c3 Ne7
{ Although White is better in many ways, I think it's worth seeing this line to learn the ideas. }
11. Ne5 Bxe5 12. dxe5 Qh4 13. b4
{ We are ready to meet  13...Bc6  with  14.b5  . } 13... a6 14. f4 Bc6
{ 14...Nf5  would be met with  15.a4  Bc6  16.Ba3!  Black is just too slow to obtain any counterplay. }
15. a4 O-O 16. Be3
{ After  16...Nd5  , we can retreat the Bishop with  17.Bd2  and how can Black  stop b4-b5? }
16... Nf5
{ Perhaps one more tempo would allow Black to make this setup work but eventually, it always comes down to a single tempo. }
17. Bf2 Qxf4 18. Bc5 Qg5 19. b5
{ The most precise way − Black will not be allowed to get any compensation. }
19... axb5 20. axb5 Bd5 21. Bxf8 Rxf8 22. Rf2
{ But not  22.c4??  Bxg2!  23.Qxg2  Qe3+  .  We will play c3-c4 on the next move with a winning position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "36. Rubinstein Variation 3.Nc3 dxe4 4.Nxe4 Bd7/Nf6"]
[Black "Rubinstein 4.Nxe4 Nf6 5.Nxf6+ Qxf6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... dxe4
{ Black has released the tension in the center. In general, this should be good news for White. }
4. Nxe4 Nf6 { A dubious continuation. } 5. Nxf6+
{ Taking back with the Pawn breaks Black's Pawn structure. Taking back with Queen is against one of the most principled rules: we should not develop our Queen early as it can easily become a target. }
5... Qxf6 { The Queen is exposed on f6. } 6. Nf3 h6
{ After Bf1-d3, Black will anyway have to do it so we might as well start with it. }
7. Bd3 Bd6 { 7...Nc6  8.c3  Bd6  9.Qe2  Bd7  10.O-O  transposes. } 8. Qe2
{ Giving Black one more chance to lose the Queen. } 8... Bd7
{ 8...Nc6  9.c3  Bd7  10.O-O  transposes. } 9. O-O
{ We don't need to worry about  9...Bc6  10.Ne5  . } 9... Nc6 10. c3 O-O
{ We could go  11.Re1  here, however, after  11...Ne7  Black gets an improved version of the 10...Ne7 line and although White is still on top, we need to be accurate. Therefore I prefer: }
11. Rd1
{ We don't need to worry about  11...e5  12.Qe4!  and White wins the Pawn. }
11... Ne7 { With the Rook on d1 this just won't work. } 12. Ne5 Bxe5
{ A losing mistake but otherwise Black's previous move would be pointless. }
13. dxe5 Qh4 14. Bc2 { White is threatening both Rd1xd7 and Rd1-d4. } 14... Nd5
15. c4 Nb6 16. Be3 Rfd8 17. Rd4 Qe7 18. Rg4
{ After  18...Kf8  , the simple  19.Qd3  wins. } *

