{ Black has released the tension in the center. In general, this should be good news for White. }
4. Nxe4 Be7 { Black intends to recapture on f6 with the Bishop. } 5. Nf3 Nf6 6.
Nxf6+ Bxf6 7. c3 { Important nuance −  7.Bd3?!  would allow  7...c5! } 7... Nd7
8. Bd3 O-O
{ Black should not have rushed with castling. White can now obtain a strong attack. }
9. h4 { Threatening the Greek gift sacrifice. } 9... Re8
{ Black has defended against the worst.  10.Bxh7+?!  Kxh7  11.Ng5+  Kg8  12.Qh5  Nf8!  13.Qxf7+  Kh8  and there is nothing more than a perpetual check. Alternatively, @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pppn1ppp/4pb2/8/3P3P/2PB1N2/PP3PP1/R1BQK2R b KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...h6  could be played but then simple  10.Qe2  threatening Qe2-e4 would be strong. }
10. Ng5 g6 11. Ne4
{ White has a big advantage. Our plan is pretty simple: advance the h-pawn, and  11...e5  should be met with  12.d5  . }
