1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... dxe4
{ Black has released the tension in the center. In general, this should be good news for White. }
4. Nxe4 Be7 { Black intends to recapture on f6 with the Bishop. } 5. Nf3 Nf6 6.
Nxf6+ Bxf6 7. c3 { Important nuance −  7.Bd3?!  would allow  7...c5! } 7... Nd7
8. Bd3 c5 { This is how Black should play, being only worse :-@@EndBracket@@. }
9. O-O
{ 9.Bc2!?  intending to meet  9...cxd4  with  10.Nxd4  would also be better for White. }
9... O-O { 9...cxd4  10.cxd4  O-O  11.Re1  transposes. } 10. Re1 cxd4 11. cxd4
{ Black's main problem is that he can't fianchetto the light-squared Bishop.  11...b6??  would lose an exchange after  12.Be4!  Rb8  13.Bf4  . }
11... Nb6 12. Be4 { Aimed against ...Bc8-d7. } 12... Nd5 13. Qd3
{ The h7-Pawn is hanging. } 13... g6 14. h4 { Typical advance. } 14... Bd7 15.
Bh6 Bg7 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Bxd5 { Just before the Bishop managed to reach c6. }
