[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "37. Rubinstein Variation 4.Nxe4 Nd7"]
[Black "Rubinstein 4.Nxe4 Nd7 − 7.Be3 Bd6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... dxe4
{ Black has released the tension in the center. In general, this should be good news for White. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ Black's plan is to develop the pieces and, when the time comes, challenge White's center with ...c7-c5. It's a frequent guest in tournament practice mainly because of the complex positions arising from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bb4  or  3...Nf6  4.e5  , which are not to everyone's taste.  Also, if White does not handle the opening accurately, Black might equalize quite easily by just making healthy moves. Naturally, we are going to handle the opening as accurately as we can. }
5. Nf3 Ngf6 { 5...Be7  transposes to the 4...Be7 move order. } 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7.
Be3
{ This specific move order is directed against the ...c7-c5 plan which would be kind of a problem after  7.Bd3  .  Black can now develop his dark-squared Bishop to one of two possible squares or directly challenge our setup with ...Nf6-d5. }
7... Bd6
{ What I like about White's setup is that we don't really care if it's ...Bd6 or ...Be7. We will anyway place the light-squared Bishop on d3, the Queen on e2, and then castle long. }
8. Bd3 b6
{ Black could also start with ...O-O, which should transpose soon as it is hard to imagine the fianchetto will be skipped. }
9. Qe2 O-O 10. O-O-O Bb7 11. Rhe1
{ Although both sides have castled on the opposite sides, we are not going to see any immediate attacks on the Kings. The reason for that is that none of the sides have any clear targets. Therefore, the game will be mostly focused in the center. }
11... Nd5
{ This was recently played in a game between Pichot and Meier in Dubai Rapid Cup 2021. Georg Meier is probably the biggest advocate of the Rubinstein Variation right now, so we should really pay attention.   The point of Black's last move is that if we retreat the Bishop with  12.Bd2  , then  12...Nf4  will come, forcing the exchange. However, in my opinion, this plan doesn't go well in pair with the fianchettoing of the light-squared Bishop, which will soon become apparent. }
12. Kb1 Nxe3 13. fxe3 Qe7
{ 13...c5??  would blunder the Pawn after  14.dxc5  bxc5  15.Bxh7+!  Kxh7  16.Qd3+  Kg8  17.Qxd6  . }
14. e4 { White is threatening e4-e5. } 14... e5 15. Bc4
{ Nice improving move by Pichot. Let's first see what happens if Black takes on d4. }
15... exd4 16. e5 Bc5 17. h4
{ White's attack is more dangerous than it seems. Nf3-g5 and e5-e6 are very powerful ideas and it's not clear how to stop them. }
17... h6 { Just to prove our point... } 18. e6 fxe6 19. Ng5
{ This is how bad Black's position already is. } 19... hxg5 20. Bxe6+ Rf7 21.
hxg5 g6
{ 21...Bc8  wouldn't help.  22.Bxf7+  Qxf7  23.Qe4  ,  threatening Qe4xa8 and g5-g6. }
22. Qe5 { White is winning as Black can't prevent Re1-h1. } *

