3... dxe4
{ Black has released the tension in the center. In general, this should be good news for White. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ Black's plan is to develop the pieces and, when the time comes, challenge White's center with ...c7-c5. It's a frequent guest in tournament practice mainly because of the complex positions arising from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bb4  or  3...Nf6  4.e5  , which are not to everyone's taste.  Also, if White does not handle the opening accurately, Black might equalize quite easily by just making healthy moves. Naturally, we are going to handle the opening as accurately as we can. }
5. Nf3 Ngf6 { 5...Be7  transposes to the 4...Be7 move order. } 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7.
Be3
{ This specific move order is directed against the ...c7-c5 plan which would be kind of a problem after  7.Bd3  .  Black can now develop his dark-squared Bishop to one of two possible squares or directly challenge our setup with ...Nf6-d5. }
7... Bd6
{ What I like about White's setup is that we don't really care if it's ...Bd6 or ...Be7. We will anyway place the light-squared Bishop on d3, the Queen on e2, and then castle long. }
8. Bd3 b6
{ Black could also start with ...O-O, which should transpose soon as it is hard to imagine the fianchetto will be skipped. }
9. Qe2 O-O 10. O-O-O Bb7 11. Rhe1
{ Although both sides have castled on the opposite sides, we are not going to see any immediate attacks on the Kings. The reason for that is that none of the sides have any clear targets. Therefore, the game will be mostly focused in the center. }
11... c5
{ The main point of developing the Bishop to d6 − this move would not be possible with the Bishop on e7 due to d4xc5 and Bd3xh7+. }
12. dxc5 bxc5 13. Bg5
{ Clearly, there are disadvantages of not having the Bishop on e7. } 13... h6
14. Bh4 Qc7
{ Black is OK with  15.Bxf6  gxf6  as that would hand the control of most squares in the center. }
15. Ne5
{ This is why we put the Rook on e1! Our Knight is becoming our most important asset. }
15... Nd5 16. Bg3
{ White is better. We can go c2-c3, retreat the Bishop to c2 and then try to combine our strong position in the center with possible attacking chances on the Kingside @@StartBracket@@b1-h7 diagonal@@EndBracket@@. The good thing is that in many cases we will have the advantage in the endgame too, as Black has some potential weaknesses on the Queenside. }
