[Black "Rubinstein 4.Nxe4 Nd7 − 7.Be3 Be7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense got its name after Paris beat London in a correspondence match in 1834, successfully adopting this opening with Black. The French is different than other openings after 1.e4 − the structures we are going to see are not often seen in other openings @@StartBracket@@especially the Winawer@@EndBracket@@, which makes it difficult to handle with the white pieces. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The fashion changes, but  3.Nc3  remains the main move. Not only is the Knight developed to the most active square, but in a way we are also anticipating  3...c5  . }
3... dxe4
{ Black has released the tension in the center. In general, this should be good news for White. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ Black's plan is to develop the pieces and, when the time comes, challenge White's center with ...c7-c5. It's a frequent guest in tournament practice mainly because of the complex positions arising from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bb4  or  3...Nf6  4.e5  , which are not to everyone's taste.  Also, if White does not handle the opening accurately, Black might equalize quite easily by just making healthy moves. Naturally, we are going to handle the opening as accurately as we can. }
5. Nf3 Ngf6 { 5...Be7  transposes to the 4...Be7 move order. } 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7.
Be3
{ This specific move order is directed against the ...c7-c5 plan which would be kind of a problem after  7.Bd3  .  Black can now develop his dark-squared Bishop to one of two possible squares or directly challenge our setup with ...Nf6-d5. }
7... Be7
{ Developing the Bishop to e7 indicates that Black might be planning an early ...c7-c5 as after d4xc5, the Bishop won't be attacked. }
8. Bd3 O-O 9. Qe2 b6
{ This setup is rather passive but there is one nuance we should be aware of. }
10. O-O-O Bb7 11. Kb1
{ With the Bishop on d6, our move was Rh1-e1 as White was anticipating ...c7-c5. Here, ...c7-c5 is not a problem due to a possible x-ray on the d-file.   However, Black had another idea:  11.Rhe1?!  would be met with  11...Qd5!  12.Kb1  Qh5!  and White can't  prevent ...Bb7xf3, breaking our Pawn structure. }
11... Nd5 12. Bd2 { 12.h4  would be also nice. } 12... c5 13. dxc5 Bxc5
{ 13...bxc5  made no sense.  14.c4  Nf6  15.Ne5  followed by Bd2-c3, with a crushing advantage. }
14. c4 Nf6 15. Bc3
{ White is clearly better. We will put the Knight on e5 and then advance the h-pawn. In case of ...Qd8-e7, we can consider a2-a3, preventing ...Bc5-b4. It is hard to tell how Black can organize counterplay. }
