4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ Black's plan is to develop the pieces and, when the time comes, challenge White's center with ...c7-c5. It's a frequent guest in tournament practice mainly because of the complex positions arising from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bb4  or  3...Nf6  4.e5  , which are not to everyone's taste.  Also, if White does not handle the opening accurately, Black might equalize quite easily by just making healthy moves. Naturally, we are going to handle the opening as accurately as we can. }
5. Nf3 Ngf6 { 5...Be7  transposes to the 4...Be7 move order. } 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7.
Be3
{ This specific move order is directed against the ...c7-c5 plan which would be kind of a problem after  7.Bd3  .  Black can now develop his dark-squared Bishop to one of two possible squares or directly challenge our setup with ...Nf6-d5. }
7... Be7
{ Developing the Bishop to e7 indicates that Black might be planning an early ...c7-c5 as after d4xc5, the Bishop won't be attacked. }
8. Bd3 O-O 9. Qe2 c5 { A logical try − Black is fighting for the center. } 10.
O-O-O Qc7
{ Now we directly transposed to a good version of the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/8/3P4/5N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bd3  line:  7...c5  8.Be3  Qc7  9.Qe2  Be7  @@StartBracket@@instead, Black should play  9...a6!  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/ppq1bppp/4pn2/2p5/3P4/3BBN2/PPP1QPPP/R3K2R w KQkq - 4 10@@EndFEN@@  10.O-O-O  O-O  . }
11. dxc5 Nd5 { Black wants to take on e3 and only then on c5. } 12. Bd2
{ I prefer this one over  12.Bd4  Nf4  . } 12... Bxc5
{ This is what you can expect from 90% of your opponents. However, Black's Bishop belongs to f6, not c5. }
13. Kb1 a6
{ 13...b5  would not be a problem.  14.Bxb5  Rb8  15.Bc4  and the Bishop on b3 will prevent Black from obtaining any valid counterplay. }
14. g4 { White's attack is clearly faster. } 14... b5 15. Ng5 g6 16. Qe1
{ A unique idea! The point is that now we don't care about ...Nd5-f4 as we always have Bd3-e4. At the same time, our plan is very simple: push the h-Pawn. Needless to say, the Queen can join the attack in many ways − the hypothetical Rh1-h8+ and Qd1-h1+ is one of them. }
