8. Bd2 Be7
{ Black is delaying ...c7-c5 waiting for White to develop the light-squared Bishop first. }
9. Bd3 c5
{ Both sides moved their Bishops @@StartBracket@@Bf1-d3 and ...Bf8-e7@@EndBracket@@ so it's hard to say that Black has actually gained anything with this delay. }
10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. O-O
{ Probably this is one of the most difficult moments. We have already seen how well the long castle lines worked so why not now? Let's try  11.Qe2  instead:  11...O-O  12.O-O-O  and now  12...Qc7  will transpose to one of the 7...Be7 lines which we like.  However Black can instead go  12...b5!  and it turns out that things are not that simple. Perhaps it is easier to reverse the question: why didn't we just castle short after@@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/8/3P4/4BN2/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Be7?  After  8.Bd3  O-O  9.O-O  , Black is not  forced to go ...c7-c5. The Bishop can be fianchettoed  − after  9...b6  , it seems that Black is doing just fine. }
11... O-O 12. Qe2 Qc7 13. Qe4
{ Provoking some serious weaknesses in Black's camp. } 13... f5
{ 13...Nf6  would give White a too strong attack after  14.Qh4  . } 14. Qe2 Bd7
15. Rfe1
{ White has a nice long-term advantage. We can place the Knight on e5 improving the pressure on Black's position. Also, a2-a3 makes a lot of sense − we would be happy to play b2-b4 and if Black stops it with ...a7-a5, then at least we provoked another weakness. }
