Be3
{ This specific move order is directed against the ...c7-c5 plan which would be kind of a problem after  7.Bd3  .  Black can now develop his dark-squared Bishop to one of two possible squares or directly challenge our setup with ...Nf6-d5. }
7... Nd5
{ The most ambitious response. If we allow taking on e3 with  8.Bd3  Nxe3  9.fxe3  , then Black will  be able to achieve ...e6-e5 with the Bishop on c8. Please compare it  with the Pichot-Meier game @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/8/3P4/4BN2/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bd6  8.Bd3  b6  9.Qe2  O-O  10.O-O-O  Bb7  11.Rhe1  Nd5  @@EndBracket@@  . }
8. Bd2 c5
{ The most critical line. Black challenges our Pawn center as quickly as possible. }
9. Bb5+
{ The only move to fight for advantage but also a logical one. Since Black still hasn't moved the dark-squared Bishop, it makes sense to bet on development. }
9... Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. c4
{ Once again, this has to be played.  11.O-O  cxd4  12.Nxd4  Be7  wouldn't pose Black any problems. }
