{ Black claims to get an improved version of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  variation  . However, in reality, it is White who benefits from the inclusion of the moves ...Bf5 and h4. }
5. dxc5 Nc6 { 5...e6??  would drop the piece after  6.g4! } 6. Bb5 Qc7
{ Once again, Black could not play  6...e6  because of  7.g4! } 7. Nc3
{ But now Black is forced to act! } 7... Qxe5+ 8. Nge2
{ Black has won the Pawn back but the Queen is exposed in the center and White is clearly ahead in development. }
8... e6 9. Bf4 Qf6 10. Bg5 Qe5 11. Qd4
{ Black can choose between two bad options:  11...Qxd4  12.Nxd4  or @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/1BPpqbB1/3Q3P/2N5/PPP1NPP1/R3K2R b KQkq - 5 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qc7  12.Ng3  . White's advantage is overwhelming in both cases. }
