10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bc5
{ The immediate  11...Nc6  would be even worse. After  12.Nb5  Rc8?  13.c4!  dxc4  14.Bg5  , White already has a winning advantage.  Objectively, @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/pp3pp1/q1n1p3/1N1pP2p/P6P/8/1PP2PP1/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12...O-O-O  has to be played but I don't think I need to convince anyone that it is not OK for Black to castle long in such a position.   After  11...Nh6  12.Qxh5  , White is just a Pawn up. }
12. Nb5 Qb6 13. c4
{ Since White's advantage is based on activity, we have to play dynamically. }
13... a6 { 13...dxc4  14.Nd2  is just over. } 14. N5c3 d4
{ 14...dxc4  15.Nd2  would be much better for White. } 15. Ne4 Nd7 16. Re1 Ne7
{ 16...Nxe5?  would be met with  17.Nxc5  Qxc5  18.b4!  Qc7  19.Bf4  and Black has to play ugly  19...f6  . After  20.Nd2  White has a winning advantage. }
17. a5 Qc7 18. Nxc5 Qxc5 19. Nd2
{ White has a strong initiative. Taking the Pawn is risky:  19...Nxe5  20.Ne4  followed by c4-c5. Notice that Black can't castle due to the weak h5-Pawn, a common problem for Black in this line. }
