{ The name Caro-Kann Defense comes from two players, Horatio Caro and Marcus Kann, who analyzed this opening in 1886. Its strategic idea is both sound and simple: Black wants to put the Pawn on d5, just like in the French, but without depriving the light-squared Bishop of its future on the h3-c8 diagonal.  I consider it a third @@StartBracket@@next to the Sicilian Defense and 1.e4 e5@@EndBracket@@ great @@StartBracket@@and bulletproof@@EndBracket@@ defense against 1.e4 − something that can be successfully used for a very long time. It is also strategically rich, as White can aim for both open and closed positions. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ The Advance Variation has always been considered critical against the Caro-Kann. After all, grabbing space in the center can't be a bad strategy. }
3... Bf5
{ This is the Caro-Kann players' argument in their debates with the French players. The Bishop is strong on f5, although it is frequently becoming a target and is sometimes missed on the Queenside. }
4. h4
{ One of the hottest Caro-Kann trends in recent years. It has been a part of the repertoires of many top 1.e4 players in the world such as Caruana, Giri, or Dominguez Perez. The main point of this aggressive continuation is to prepare the even more aggressive g2-g4.  Now Black has a choice: either allow g2-g4 or prevent it with ...h7-h5. Since ...h7-h5 is by far the main @@StartBracket@@and best!@@EndBracket@@ continuation, we could also say that by playing h2-h4, White is provoking ...h7-h5 which, as a result, weakens the g5-square. }
4... h5 { Now both g4 and g5 are weak. } 5. Bd3
{ The most natural continuation as Black's light-squared Bishop was very active on f5. }
5... Bxd3 6. Qxd3 e6
{ This move order allows the aggressive  7.Bg5  Qb6  8.Nd2  . However, as recent tournament practice has shown @@StartBracket@@Shirov-Shankland, Berlin GP 2022@@EndBracket@@, Black has no problems in that line. }
7. Nf3
{ On the other hand, Black has no way of exploiting it since  7...Qa5+  is the best move anyway. }
7... c5
{ This is a serious continuation and I think it is just a matter of time before it becomes more frequent in tournament practice. }
8. dxc5
{ 8.Bg5  is perhaps critical, but also very complex and since Black's previous move is rarely seen, I don't think it's the most practical choice. }
8... Bxc5 9. c4 Nc6 10. O-O Nb4
{ The best response. Black is trying to use the pieces that are already in play. }
11. Qe2 dxc4 12. Rd1
{ 12.Qxc4  Qd5!  was Black's point. With the text move, we are creating a real challenge. }
12... Nd3 13. Nc3 { The Knight is heading to e4. } 13... Qc7
{ The best reaction.  13...Nh6  14.Ne4  Qc7  15.Rxd3  cxd3  16.Qxd3  transposes. }
14. Ne4 Nh6
{ This is much stronger than  14...Ne7  15.b3!  Black's point is that now @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/ppq2pp1/4p2n/2b1P2p/2p1N2P/3n1N2/PP2QPP1/R1BR2K1 w kq - 6 15@@EndFEN@@  15.b3?!  would be met with  15...Ng4! }
15. Rxd3
{ The best try. After the exchange sacrifice, Black will face some immediate problems with the King still in the center and the pieces lacking coordination. }
15... cxd3 16. Qxd3 { Right now Qb5+ is a threat. } 16... Qb6
{ Logical but inaccurate. Now Black's task will be very difficult. } 17. Bxh6
Rxh6 18. Rd1 { Black has to deal with Qd3-d7+. } 18... Be7
{ Black correctly claims that  19.Qd7+  Kf8  leads nowhere. } 19. Nd6+ Bxd6
{ 19...Kf8??  20.Ng5  would transpose. } 20. exd6
{ It is really not obvious how Black should react now. For example,  20...Rd8  is easily refuted with  21.d7+  followed  by Qd3-a3+. }
20... a5 { Beautiful defense! The point is to control b4-square. } 21. d7+ Ke7
{ Black doesn't need to be worried about  22.Qa3+  Qb4  . } 22. Qc3 Rd8
{ This is the best. Black is not worried about  23.Qxg7  Rg6  . } 23. Rd4
{ The best try. Now White, once again, is threatening Qc3-a3+. } 23... f6
{ This time it is losing. } 24. Qa3+ Kf7 25. Rf4
{ Black can't stop Nf3-g5+ as  25...Kg8  26.Qe7  is easily winning. } 25... Qc7
26. Ng5+ Kg8 27. Nxe6 Qc1+ 28. Kh2 Rxd7
{ Black might hope that this would save the day. } 29. Qf8+ Kh7 30. Qe8 Rd1
{ It seems that Black is escaping with this one... } 31. Rxf6
{ Beautiful but it is not that difficult. } 31... Rh1+ 32. Kg3 Rxf6 33. Ng5+
Qxg5+ { It's better than mate in one, isn't it? } 34. hxg5 Rf5 35. f4
{ White is technically winning. With such a weak King, there is not much that Black can do. }
*

