{ Compared with the 4.dxc5 line, Black's Knight is already committed to c6. }
5... Bg4
{ Black is trying to solve the light-squared Bishop problem before playing ...e7-e6. }
6. c3 a6
{ Black is preventing Bf1-b5 but, at the same, allows our next move... } 7. Qb3
{ Now Black needs to defend the b7-Pawn. } 7... Qc7
{ Black is hoping to get some compensation for the central Pawn. } 8. Qxd5 e6
9. Qe4 Bxf3 10. gxf3 Qxe5
{ Although it might not be that obvious, White should get a winning advantage after this. }
11. Qxe5 Nxe5 12. b4
{ Needless to say, the c5-Pawn is far more important than f3. } 12... Nxf3+ 13.
Kd1
{ 13.Ke2  might seem more natural but after  13...Ne5  ,  Black can go ...Ne5-g6 later, and some possible checks on f4 might happen. After the text move, the white King will be very comfortable on c2. }
13... O-O-O+ 14. Kc2 Nf6 15. Na3
{ The Knight will come to c4, the dark-squared Bishop to e3 or f4. Black's position is just hopeless. }
