1. e4 c6
{ The name Caro-Kann Defense comes from two players, Horatio Caro and Marcus Kann, who analyzed this opening in 1886. Its strategic idea is both sound and simple: Black wants to put the Pawn on d5, just like in the French, but without depriving the light-squared Bishop of its future on the h3-c8 diagonal.  I consider it a third @@StartBracket@@next to the Sicilian Defense and 1.e4 e5@@EndBracket@@ great @@StartBracket@@and bulletproof@@EndBracket@@ defense against 1.e4 − something that can be successfully used for a very long time. It is also strategically rich, as White can aim for both open and closed positions. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ The Advance Variation has always been considered critical against the Caro-Kann. After all, grabbing space in the center can't be a bad strategy. }
3... c5
{ This line has become very popular in recent years. Instead of developing the Bishop to f5, which is logical but slow, Black is trying to undermine our Pawn center right away. }
4. Nf3
{ Instead of capturing the Pawn, White is focusing on the quick development of the pieces. }
4... Nc6 { In my opinion, this is slightly inaccurate. } 5. dxc5
{ Compared with the 4.dxc5 line, Black's Knight is already committed to c6. }
5... e6
{ The strongest choice, but with the Knight on c6, it is not enough for equality. }
6. a3
{ 6.Be3  was also possible but after  6...Nh6!  the outcome wasn't that clear to me. }
6... Bxc5 7. b4 Be7
{ A bit odd, but not impossible. The point is that Black wants to quickly play ...f7-f6 − the Bishop on e7 might end up on the long diagonal. }
8. Nbd2
{ The more aggressive  8.b5!?  is also possible. However, given that we don't really expect to face this line too often, I believe it is better to have a simple and logical answer, especially if it works well. }
8... f6 9. Bb2 Nh6 { The Knight is heading to f7. } 10. Be2
{ I want to suggest an alternative line here not only because it is good but also to understand the difference between these two similar moves  @@StartBracket@@  10.Be2  and  10.Bd3  @@EndBracket@@  . }
10... O-O 11. O-O fxe5
{ As you shall see, with the Bishop on d3, Black doesn't take on e5 but plays ...Nh6-f7. Here,  11...Nf7  would be weaker.  12.exf6  Bxf6  13.Bxf6  Qxf6  14.c4  and White is just better as  14...Nce5  does not attack the Bishop. }
12. Nxe5 Bf6 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. c4
{ White is slightly better. We can put the Knight on b3 and then probably just take on d5. Black will most likely recapture with the c-Pawn and then we can put the Rook on c1 and advance our Pawns on the Queenside. }
