1. e4 c6
{ The name Caro-Kann Defense comes from two players, Horatio Caro and Marcus Kann, who analyzed this opening in 1886. Its strategic idea is both sound and simple: Black wants to put the Pawn on d5, just like in the French, but without depriving the light-squared Bishop of its future on the h3-c8 diagonal.  I consider it a third @@StartBracket@@next to the Sicilian Defense and 1.e4 e5@@EndBracket@@ great @@StartBracket@@and bulletproof@@EndBracket@@ defense against 1.e4 − something that can be successfully used for a very long time. It is also strategically rich, as White can aim for both open and closed positions. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ The Advance Variation has always been considered critical against the Caro-Kann. After all, grabbing space in the center can't be a bad strategy. }
3... c5
{ This line has become very popular in recent years. Instead of developing the Bishop to f5, which is logical but slow, Black is trying to undermine our Pawn center right away. }
4. Nf3
{ Instead of capturing the Pawn, White is focusing on the quick development of the pieces. }
4... cxd4 5. Qxd4
{ A bit unusual as normally we don't want to develop the Queen that early. However, the Queen will be quite comfortable on the Kingside while the Knight is better placed on f3, from where it protects the key e5-Pawn. }
5... Nc6 6. Qf4 e6
{ Anyway, Black had no chance of activating the light-squared Bishop. } 7. Bd3
Nge7
{ Based on the false assumption that it is okay to trade the Knight on g6. } 8.
O-O Ng6 9. Bxg6 { Funnily enough, this is a novelty. } 9... hxg6
{ It might seem that Black is doing just fine − the Rook has been activated and swapping our light-squared Bishop is usually good for Black, isn't it? }
10. c4
{ The h-file has no value and neither do Black's passive Bishops. Do you know what does have value? The dark squares around the black King, the d-file, and of course our active Queen. }
10... dxc4 11. Nc3 { Development first. } 11... Be7 12. Rd1 Bd7 13. Ne4
{ Black can't castle short:  13...O-O  14.Neg5!  and there is no good defense  against Qf4-h4 since  14...f6  runs into  15.Nxe6  . }
13... Qc7 14. Bd2
{ However, castling long is hardly better.  14...O-O-O  15.Nd6+  already gives White a winning advantage. Also, @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/ppqbbpp1/2n1p1p1/4P3/2p1NQ2/5N2/PP1B1PPP/R2R2K1 b kq - 7 14@@EndFEN@@  14....f5  doesn't work.  15.exf6  Qxf4  16.fxg7!  and White is a Pawn up in a better position. }
