{ A bit unusual as normally we don't want to develop the Queen that early. However, the Queen will be quite comfortable on the Kingside while the Knight is better placed on f3, from where it protects the key e5-Pawn. }
5... Nc6 6. Qf4 e6
{ Anyway, Black had no chance of activating the light-squared Bishop. } 7. Bd3
Nb4
{ Black wants to trade the Queen's Knight and only then bring another one to g6. }
8. Bd2
{ This strong idea has not yet been played in classical chess. In order to understand White's point we should see the 'normal' variation first:  8.O-O  Nxd3  9.cxd3  Ne7  10.Nc3  Ng6  11.Qg3  Be7  and Black  has prevented h2-h4. One could argue that instead of developing the Knight,  White can start with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2nppp/4p3/3pP3/5Q2/3P1N2/PP3PPP/RNB2RK1 w kq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.h4  . However, it seems that  10...Nf5  is strong then. }
8... Nxd3+ 9. cxd3 Ne7 10. Nc3
{ Perhaps there is no difference but I would not hurry with h2-h4. It just looks more natural to develop the Knight first. }
10... Ng6 11. Qg3 Bd7
{ For the time being, Black refrains from touching the dark-squared Bishop. }
12. h4 h5 13. Ne2 { Once again, the Knight is heading to f4. } 13... Qb6
{ This is the only way for Black to get reasonable counterplay. } 14. Bc3
{ Black was ready to meet  14.O-O  with  14...Qb5!  targeting  the d3-Pawn.  @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp1b1pp1/1q2p1n1/3pP2p/7P/3P1NQ1/PP1BNPP1/R3K2R w KQkq - 2 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Nf4?!  would blunder  14...Nxe5!  15.Nxe5  Qxb2  . }
14... Be7
{ 14...Qb5?!  15.Ng5!  only helps White. At this point, I would like to share one insight with you: as a Chessable author, from now on I promise to stay away from the openings that have been covered by Erwin L'Ami. He's given me a lot of headaches with his Cozio Defense but it was nothing compared to his Caro-Kann Lifetime Repertoire!  Initially, I thought that @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/pp1bbpp1/1q2p1n1/3pP2p/7P/2BP1NQ1/PP2NPP1/R3K2R w KQkq - 4 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Nf4  is the move, only to discover his solution for Black:  15...Nxf4!  @@StartBracket@@instead of  15...Rh6  recommended by the engines@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/pp1bbpp1/1q2p3/3pP2p/5n1P/2BP1NQ1/PP3PP1/R3K2R w KQkq - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Qxf4  Rh6!  17.Ng5  f6  18.exf6  Rxf6!  19.Bxf6  gxf6  20.Nf3  e5  , with very practical compensation for the exchange. I tried to challenge it but I quickly realized that even if we achieve an objective advantage, it will still be a difficult position to handle. Kudos to Erwin for his idea and another short sleep for me... }
15. a3
{ The point of this innocent @@StartBracket@@but generally useful@@EndBracket@@ move is, brutally speaking, to give the move to Black. It appears that Black doesn't have too many options that don't worsen the position.   For example,  15...Bb5  doesn't achieve anything, White can just play  16.Rd1  . Another idea is that  now we really are threatening Nf3-g5. Do you remember how the 15.Ng5 line ended? The black Queen gave a check on b4 − clearly, this won't be happening anymore. }
15... Rc8
{ The best move, although Black can now forget about castling long, which also means that Black can forget about Erwin's exchange sacrifice! }
16. Nf4 Nxf4 17. Qxf4 Bb5 { Targeting our d3-Pawn. } 18. Qd2 Qa6
{ Otherwise, we would have castled, with a nice positional advantage. } 19. Ke2
{ White's King is completely safe in the center. We are threatening a4! which, if Black allows it, will deprive the light-squared Bishop of any activity. For example,  19...O-O  20.a4  Be8  21.Rh3  starts a dangerous attack on Black's King. }
