[White "42. Caro-Kann 3.e5 − 3rd Move Alternatives"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 3.e5 Na6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The name Caro-Kann Defense comes from two players, Horatio Caro and Marcus Kann, who analyzed this opening in 1886. Its strategic idea is both sound and simple: Black wants to put the Pawn on d5, just like in the French, but without depriving the light-squared Bishop of its future on the h3-c8 diagonal.  I consider it a third @@StartBracket@@next to the Sicilian Defense and 1.e4 e5@@EndBracket@@ great @@StartBracket@@and bulletproof@@EndBracket@@ defense against 1.e4 − something that can be successfully used for a very long time. It is also strategically rich, as White can aim for both open and closed positions. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ The Advance Variation has always been considered critical against the Caro-Kann. After all, grabbing space in the center can't be a bad strategy. }
3... Na6
{ This move is just ridiculous but even some grandmasters played it in the past so I guess we can't ignore it... }
4. Nd2
{ Black's trick was  4.Bxa6  Qa5+  , which is not a total disaster for White, but of course, we have no reason to give our opponents the Bishop pair that easily. }
4... Nc7
{ Hardly a square for the Knight. It sort of anticipates c2-c4 but this is just one of White's plans. We can choose a different plan to make that Knight look stupid. }
5. Bd3 g6
{ Black is preparing ...Bc8-f5. Even the 3...g6 line looks good compared to this one. }
6. c3 Nh6 7. Ndf3 Bf5 8. Ne2
{ 8.Bxh6  Bxh6  9.Bxf5  would also be much better for White. } 8... Bxd3 9.
Qxd3 Nf5 10. O-O
{ White has a big advantage. We have more space and superior development. We are going to attack the side where Black puts the king, with a2-a4 and b2-b4-b5 or g2-g4. }
