[Black "Caro-Kann 3.e5 g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The name Caro-Kann Defense comes from two players, Horatio Caro and Marcus Kann, who analyzed this opening in 1886. Its strategic idea is both sound and simple: Black wants to put the Pawn on d5, just like in the French, but without depriving the light-squared Bishop of its future on the h3-c8 diagonal.  I consider it a third @@StartBracket@@next to the Sicilian Defense and 1.e4 e5@@EndBracket@@ great @@StartBracket@@and bulletproof@@EndBracket@@ defense against 1.e4 − something that can be successfully used for a very long time. It is also strategically rich, as White can aim for both open and closed positions. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ The Advance Variation has always been considered critical against the Caro-Kann. After all, grabbing space in the center can't be a bad strategy. }
3... g6
{ Some players just like to use this setup. It is usually connected with the following strategy: put as many Pawns as possible on the light squares, get rid of the light-squared Bishop, and complete the checkers setup with ...e7-e6. The other follow-up is to develop the Knight to h6 and try to undermine our Pawn center with ...f7-f6. }
4. Nf3 { I see no reason not to play this natural move. } 4... Nh6
{ This is the ...f7-f6 plan being badly excecuted. It is better to start with ...Bf8-g7 and ...f7-f6 because then Black can take on e5 and develop the Knight to f6. }
5. Bf4 { Anticipating Black's next move. } 5... f6 6. Bd3
{ We are not worried about  6...g5  7.Bg3  . } 6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O
{ Black has no time to develop with  7...Bg4  due to  8.exf6  exf6  9.Re1+  and castling rights are lost for this game. }
8. h3
{ White has full control over the e5-square. Our next move should be Rf1-e1. }
