1. e4 c6
{ The name Caro-Kann Defense comes from two players, Horatio Caro and Marcus Kann, who analyzed this opening in 1886. Its strategic idea is both sound and simple: Black wants to put the Pawn on d5, just like in the French, but without depriving the light-squared Bishop of its future on the h3-c8 diagonal.  I consider it a third @@StartBracket@@next to the Sicilian Defense and 1.e4 e5@@EndBracket@@ great @@StartBracket@@and bulletproof@@EndBracket@@ defense against 1.e4 − something that can be successfully used for a very long time. It is also strategically rich, as White can aim for both open and closed positions. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ The Advance Variation has always been considered critical against the Caro-Kann. After all, grabbing space in the center can't be a bad strategy. }
3... g6
{ Some players just like to use this setup. It is usually connected with the following strategy: put as many Pawns as possible on the light squares, get rid of the light-squared Bishop, and complete the checkers setup with ...e7-e6. The other follow-up is to develop the Knight to h6 and try to undermine our Pawn center with ...f7-f6. }
4. Nf3 { I see no reason not to play this natural move. } 4... Bg7
{ Black is preparing ...f7-f6. } 5. Bd3
{ We can ignore  5...Bg4  as there is the simple  6.Nbd2  followed by h2-h3. }
5... f6 6. O-O fxe5 7. Nxe5
{ The main thing to remember about this unusual Pawn structure is that we should not try to improve our center with c2-c3, but rather undermine Black's with c2-c4. }
7... Nd7 8. Nf3
{ It seems that Black has one Knight too many, we should not make their life easier. }
8... Nh6 9. Re1 Nf7
{ Or  9...O-O  10.Bg5  Nf6  11.Nbd2  Nf7  12.Bh4  with a big advantage. } 10.
c4
{ As mentioned, apart from creating a target on d5 @@StartBracket@@which will sooner or later force Black to move the Pawn to e6@@EndBracket@@, White's last move has one more benefit: we can now comfortably develop the Queen's Knight to c3. }
10... O-O 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Nc3 Nb8
{ Logical. Black doesn't want both Knights on the f-file. After  12...Nf6  13.h3  , it would already be difficult to find a sensible move. }
13. h3 { ...Bc8-g4 had to be prevented. } 13... Nc6 14. Bc2
{ White has a clear advantage. The Pawn on d4 is now defended. After  14...e6  @@StartBracket@@I can't really imagine Black doing anything else@@EndBracket@@,  we can bring the Bishop to f4. In the long run, we might want to start the Kingside attack with h4-h5. }
