{ The Advance Variation has always been considered critical against the Caro-Kann. After all, grabbing space in the center can't be a bad strategy. }
3... g6
{ Some players just like to use this setup. It is usually connected with the following strategy: put as many Pawns as possible on the light squares, get rid of the light-squared Bishop, and complete the checkers setup with ...e7-e6. The other follow-up is to develop the Knight to h6 and try to undermine our Pawn center with ...f7-f6. }
4. Nf3 { I see no reason not to play this natural move. } 4... Bg4
{ So, the checkers setup. } 5. Nbd2
{ The Knight on b1 is often kind of a problem in the Advance Variation so it's good to have that sorted. }
5... e6 6. h3
{ Forcing the exchange will give White a free hand in developing the rest of the pieces. }
6... Bxf3 7. Nxf3 c5
{ At least Black can develop the Knight to c6 now.  7...Nd7  8.Bd3  c5  9.c3  would be so much better for White. }
8. Bb5+ { Which is why we won't settle for c2-c3. } 8... Nc6 9. O-O
{ In the spirit of the Caro-Kann, White wants to open up the position with c2-c4. This plan is especially sound with the Bishop pair and Black's ridiculous Pawn on g6. }
9... cxd4 { 9...Qb6  10.c4!  dxc4  11.Qa4  would give White a huge advantage. }
10. Nxd4 Rc8 11. Ba4
{ This is a hard one, but to make you feel better, almost any move is fine, this one simply is the best. The point is that we want to play c2-c4 and if Black then takes the Pawn, we want to be able to take Nd4xc6 and after ...b7xc6*, our Bishop won't be under attack. The other idea is to bring the Knight to b5. }
11... Bg7 12. Nb5 { Threatening both Nb5-d6 and Nb5xa7. } 12... Bxe5 13. Nxa7
Rc7 14. Re1 { Now Black cannot avoid material losses. } 14... Bg7 15. Bf4
{ White has a winning advantage. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "42. Caro-Kann 3.e5 − 3rd Move Alternatives"]
[Black "Caro-Kann 3.e5 g6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The name Caro-Kann Defense comes from two players, Horatio Caro and Marcus Kann, who analyzed this opening in 1886. Its strategic idea is both sound and simple: Black wants to put the Pawn on d5, just like in the French, but without depriving the light-squared Bishop of its future on the h3-c8 diagonal.  I consider it a third @@StartBracket@@next to the Sicilian Defense and 1.e4 e5@@EndBracket@@ great @@StartBracket@@and bulletproof@@EndBracket@@ defense against 1.e4 − something that can be successfully used for a very long time. It is also strategically rich, as White can aim for both open and closed positions. }
2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ The Advance Variation has always been considered critical against the Caro-Kann. After all, grabbing space in the center can't be a bad strategy. }
3... g6
{ Some players just like to use this setup. It is usually connected with the following strategy: put as many Pawns as possible on the light squares, get rid of the light-squared Bishop, and complete the checkers setup with ...e7-e6. The other follow-up is to develop the Knight to h6 and try to undermine our Pawn center with ...f7-f6. }
4. Nf3 { I see no reason not to play this natural move. } 4... Bg4
{ So, the checkers setup. } 5. Nbd2
{ The Knight on b1 is often kind of a problem in the Advance Variation so it's good to have that sorted. }
5... e6 6. h3
{ Forcing the exchange will give White a free hand in developing the rest of the pieces. }
6... Bxf3 7. Nxf3 c5
{ At least Black can develop the Knight to c6 now.  7...Nd7  8.Bd3  c5  9.c3  would be so much better for White. }
8. Bb5+ { Which is why we won't settle for c2-c3. } 8... Nc6 9. O-O
{ In the spirit of the Caro-Kann, White wants to open up the position with c2-c4. This plan is especially sound with the Bishop pair and Black's ridiculous Pawn on g6. }
9... cxd4 { 9...Qb6  10.c4!  dxc4  11.Qa4  would give White a huge advantage. }
10. Nxd4 Rc8 11. Ba4
{ This is a hard one, but to make you feel better, almost any move is fine, this one simply is the best. The point is that we want to play c2-c4 and if Black then takes the Pawn, we want to be able to take Nd4xc6 and after ...b7xc6*, our Bishop won't be under attack. The other idea is to bring the Knight to b5. }
11... Bc5
{ With the Pawn on g6, this is not the right square for the Bishop. However, you saw the alternative, Black doesn't really have a choice. }
12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13. c3
{ White has a big advantage.  13...Ne7  14.Bg5  is unlivable, which means Black is forced to retreat the Bishop to its starting position. We can then play b2-b4 and develop the Bishop to e3, achieving complete domination on the dark squares. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "43. Scandinavian Defense 2.exd5 Qxd5 3.Nc3 Qa5"]
[Black "Scandinavian 3.Nc3 Qa5 4.d4 Bf5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian Defense is on the same level as the Alekhine Defense − it is not a good opening, objectively, but it does require some knowledge from us. For this reason, it is quite popular in rapid and blitz chess as the opening accuracy of even strong players is not that impressive in shorter time controls. }
2. exd5 Qxd5
{ Unlike other openings, Black begins development with the Queen. We know it's not a good strategy in general, but we still have to prove it wrong. }
3. Nc3
{ For many years  3...Qa5  was played rather automatically, but today it's just one of the options. }
3... Qa5
{ The Queen is well placed on a5 but in many lines, White can challenge her position with Bc1-d2 or b2-b4. }
4. d4 Bf5 { 4...c6  5.Nf3  Bf5  6.Bd2  transposes. } 5. Nf3 c6 6. Bd2 e6
{ Black sometimes uses this move order, trying to avoid the Nc3-d5 lines.  6...Nf6  would transpose. }
7. Bc4 Nd7 8. d5 { Breaking through Black's defenses. } 8... cxd5 9. Nxd5 Qc5
10. Qe2 Rc8 11. Bb3
{ Black is in real trouble. We want to move the Bishop to c3 and then castle long. }
11... Ngf6 12. Nxf6+ gxf6 13. Bc3 { As promised... } 13... Rg8 14. O-O-O Rxg2
{ I think it makes sense to see this line as during the game we tend to worry. }
15. Nd4 Bg4 16. Qf1 Bxd1 17. Qxg2
{ We will take the Pawn on b7 on the next move. White is much better. } *

