[Black "Scandinavian 3.Nc3 Qa5 4.d4 Bf5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian Defense is on the same level as the Alekhine Defense − it is not a good opening, objectively, but it does require some knowledge from us. For this reason, it is quite popular in rapid and blitz chess as the opening accuracy of even strong players is not that impressive in shorter time controls. }
2. exd5 Qxd5
{ Unlike other openings, Black begins development with the Queen. We know it's not a good strategy in general, but we still have to prove it wrong. }
3. Nc3
{ For many years  3...Qa5  was played rather automatically, but today it's just one of the options. }
3... Qa5
{ The Queen is well placed on a5 but in many lines, White can challenge her position with Bc1-d2 or b2-b4. }
4. d4 Bf5 { 4...c6  5.Nf3  Bf5  6.Bd2  transposes. } 5. Nf3 c6 6. Bd2 e6
{ Black sometimes uses this move order, trying to avoid the Nc3-d5 lines.  6...Nf6  would transpose. }
7. Bc4 Qc7 { 7...Nf6  would also transpose. } 8. Nh4
{ We will take the Bishop pair. } 8... Bg6 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qf3 Nf6
{ 10...Rxh2?!  11.Rxh2  Qxh2  12.O-O-O  would give White too much compensation. After  12...Nf6  , we will go  13.g4  and then g4-g5. }
11. O-O-O
{ With the h-file open for the black Rook, White prefers to castle long. }
11... Nbd7 12. h4 { Securing our Pawn but also fixing Black's Pawn structure. }
12... O-O-O 13. Bg5
{ White is clearly better. We want to retreat the Bishop to b3, move the King to b1, and then perhaps remove the Knight from c3 and play c2-c3. }
