9. O-O-O Nbd7 10. Bd3
{ Sometimes the simplest means the best. Quite often actually. } 10... Bxd3 11.
Qxd3 Rd8 12. Qg3
{ This is not that simple but it's important. White needs to be ready to sacrifice the central Pawn. }
12... Qxd4 { Otherwise, White would be clearly better without any effort. } 13.
Nxd7 Qxd7 14. Rhe1 { Black can't move the Bishop and we want to go Bd2-g5. }
14... Qc8 15. Bg5 Be7 16. Rxd8+ { Finally, Black has a choice. } 16... Bxd8
{ Black wants to recapture with the Bishop. } 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Ne4 Kf8
{ 18...Qd8  19.Nxf6+  Qxf6  20.Qb8+  . } 19. Qf4 Be7 20. Nd6 Bxd6 21. Qxd6+ Ke8
22. Re3
{ White is better and doesn't need to worry about the Pawn. We will most likely win it back with Qd6-d4, attacking g7 and a7. We could do it now but anyway Black has no moves and  22...a6?!  would only weaken the position.  23.Rb3!  followed by Qd6-b4 and Black will have to push the b-Pawn, creating another target − the c6-Pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "43. Scandinavian Defense 2.exd5 Qxd5 3.Nc3 Qa5"]
[Black "Scandinavian 3.Nc3 Qa5 4.d4 Nf6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian Defense is on the same level as the Alekhine Defense − it is not a good opening, objectively, but it does require some knowledge from us. For this reason, it is quite popular in rapid and blitz chess as the opening accuracy of even strong players is not that impressive in shorter time controls. }
2. exd5 Qxd5
{ Unlike other openings, Black begins development with the Queen. We know it's not a good strategy in general, but we still have to prove it wrong. }
3. Nc3
{ For many years  3...Qa5  was played rather automatically, but today it's just one of the options. }
3... Qa5
{ The Queen is well placed on a5 but in many lines, White can challenge her position with Bc1-d2 or b2-b4. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 { 5...c6  6.Bd2  Bf5  transposes. } 6. Bd2
{ White can also start with  6.Bc4  , but I don't find any difference. Another possibility would be  6.Ne5  . }
6... c6 7. Bc4 Nbd7
{ Aimed against Nc3-d5, allowing Black to recapture on f6 with the Knight. However, it is not without a downside. }
8. Qe2 { Threatening Nc3-b5-d6+! } 8... e6
{ This is practically a losing mistake! } 9. d5 cxd5 10. Nxd5 Qc5 11. b4 Qc8
{ So much for the Scandinavian Queen. } 12. Nxf6+ gxf6
{ 12...Nxf6  13.Bb5+  and Black's King is invited for an unhealthy walk with  13...Ke7  since  13...Nd7  would be met by  14.Ne5  . }
13. Nd4 Bg6 14. h4 { Black's problems just never end. } 14... h5 15. f4 Be7 16.
O-O-O Qc7 17. Rhe1 { White is threatening f4-f5. } 17... Qb6
{ 17...O-O-O  18.Nb5  and Black can resign. } 18. Bc3
{ Black is lost. After  18...O-O-O  19.Nb5  , Black  won't be able to save the a7-Pawn  while @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/pp1nbp2/1q2ppb1/7p/1PBN1P1P/2B5/P1P1Q1P1/2KRR3 b kq - 6 18@@EndFEN@@  18...Bxb4  19.Bxb4  Qxb4  20.Nxe6!  is even faster. }
*

