[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "43. Scandinavian Defense 2.exd5 Qxd5 3.Nc3 Qa5"]
[Black "Scandinavian 3.Nc3 Qa5 4.d4 Nf6 #18"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian Defense is on the same level as the Alekhine Defense − it is not a good opening, objectively, but it does require some knowledge from us. For this reason, it is quite popular in rapid and blitz chess as the opening accuracy of even strong players is not that impressive in shorter time controls. }
2. exd5 Qxd5
{ Unlike other openings, Black begins development with the Queen. We know it's not a good strategy in general, but we still have to prove it wrong. }
3. Nc3
{ For many years  3...Qa5  was played rather automatically, but today it's just one of the options. }
3... Qa5
{ The Queen is well placed on a5 but in many lines, White can challenge her position with Bc1-d2 or b2-b4. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 { 5...c6  6.Bd2  Bf5  transposes. } 6. Bd2
{ White can also start with  6.Bc4  , but I don't find any difference. Another possibility would be  6.Ne5  . }
6... c6 7. Bc4 e6 { The main position of the line. } 8. Nd5
{ This is the most popular and probably the best move. In general, we are happy to get rid of the c3-Knight. }
8... Qd8 9. Nxf6+ Qxf6 { This is more serious than  9...gxf6  . } 10. Qe2 Bg4
{ Black is about to damage our Pawn structure. } 11. d5
{ Without this, Black would be just fine. } 11... Bxf3 12. gxf3 cxd5 13. Bxd5
{ Our strong Bishop pair gives us more than enough compensation for the broken Pawn structure. }
13... Nd7 14. O-O-O O-O-O 15. Be4 Qe5
{ The most popular move, although it's not too strong. The Queen is coming back to the Queenside. }
16. Bc3 Qc7 17. Kb1 f6 { Black wants to be able to develop the Bishop. } 18.
Rhg1 { Black will have to wait for it. } 18... Nc5 19. Rxd8+ Qxd8 20. h4
{ We want to push the h-Pawn as far as possible. Black will most likely stop it with ...h7-h6 or ...h6-h5, but then the g7-Pawn will become a permanent weakness. }
*

