[Black "Scandinavian 3.Nc3 Qd6 − 5.Nf3 Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian Defense is on the same level as the Alekhine Defense − it is not a good opening, objectively, but it does require some knowledge from us. For this reason, it is quite popular in rapid and blitz chess as the opening accuracy of even strong players is not that impressive in shorter time controls. }
2. exd5 Qxd5
{ Unlike other openings, Black begins development with the Queen. We know it's not a good strategy in general but we still have to prove it wrong. }
3. Nc3
{ For many years  3...Qa5  was played rather automatically, but today it's just one of the options. }
3... Qd6
{ Quite a popular continuation, mostly because Black's problem after  3...Qa5  became apparent.  3...Qd6  can be combined with many setups: the light-squared Bishop may be fianchettoed or developed to g4 @@StartBracket@@sometimes f5@@EndBracket@@. The dark-squared Bishop may be fianchettoed as well.  The Queen is less exposed on d6, although it can still be attacked. For instance, if White fianchettoes the light-squared Bishop, then the black Queen can be chased away with Bc1-f4. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bg4 { One of the simplest lines. } 6. h3 Bh5 7. g4 Bg6 8. Bg2
{ White is ready to go Nf3-e5, which explains Black's next move. } 8... Nbd7 9.
g5 { This is simple and effective. } 9... Ne4
{ It looks healthy but breaking our Pawns won't help Black. } 10. O-O Nxc3 11.
bxc3 Be4 { 11...e6  12.Nh4  . } 12. c4
{ White is much better @@StartBracket@@or winning if you ask the engines@@EndBracket@@. After  12...e6  13.Re1  , Black won't be able to  stop d4-d5. }
*

