[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "44. Scandinavian Defense 2.exd5 Qxd5 3.Nc3 Qd8/Qd6"]
[Black "Scandinavian 3.Nc3 Qd6 − 5.Nf3 a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian Defense is on the same level as the Alekhine Defense − it is not a good opening, objectively, but it does require some knowledge from us. For this reason, it is quite popular in rapid and blitz chess as the opening accuracy of even strong players is not that impressive in shorter time controls. }
2. exd5 Qxd5
{ Unlike other openings, Black begins development with the Queen. We know it's not a good strategy in general but we still have to prove it wrong. }
3. Nc3
{ For many years  3...Qa5  was played rather automatically, but today it's just one of the options. }
3... Qd6
{ Quite a popular continuation, mostly because Black's problem after  3...Qa5  became apparent.  3...Qd6  can be combined with many setups: the light-squared Bishop may be fianchettoed or developed to g4 @@StartBracket@@sometimes f5@@EndBracket@@. The dark-squared Bishop may be fianchettoed as well.  The Queen is less exposed on d6, although it can still be attacked. For instance, if White fianchettoes the light-squared Bishop, then the black Queen can be chased away with Bc1-f4. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 a6
{ The most popular move in the position, although White is doing really well here. }
6. g3 b5
{ It is really dangerous to fianchetto the Bishop right now as Black will face some immediate pressure. }
7. Bf4 Qd8
{ The best move objectively, but then why didn't Black retreat the Queen to d8 right away? }
8. Bg2 Bb7 9. O-O e6
{ This is what pretty much everybody does.  9...b4  10.Na4  e6  11.Nc5  , while @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/1bp1pppp/p4n2/8/Np1P1B2/5NP1/PPP2PBP/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nbd7  11.c4  would be easily better for White. }
10. d5
{ The simple  10.Ne5  would be nice but this breakthrough gives White a winning advantage. }
10... Bxd5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5
{ At first, I thought that Black's position can't be that bad. After all, there is no clear way to break the defense. }
12. Be5
{ This cheeky move is the key. The Bishop successfully prevents Black from completing development. }
12... Nd7 13. a4 c6 14. Qe2
{ Black can never take on e5 as the Queenside would become too weak. We can bring the f-Rook to d1 and slowly improve with something like h2-h4 and Bg2-h3. We need to handle this carefully but if we do, then Black won't manage to solve all the problems in this position. }
