{ As the title gives it away, the Alekhine Defense was introduced in 1921 by the former World Champion, Alexander Alekhine. This opening hasn't been very popular at the top level, but the boom of online chess brought it back to the limelight, together with other dubious lines.  The basic idea of developing the Knight to f6 straight away is to provoke White to advance the Pawn to the fifth ranks as early as move two and then challenge White's Pawn center. In a way, Black employs a similar strategy as in the Grünfeld Defense, but here, it is actually incorrect. }
2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6
{ There are many moves here, such as  4.Nf3  , but we will go  4.c4  . } 4. c4
Nb6 5. f4
{ While there are other good lines, this is clearly the most ambitious continuation. White simply grabs as much space as possible. }
5... g6
{ The second most popular move. After fianchettoing the Bishop and castling, Black will want to undermine our pawn center with ...c7-c5. }
6. Nc3 Bg7
{ Quite an important position − it is easy to lose one's attention and simply go  7.Nf3?!  but after  7...dxe5  8.fxe5  c5!  Black is fine. }
7. Be3 Be6 { Grünfeld style − luring our pawns into Black's territory. } 8. d5
Bc8 { 8...Bf5  9.Nf3  and the Bishop is hardly helpful on f5. } 9. Nf3 c6
{ Such a move can't be challenging but, truth to be told, there are no good options for Black. }
10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O Bg4 12. e6 { A typical idea. } 12... fxe6 13. Ng5
{ After  13...Bxe2  14.Qxe2  , Black will lose an exchange, or worse. } 13...
Nxc4 14. Bc1 { Surprisingly, it is the only good move here. } 14... Bxe2
{ 14...Bf5  15.g4  . } 15. Qxe2 exd5 16. Qe6+ Kh8 17. Qh3 h5
{ 17...h6  18.Ne6  Qc8  19.f5  would only make it easier for us. I guess it is clear now why we had to retreat our Bishop  to c1 instead of f2. }
18. Ne6 Qc8 19. f5
{ Our plan is not to take on g6 but to bring another Knight to f4. Black should not survive this one. }
*

