1. e4 Nf6
{ As the title gives it away, the Alekhine Defense was introduced in 1921 by the former World Champion, Alexander Alekhine. This opening hasn't been very popular at the top level, but the boom of online chess brought it back to the limelight, together with other dubious lines.  The basic idea of developing the Knight to f6 straight away is to provoke White to advance the Pawn to the fifth ranks as early as move two and then challenge White's Pawn center. In a way, Black employs a similar strategy as in the Grünfeld Defense, but here, it is actually incorrect. }
2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6
{ There are many moves here, such as  4.Nf3  , but we will go  4.c4  . } 4. c4
Nb6 5. f4
{ While there are other good lines, this is clearly the most ambitious continuation. White simply grabs as much space as possible. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5 c5
{ Black is putting pressure on the d4-Pawn, however, it is not supported by pressure on the e5-Pawn.   6...g6  7.Nc3  transposes to the line we've examinedhere. }
7. d5 g6 8. Nc3 Bg7 9. Bf4 O-O 10. Qd2 e6 11. d6
{ 11.O-O-O  is fine, but some lines are complicated while our choice is simpler and equally strong. }
11... Nc6 12. Nf3 Nd7 { Playing against our e5-Pawn is Black's only plan. } 13.
Qe3 f6
{ If Black tries to confuse us with  13...Nd4  , then we should simply ignore it and play  14.O-O-O  with great advantage. }
14. O-O-O { Once again, we are not taking that Pawn. } 14... Ndxe5 15. Nxe5
Nxe5 { 15...fxe5  16.Bg5  . } 16. Bxe5 fxe5 17. h4 Bd7 18. h5
{ We will take on g6 on the next move. If Black recaptures, then Bf1-d3 should do the job. If Black tries ...h7-h6, then we will go Bf1-e2-f3, ensuring our control over the e4-square. White's advantage is overwhelming. }
