1. e4 Nf6
{ As the title gives it away, the Alekhine Defense was introduced in 1921 by the former World Champion, Alexander Alekhine. This opening hasn't been very popular at the top level, but the boom of online chess brought it back to the limelight, together with other dubious lines.  The basic idea of developing the Knight to f6 straight away is to provoke White to advance the Pawn to the fifth ranks as early as move two and then challenge White's Pawn center. In a way, Black employs a similar strategy as in the Grünfeld Defense, but here, it is actually incorrect. }
2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6
{ There are many moves here, such as  4.Nf3  , but we will go  4.c4  . } 4. c4
Nb6 5. f4
{ While there are other good lines, this is clearly the most ambitious continuation. White simply grabs as much space as possible. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5 Nc6 { The main move. } 7. Be3 Bf5
{ Basically, the only move. } 8. Nc3 Qd7
{ This may be connected with castling long or simply ...Ra8-d8. } 9. Nf3 e6 10.
Be2 Bg4 { Black is trying to put pressure on the d4-Pawn. } 11. O-O Rd8 12. b3
{ We don't need to worry. If Black wins our d4-Pawn, it is going to cost the b7-Pawn. }
12... Be7 13. Qe1 Bxf3 { Otherwise, the Rook would come to d1. } 14. Bxf3 Nxd4
15. Bxb7 c6
{ 15...Nc2??  16.Qf2  and Black is losing a piece. The more subtle @@StartFEN@@3rk2r/pBpqbppp/1n2p3/4P3/2Pn4/1PN1B3/P5PP/R3QRK1 b k - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Bb4  ,  planning ...Bxc3 and ...Ne2+, can be met with the cool-headed  16.Kh1  and after  16...Nc2  17.Qf2  Nxe3  18.Bc6!  , Black cannot avoid material losses. }
16. Rd1 Qxb7 17. Rxd4 Rxd4 18. Bxd4
{ The material is equal, but the position is not. } 18... c5 19. Be3
{ After  19...O-O  , we will go  20.Qg3  practically forcing  20...Kh8  , and then we can play  21.Rd1  .  White is clearly better. Black's weak c5-Pawn is a bigger problem than our e5-Pawn is for us. Most of the endings should be also clearly better, so keep the Qg3-f3 idea in mind. }
