1. e4 Nf6
{ As the title gives it away, the Alekhine Defense was introduced in 1921 by the former World Champion, Alexander Alekhine. This opening hasn't been very popular at the top level, but the boom of online chess brought it back to the limelight, together with other dubious lines.  The basic idea of developing the Knight to f6 straight away is to provoke White to advance the Pawn to the fifth ranks as early as move two and then challenge White's Pawn center. In a way, Black employs a similar strategy as in the Grünfeld Defense, but here, it is actually incorrect. }
2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6
{ There are many moves here, such as  4.Nf3  , but we will go  4.c4  . } 4. c4
Nb6 5. f4
{ While there are other good lines, this is clearly the most ambitious continuation. White simply grabs as much space as possible. }
5... dxe5 6. fxe5 Nc6 { The main move. } 7. Be3 Bf5
{ Basically, the only move. } 8. Nc3 e6 { The main move. } 9. Nf3 Be7
{ 9...Qd7  transposes to the 8...Qd7 move order. } 10. Be2 O-O
{ 10...f6  11.O-O  O-O  transposes. } 11. O-O f6
{ The only sensible plan for Black. } 12. exf6 Bxf6
{ Black has a bad Pawn structure, but there is some pressure on the d4-Pawn. }
13. Qd2 Qe7 14. Rad1 Rad8 15. Kh1
{ 15.Qc1  is more popular but not that strong as it allows  15...e5  16.d5  Nd4!  After  17.Nxd4  exd4  18.Bxd4  Bg5  19.Qa1  Na4!  Black has good compensation for the pawn. }
15... h6 16. h3
{ 16.Bg1  Bg4!  With the Bishop on g1, the same idea wouldn't be that effective. }
16... Rd7 17. Qc1
{ We prevented ...Bf5-g4 and secured the King, so there are no more tricks. Finally, we can remove the Queen from the d-file. Our plan is to go d4-d5 @@StartBracket@@even on the next move!@@EndBracket@@, but we can also improve our position with Be3-g1 and b2-b3. White is clearly better. }
*

