[Black "Nimzowitsch Defense 1.e4 Nc6 2.Nf3 Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ I used to think that  1...Nc6  is very weak, but it turns out that  2.d4  d5!  is quite playable for Black. }
2. Nf3
{ On the other hand, there is no way for Black to take advantage of this move order. }
2... Nf6
{ 2...e5  3.Bb5  Welcome to the Ruy Lopez, which we've examined thoroughly in Part  1. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. d4 d6
{ Black transposes to the Alekhine Defense − we don't normally go for this line, but normally Black doesn't play ...Nb8-c6 in the Alekhine. }
5. c4 Nb6 6. Nc3 { There was no need for e5-e6. } 6... Bg4 7. exd6 cxd6 8. d5
Ne5 9. c5 { Typical idea. } 9... Bxf3
{ Obviously, the c5-Pawn is taboo:  9...dxc5?  10.Nxe5  Bxd1  11.Bb5+  and White is winning. }
10. gxf3 dxc5 11. Bf4 Qd6 12. Bb5+ Kd8 13. O-O
{ White is much better while Black still has to develop some pieces and the King is really weak. }
