[White "48. Owen Defense 1.e4 b6"]
[Black "Owen Defense 1.e4 b6 2.d4 e6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ One of the moves that has gained a lot of popularity in recent years. Twenty years ago, we rarely saw a serious player playing such an opening. Today, we have plenty of them. One of the reasons behind this growth is a boom in online chess where you can allow yourself much more than you would have allowed in a classical OTB tournament.  Another reason is the engines. According to them, this is not such a bad move, after all, only a bit bad. :-@@EndBracket@@ Despite all that, this is not the correct way of handling the opening and, as White players, we should take advantage of it. }
2. d4 e6 3. Nf3 d5
{ Without too much effort, we can just take on d5.  3...Bb7  4.Bd3  transposes to the 2...Bb7 move order. }
4. exd5
{ 4.e5  Qd7  5.Bd3?!  I only put this line to show the idea behind this specific move order.  Black delayed ...Bb7, hoping to exchange the light-squared Bishops without losing a tempo. This cat and mouse game is not difficult for White who has many useful moves @@StartBracket@@such as c2-c3 or h2-h4@@EndBracket@@ before moving the Bishop to d3.    5...Ba6  −  the idea of exchanging the Bishops is of course sensible since Black, having put the central Pawns on e6 and d5, in a way stifled most of the potential of the light-squared Bishop. }
4... Qxd5
{ It's a bad version of Scandinavian Defense @@StartBracket@@is there a good one?@@EndBracket@@. }
5. c4 Qd8 6. Nc3 { We can just develop our pieces to their natural positions. }
*

