2. d4 e6 3. Nf3 d5
{ Without too much effort, we can just take on d5.  3...Bb7  4.Bd3  transposes to the 2...Bb7 move order. }
4. exd5
{ 4.e5  Qd7  5.Bd3?!  I only put this line to show the idea behind this specific move order.  Black delayed ...Bb7, hoping to exchange the light-squared Bishops without losing a tempo. This cat and mouse game is not difficult for White who has many useful moves @@StartBracket@@such as c2-c3 or h2-h4@@EndBracket@@ before moving the Bishop to d3.    5...Ba6  −  the idea of exchanging the Bishops is of course sensible since Black, having put the central Pawns on e6 and d5, in a way stifled most of the potential of the light-squared Bishop. }
4... exd5
{ This is almost symmetrical, except White is two tempi up instead of one, plus for Black, ...b7-b6 is not useful at all. }
5. Ne5
{ This natural move is twice as strong here, as we are trying to exploit the weak light squares in Black's camp. }
5... a6 6. Bd3 { The aggressive  6.c4  is also promising. } 6... Nf6 7. O-O Be7
8. Re1 O-O 9. Bf4 { White is a few tempi ahead. } *

