[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ One of the moves that has gained a lot of popularity in recent years. Twenty years ago, we rarely saw a serious player playing such an opening. Today, we have plenty of them. One of the reasons behind this growth is a boom in online chess where you can allow yourself much more than you would have allowed in a classical OTB tournament.  Another reason is the engines. According to them, this is not such a bad move, after all, only a bit bad. :-@@EndBracket@@ Despite all that, this is not the correct way of handling the opening and, as White players, we should take advantage of it. }
2. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3 Nf6 4. Qe2
{ One of the essential things about our setup: we should not develop the b1-Knight too hastily. }
4... e6 5. Nf3 d5 { 5...c5?!  6.d5  would already be huge. } 6. e5 Nfd7 7. c3
c5 8. h4 { A typical plan. } 8... Qc8
{ Black wants to swap the light-squared Bishops. } 9. a4
{ This is how we usually fight against the ...Bb7-a6 plan. After  9...Ba6  , we now have  10.Bb5!  Bxb5  11.axb5  and the  Pawn on b5 paralyzes Black's Queenside effectively. }
9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nc6 11. Nxc6 Bxc6 12. O-O
{ White is clearly better. We want to bring the Knight to f3, and the Bishop to f4. In some cases, we might want to bring the Queen to g4 or h5 first. }
