1. e4 b6
{ One of the moves that has gained a lot of popularity in recent years. Twenty years ago, we rarely saw a serious player playing such an opening. Today, we have plenty of them. One of the reasons behind this growth is a boom in online chess where you can allow yourself much more than you would have allowed in a classical OTB tournament.  Another reason is the engines. According to them, this is not such a bad move, after all, only a bit bad. :-@@EndBracket@@ Despite all that, this is not the correct way of handling the opening and, as White players, we should take advantage of it. }
2. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. c3 { Maintaining our strong Pawn center. }
5... Nf6 6. Qe2 d5 7. e5 Nfd7
{ Instead,  7...Ne4  8.Nbd2  forces Black to exchange on d2 and merely helps us develop. }
8. O-O
{ Here, it is important to grasp the nuances. Although it seems like a usual move order thing, for us, ...Nc6 and ...Be7 are not interchangeable! }
8... Nc6
{ This makes Nb1-a3 weaker as after  9.Na3  a6  ,  our Nf3-e1 maneuver will not be possible as the white Knight has to stay on f3 to protect the Pawn on d4. On the other hand, it allows... }
9. h4 Be7 10. h5 h6 11. Bf4
{ Without h4-h5, this would very often run into ...g7-g5. } 11... cxd4 12. cxd4
Nb4 13. Nc3 { Simple and pleasant. } 13... Nxd3 14. Qxd3 a6
{ 14...O-O  15.Nb5!  Ba6  16.a4  . } 15. Rac1
{ Once Black castles, we can actually try pushing the g2-Pawn. White is slightly better. }
