[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "49. St. George Defense 1.e4 a6"]
[Black "St. George Defense 1.e4 a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 a6
{ The St. George Defense is mostly used for fun since the objective value of this move is not high, as one can expect. }
2. d4 b5
{ 2...e6  3.Bd3  d5  4.Nc3  transposes to the French, which we've examined thoroughly in the relevant chapter. }
3. a4 { White immediately puts pressure on Black's Pawn formation. } 3... Bb7
{ 3...b4  4.Bd3  e6  5.Nd2  Bb7  6.Nb3!?  transposes. } 4. Nd2 bxa4
{ Black hasn't achieved much with this opening strategy. The Pawn structure is broken and White has a great advantage in the center. }
5. Bd3 e6 6. Ngf3 c5 { The only way to challenge our Pawn center. } 7. d5 exd5
8. O-O { Black has huge problems on the e-file. } 8... c4 9. exd5 cxd3 10. Re1+
Be7 11. d6
{ We will win back the piece and take the a4-Pawn after that. The Rook will be very active on the 4th rank and White's advantage is already decisive. }
*

